properties.name: Thallon Silo Mural
properties.description:
The Watering Hole Mural was painted on the Thallon GrainCorp Silos in July 2017, by Artists Joel Fergie (The Zookeeper) and Travis Vinson (Drapl). It depicts icons of the Thallon district using a compilation of images by local photographers. 

These include The Moonie River, Pale Faced Rosellas, the district’s agricultural heritage, and a scarred tree recognizing Thallon’s Indigenous Community, all set against the backdrop of a stunning Western Queensland Sunset. 

Parking, a viewing platform and interpretative sign are located adjacent to the silos just off Thallon’s Campground, which includes showers and toilets. Camping is free unless you require power, which is $5.50 per night.

properties.name: Goondiwindi Art Gallery
properties.description: Appreciate art?  Why not drop into the Goondiwindi Regional Civic Centre Gallery or the Texas Art Gallery. You can view their current exhibition. Entry is free and depending on the exhibition, most pieces are usually available for sale.

properties.name: Cotton Farm Tour
properties.description:
Join us behind the scenes for an unbelievable experience to Goondiwindi Cotton's working cotton farm - "Alcheringa".

Discover the history of cotton production in Australia and the evolution from field to fabric. Along the way, take in the Gunsynd Memorial, Custom's House Museum for morning tea and finish the tour at our very own fashion house.

Please contact us if you plan on bringing any pets as we may be able to help on a case by case basis.

properties.name: Lake Houdraman Campground
properties.description:
"The Lake" - Lake Houdraman Campground is just a short drive (4km) from downtown Quilpie with easy access for conventional vehicles, motorhomes, caravans and touring coaches. Taking pride-of-place on the property is Lake Houdraman, a beautiful expanse of water set amongst shady gum trees.

Swim, fish or ride your pushbike around the lake. Plus, it's a birdwatcher's delight. Luxe it up in their new lakeside Bathhouse. Enjoy a relaxing soak in warm artesian water (additional charge).

There's also a pot belly heater. Learn more about the property on a private 4WD station tour (additional charge and bookings essential), toast marshmallows and stargaze around the campfire. Meet other travellers at the communal bar after 5pm.

properties.name: Eumundi Pottery for the Planet
properties.description:
Visit The Pottery, our ceramic showroom in Eumundi on the Sunshine Coast. Located along Eumundi's main road, just across from the Eumundi Markets, our ceramic showroom has some of our favourite ceramics on display. Shop our unique ceramic pieces not available anywhere else.

Looking for Pottery Classes on the Sunshine Coast? Join the team behind Pottery For The Planet for our Pottery Classes in Eumundi and handbuild a set of ceramics sure to be the talking piece of your home.

Hope to see you soon!

properties.name: Mary Valley Adventure Trails - Guided Horse Riding
properties.description:
Guided Horse Riding Tours through Queensland's rainforest and farmland in the Noosa Hinterland's scenic Mary Valley, on the Sunshine Coast of Queensland, Australia - just north of Brisbane

* Real horse riding on quality horses in the State Forest
* Handy to Noosa and Sunshine Coast, Queensland.
* Horse riding Lessons with qualified instructors
* Affordable - $180 for a 1/2 day ride (approx 3 hours)
* Horse agistment
* Horse leasing
* Endurance riding and coaching

properties.name: K'gari Fraser Island Adventures
properties.description:
Ready to kick your adventure into high gear? Get behind the wheel and experience the thrill of our guided 4WD tours on K'gari, Fraser Island's ultimate playground!

Roam along pristine beaches, conquer rugged terrain, and delve deep into the heart of this natural wonderland with our expert guides leading the way. Whether you're a seasoned off-road enthusiast or a first-time explorer, our tours are tailored to suit all levels of adventure.

Feel the adrenaline rush as you navigate sandy tracks and encounter breathtaking nature around every corner. From hidden freshwater lakes to towering rainforests, there's no shortage of awe-inspiring sights to discover on K’gari Fraser Island.

Our tours offer more than just excitement – they're also a commitment to sustainability and responsible travel. By choosing us, you're not only embarking on an unforgettable journey but also supporting eco-friendly practices that help preserve K'gari for future generations.

Don't just dream about the ultimate off-road adventure – live it with our 4WD tours. Book now and let the thrill of exploration begin!

We Offer:
Guided 4WD Tours
4WD Hire Packages from Noosa

properties.name: BIG4 Rules Beach Holiday Park
properties.description:
Rules Beach is remote and unhurried, one of Queensland’s best kept secrets.
An idyllic beachfront location offering state-of-the-art camping facilities, with extra large grass sites, sealed bitumen roads, luxurious new bathroom and laundry facilities and a beautiful new camp kitchen.

Ideal for relaxing, 4WD beach driving, fishing, turtle laying and hatching, fossicking, and swimming - no crocs, no stingers and average water temperature over 20 degrees!

With the beach on your doorstep and the spectacular Deepwater National Park and Baffle Creek nearby, these remarkable accommodation options are surrounded by breathtaking natural beauty from every vantage.

properties.name: BIG4 Breeze Holiday Parks - Cania Gorge
properties.description:
Cania Gorge is one of Queensland’s hidden secrets. It’s an ancient place created over 200 million years by natural weather events. What’s left now are towering cliffs, caves, sheltered gorges and ancient Aboriginal art in the Cania Gorge National Park.

This natural wonderland is home to more than 150 plant species, and 90 bird species and is known for rainbow lorikeets, bush-tailed rock-wallabies and common bent-wing bats.

With self-contained cabins, powered and unpowered sites and a water park, BIG4 Breeze Holiday Parks – Cania Gorge is the perfect base for your adventure.

properties.name: Longreach Region Explore Centre
properties.description:
# Longreach Region Explore Centre

The Longreach Explore Centre (Visitor Information) is the first stop for travelers on arrival. Pop in and see the team at the Gold Award Winning Explore Centre about our experiences in the region. Our team are all locals who have a unique insight and love to share the charms and best kept secrets of our region, a connection with a personal experience that will have you coming back again and again. Our friendly staff can provide information on accommodation, attractions, maps and road conditions. 

We can help plan your stay and assist you with all your booking needs. The Centre houses Souvenirs and information on other must-see areas of Queensland and the Northern Territory. When planning your trip to the Longreach region, please be mindful that we experience high temperatures from mid-October through to March. Due to the heat and a significant reduction in visitor’s numbers, the best time to visit is April – October. From November – March, many of the attractions, tours and shows cease to run.

properties.name: Wirrarri Visitor Information Centre
properties.description:
Deep in the far west of Queensland, in wild and isolated country, lies the frontier town of Birdsville. At the end of the famous Birdsville Track, and situated on the eastern edge of the Simpson Desert, Birdsville is surrounded by the vast gibber plains of Sturt's Stony Desert and rich Channel Country.

Wirrarri (the first nation word for Birdsville) has been inhabited for thousands of years by the Yarluyandi, and is now part of the Wangkangurru Yarluyandi Native Title area. In more recent history, white settlers started the town as a rest stop and watering hole for cattle drovers moving their stock. Today, it’s a thriving community where visitors to outback Queensland can enjoy a cold beer at the iconic Birdsville Hotel, back a winner at the world-renowned Birdsville Races as part of the Simpson Desert Racing Carnival, enjoy the amazing music of international artists at the Big Red Bash music festival, or simply relax whilst watching the thousands of birds that inhabit the local waterhole.

There is plenty to keep you occupied in and around Birdsville. Watch the sun set over Big Red, the tallest sand dune in the Simpson Desert. History buffs will get a kick out of seeing one of the Bourke and Wills scar trees on the banks of the Diamantina River. Soend an unforgettable day with family and friends at the Birdsville Billabong, where birdlife, fish, yabbies, and marsupials abound. Or visit the Wirrarri Visitor Information Centre, where the small museum gives insights into living in this remote place.

## Sensory Audio Guides
[Wirrarri (Birdsville) Audio Guide](https://www.australianvisitorcentresapp.com/wirrarri-audio-guide)

properties.name: Hampton Visitor Information Centre
properties.description:
The Hampton Visitor Information Centre is located at the junction of the New England Highway and the Esk-Hampton Road in Hampton, 30 minutes north of Toowoomba in south east Queensland. It is set amongst the tall timbers right on the escarpment of the Great Dividing Range at 715 metres above sea level. It is an accredited visitor information centre which offers a one stop shop for travel information on what to see and do in the area including national parks, lakes, bushwalking, bird spotting, antique and arts and craft shopping...and much more. The centre is staffed by friendly and knowledgeable locals who know all about the hidden gems of the High Country Hamlets region and are ready to help with directions, maps, brochures, accommodation enquiries and other travel assistance. It also has free WIFI for the travelling public's convenience. The centre is housed in 100 year old building. The warmth emanating from the honey coloured hoop pine walls and the wide planks of the tallowwood floors mixed with the smell of the linseed oil finish make this a delightful place to pick up tourist information, talk to a local and linger awhile.

## Sensory Audio Guides
[Hampton Audio Guide](https://www.australianvisitorcentresapp.com/hampton-audio-guide)

properties.name: South Burnett Energy Centre (Nanango)
properties.description:
The South Burnett Energy Centre reflects the past, the people and the energy technology that developed the region and continues to mould their future. The visually exciting displays are located in a building formerly owned by Tarong Coal and incorporate a number of time lines and interactive displays as well as the original engines that supplied energy to Nanango for the first time in 1933. Come along to experience and discover the history of power generation in the South Burnett... Power up your very own virtual power station. Peddle a bike to generate all forms of energy with the ultimate result of a "gobstopper". Ponder over the original working motors which provided the first reticulated power to Nanango in 1933

## Sensory Audio Guides

Yongala Dive Virtual Reality Experience, you can experience one of the world's most famous dives and learn the history of the S.S. properties.name: Sarina Sugar Shed
properties.description:
The Sarina Sugar Shed is a popular tourist attraction located in Sarina, Queensland, Australia. It is a working miniature sugar mill that offers visitors a unique opportunity to learn about the process of sugar production.  
The one-hour fully guided Sugar Shed tour. The tour starts with a welcome and introduction, followed by a short walk outdoors, past our sugar cane patch and historic machinery.
Your guide will take you on a brief historic journey into the pioneering days of the sugar cane farmers in the Mackay region. Then it is back indoors, into our miniature mill and distillery area, where your guide will take you through the process of extracting juice from fresh sugar cane.
The tour finishes with tastings of our liqueur products, our chutneys, relishes and sauces, our non-alcoholic ginger beer, and our freshly-spun fairy floss.
All tours are conducted in our working mini replica mill at the Sarina Sugar Shed, our machinery replicates the process of a full-scale mill, and we do not offer tours to the full-scale Plane Creek Mill who are situated next door to us.
4 guided tours per day: 9.30am, 11.00am, 12.30pm, 2.00pm.  
The Rum Distillery Tour operates at 12pm daily 30 mins. The experience explains the distilling process at Sarina Sugar Shed, from the crushing of the cane to distilled cane spirit that creates our rum and liqueurs.
Tasting includes an exclusive selection of rum or rum liqueurs not available on our regular tour.
Running daily at noon, enjoy this tour on its own, or packaged with our 11am or 12.30pm Sugar Shed tour for the complete experience!
This is a great experience for dedicated rum lovers or those interested in finding out more about the rum distilling process from sugar cane juice to the finished product!

Bookings are strongly advised to avoid disappointment.

properties.name: Ngana Kulkinga Dungay: We All Going Cape Tribulation - Half Day
properties.description:
Spend time with a local Kuku Yalanji Aboriginal guide, visiting some cultural sights, learning about the history of the people and how the people have maintained their culture and adapted to modern day life. 

Our Ngana Kulkinga Dungay half day tours travel north of the Daintree river and explore the Daintree rainforest and environment around Cape Tribulation, where the rainforest meets the reef.

properties.name: Ngana Julaymba Dungay: We all Going Daintree - Full Day Tour
properties.description:
Discover the Kuku Yalanji people's environment and learn the history, culture and traditions of the local Aboriginal people. Walk through the rainforest and coastal habitats, visit a number of culturally significant areas and learn about the relationships the Kuku Yalanji still have with their land. 

Sample bush foods, collect shellfish and practice traditional hunting techniques. 

Try your hand at boomerang and spear throwing, witness Mossman Gorge and cool off in a freshwater stream.

properties.name: Milbi Sunset Cruise
properties.description:
Enjoy a spectacular 90 minute sunset cruise at Hervey Bay on the Fraser Coast of Queensland. Cruise the spectacular Great Sandy Straits aboard the Milbi vessel while enjoying fresh local king prawns, canapes and champagne. 

The iconic Urangan Pier is the backdrop for your sunset cruise. Hear the tales of the Butchulla people of K'Gari (Fraser Island) and surrounds. 

Discover the Butchulla names and meanings of significant local landmarks, before stepping ashore on Weenandan (Round Island).

properties.name: Djinang Cultural Walking Tour
properties.description:
Are you looking for the perfect way to include indigenous tourism into your trip to Hervey Bay? 

Take a walk in the footsteps of a local Butchulla man. 

The Djinang Tour is a unique cultural journey that connects visitors with Butchulla culture and history, offering a new appreciation and perspective of the oldest living culture in the world. Discover significant sites to the Butchulla people in Hervey Bay and K'gari (Fraser Island). 

Deepen your understanding of this beautiful location, discover important gathering places, bush tucker and hear first hand the local story of creation.

properties.name: 4WD Aboriginal Rock Art and Ranger Day Tour
properties.description: Spend the day with the Traditional Owners departing from Cooktown and discover ancient rock art galleries on an exclusive interpretive rock art walk. Join Balnggarrawarra Traditional Owners on a full day tour of their homelands. Rich in cultural heritage and historic sites the location boasts a diverse natural and cultural landscape. Discover rare rock art and learn about traditional bush food and medicine.

properties.name: The Ginger Factory
properties.description: The iconic Ginger Factory offers fun rides, fascinating tours, a unique retail precinct and cafe surrounded by beautiful sub-tropical gardens for all to enjoy. Free entry and open seven days, year round, there is something for everyone.

properties.name: BIG4 Noosa North Shore
properties.description:
BIG4 Noosa North Shore: Nature Escape on Sunshine Coast.

Between Great Sandy National Park and Lake Cooroibah, BIG4 Noosa North Shore offers a family-friendly getaway in beautiful Noosa, Sunshine Coast. Accessible by 2WD and a quick ferry ride across the Noosa River, this nature retreat boasts a range of accommodation options including glamping tents, cozy cottages, and caravan sites.

Enjoy a relaxing stay by the pool, or try out exciting activities like laser tag, bouldering, or exploring the lake on a stand-up paddleboard. Spot local wildlife like kangaroos and lorikeets, or go whale watching during migration season. Immerse yourself in the beauty of Noosa National Park's hiking trails, or take a day trip to iconic Rainbow Beach. With its peaceful surroundings and abundance of activities, BIG4 Noosa North Shore is the perfect Sunshine Coast escape for you and your loved ones.

properties.name: Everglades Eco Safaris
properties.description:
Embark on an unforgettable wilderness adventure into Australia's only Everglades system with Everglades Eco Safaris. Located in Noosa, Sunshine Coast, Queensland, this award-winning eco-tourism company unveils the beauty of the Noosa Everglades.

Glide through the crystal-clear waterways, aptly named "River of Mirrors", on their custom-built eco-vessels. Witness an abundance of wildlife, including over 40% of Australia's birdlife, as you cruise beneath ancient tea-tree forests.

Choose from a variety of tours that cater to all ages and interests, from scenic cruises to exciting canoe adventures. With expert guides by your side, learn about the region's rich history and unique ecosystem.

properties.name: Turtle Discovery Ecotour
properties.description: Enjoy a leisurely guided eco tour through the pristine waters of the Great Sandy Marine Park in Hervey Bay. Join this leisurely guided ecotour through the calm, clear waters of the Great Sandy Marine Park. You will be able to view the coral gardens from the comfort of the Milbi, one of Australia's largest glass bottom boats. This tour offers snorkelling equipment to enable you the ultimate experience of coming face to face with the infinite wonders of the marine park.

properties.name: Ngana Kulkinga Dungay: We All Going Cape Tribulation - Full Day Tour
properties.description:
Spend time with a local Kuku Yalanji Aboriginal guide, visiting some cultural sights, learning about the history of the people and how the people have maintained their culture and adapted to modern day life. 

Our Ngana Kulkinga Dungay tours travel north of the Daintree river and explore the Daintree rainforest and environment around Cape Tribulation, where the rainforest meets the reef.

properties.name: Ngana Julaymba Dungay: We all Going Daintree. Half Day Tour
properties.description:
Discover the Kuku Yalanji people's environment and learn the history, culture and traditions of the local Aboriginal people. 

Walk through the rainforest and coastal habitats, visit a number of culturally significant areas and learn about the relationships the Kuku Yalanji still have with their land. Sample bush foods, collect shellfish and practice traditional hunting techniques. 

Try your hand at boomerang and spear throwing, witness Mossman Gorge and cool off in a freshwater stream.

properties.name: Hands On Country Eco Tour
properties.description: Cruise across the Trinity Inlet, dotted by yachts and luxury boats. Receive an authentic Mandingalbay Yidinji, welcome and cleansing smoking ceremony, and visit a cultural site which is also home to the Djunbunji Land and Sea Rangers who undertake traditional land practices to rejuvenate and nourish the land. Our Indigenous guides escort guests on a 20-minute guided nature walk at the base of Greys Peak National Park, discovering the Mandingalbay Yidinji bush "supermarket and pharmacy".

properties.name: Daintree Full Day Private Charter
properties.description:
Enjoy a personalised tour with a local Aboriginal guide. Your tailor made tour can include Cultural and Sightseeing visits around the Mossman, Mossman Gorge, coastal habitats and the Daintree area. 

When making your booking let us know your preferences and we can plan the experience to suit you i.e. art and craft galleries, guided walks, river cruises, markets, waterfalls, wildlife. Pick ups from Port Douglas, Mossman and Daintree Village are included in the private tour price.

properties.name: Splitters Farm Camping
properties.description:
Set amongst lush tropical bushland, Splitters Farm is a 160 acre property on the beautiful Splitters Creek. 

Splitters is a working Cattle Farm that originally started taking in abandoned farm animals and is now a haven for more than 400 rescue animals and counting.

properties.name: Fraser Island 4WD Adventures
properties.description: We offer a range of products and packages to suit different Fraser Island experiences. Tailor make your holiday with a 4WD hire, 4WD tour or hiking package, pick your experience below. We are based in the beautiful Hervey Bay, gateway to the Fraser Coast and Fraser Island.

properties.name: Ocean Free Great Barrier Reef and Green Island Tour
properties.description:
Ocean Free offers you the opportunity to experience the wonders of the Great Barrier Reef as it was intended. 

Ocean Free is the only operator in Cairns to offer a personal sailing, reef and island tour with only a maximum of 25 guests! Snorkel, dive the reef straight off the boat with tender transfers to explore, relax on Green Island.

properties.name: Millaa Millaa Tourist Park
properties.description: Situated in 7 acres of rainforest gardens with lush grassed surrounds the Millaa Millaa Tourist Park is Pet Friendly and provides the ideal destination for the budget minded traveller. Relax in the tropical gardens, swim in our pool, Play Golf, go for short walks, or longer self-drives to explore the area. An enjoyable relaxing stay.

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Tannum Sands
properties.description:
Seeking sanctuary? Discovery Parks - Tannum Sands, with its quiet bushland setting next to Tannum Beach, will have you refreshed and recharged in no time.

Our holiday park is within walking distance of picturesque Tannum Sands and Boyne Island, on Millennium Esplanade. The waters at Tannum Beach are so mild; you can take a dip virtually any time of year. Take a boat trip out to Wild Cattle Island, a habitat of endangered birds and turtles. 

Boyne Island, surrounded by the Boyne River, is perfect for fishing and water skiing. If you'd rather stay on dry land, Turtle Way is a 15 kilometre riverfront walking track.

properties.name: Noosa North Shore Beach Campground
properties.description: The Noosa North Shore Beach Campground is a great destination for families,

properties.name: Main Beach Tourist Park
properties.description: Main Beach Tourist Park is in the heart of the Gold Coast

properties.name: Base Airlie Beach Resort
properties.description:
Base Airlie Beach Resort has stylish rooms, local staff and a fun social atmosphere all in one great central location in Airlie Beach; the gateway to The Whitsundays.

Powered and non powered sites available.

properties.name: Alan and June Brown Stopover Carpark
properties.description:
48 HR RV Park stop area. Permits are accessible from the information centre just up the road. If an arrival is needed outside of normal hrs just call ahead. They are very flexible and lenient. 

Toilets and shower block are located across the road. They are cleaned in the mornings and I'd suggest bringing things to shower in. A few homeless people around so if that's not your thing then probably give it a miss.

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Coolwaters Yeppoon
properties.description:
Picture yourself surrounded by lush tropical bushland, a peaceful lake, and a beautiful beachfront – the perfect setting for a relaxing getaway. Welcome to Discovery Parks – Coolwaters, Yeppoon, nestled in the heart of the Southern Great Barrier Reef.

Leave your worries behind and escape the daily grind on one of Australia's most welcoming coasts. The adventure starts just outside your cabin or caravan, with a large water park, BMX track, jumping pillow, and a resort-style pool to enjoy.

For those who love the outdoors, take a kayak out on Causeway Lake or explore the nearby bushwalking trails. A short trip away, you can interact with the playful animals at Cooberrie Park Wildlife Sanctuary or explore the stunning Capricorn Caves. At Discovery Parks – Coolwaters, Yeppoon, adventure and tranquility come together for an unforgettable experience.

properties.name: Rainbow Beach Holiday Village
properties.description: Quiet, well maintained family park. Situated on the edge of the beautiful Cooloola National Park

properties.name: Horizons Kangaroo Sanctuary
properties.description: Horizon Kangaroo Sanctuary is a institution dedicated to the rehabilitation and release of orphaned joeys.

properties.name: Kinka Beach Camping
properties.description: Kinka Beach Camping is a 4WD-only location that offers a beautiful, secluded spot for camping and fishing.

properties.name: Ivory's Rock Caravan Park and Camping Ground
properties.description:
If you're a nature lover this is the place for you. You won't believe how beautiful this property is. Nearly 30 years of conservation and this property has returned to its stunning natural beauty, from the rock formations to the native landscape containing extensive bird life and wildlife and the best night sky in the world. A rest here has a deep effect on your soul.



Take advantage of the attractive and spacious camping and caravan sites at Ivory's Rock. Amenities include powered sites, modern shower-toilet blocks (including a number of private bathrooms), laundry facilities, water taps, gas barbecues, communal fire pits and WiFi access. Take a bushwalk up to Ivory's Rock peak with our experienced guide and receive an eco-interpretation of the area, whilst taking in the amazing views (Contact us directly to book a guided tour).

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Mackay
properties.description:
Ready for a holiday that's got it all? Swing by Discovery Parks - Mackay, where "tropical oasis" feels like an understatement. Pristine beaches, jaw-dropping views, and bustling wildlife.

Discovery Parks - Mackay offers a perfect blend of comfort and adventure, making it an ideal choice for travellers looking to explore the Whitsunday Coast. The park features a variety of accommodation options, including well-appointed cabins and spacious camping sites, catering to all types of travellers. With its proximity to the Mackay Marina, pristine beaches, and lush rainforests, it’s an excellent base for those seeking both relaxation and outdoor activities.

**Camping Facilities:**
Camping enthusiasts will find everything they need for a memorable stay at Discovery Parks - Mackay. The park offers a selection of powered and unpowered sites, suitable for caravans, motorhomes, and tents. 

- The powered sites provide access to essential amenities such as electricity and water, making them ideal for those traveling with caravans or motorhomes. 
- The unpowered sites offer a more traditional camping experience, with ample space to pitch a tent and enjoy the natural surroundings. 

Each site is well-maintained, ensuring a comfortable and peaceful stay.

**Amenities:**
- Camp kitchen fully equipped with cooking facilities, BBQs, and a communal dining area for meal preparation and enjoyment.
- Modern and clean bathroom facilities with hot showers and ample space.
- Laundry facilities with washing machines and dryers to keep your clothes fresh.
- Free WiFi available throughout the park to stay connected.

**Family-Friendly Features:**
This park is a family-friendly destination with plenty of activities to keep everyone entertained. The resort-style swimming pool is perfect for a refreshing dip, while the children’s playground offers a safe and fun space for kids to play. The park’s proximity to the Mackay Marina and nearby beaches provides opportunities for fishing, boating, and other water activities, making it an ideal spot for families who enjoy outdoor adventures.

**Nearby Attractions:**
Mackay is a gateway to the stunning natural beauty of the Whitsundays and the Great Barrier Reef. The park is just a short drive from the Mackay Marina, where you can enjoy dining, shopping, and waterfront views. The nearby beaches, such as Harbour Beach and Lamberts Beach, offer pristine sands and clear waters, perfect for swimming, sunbathing, and beachcombing. For nature lovers, the Eungella National Park, located a bit further inland, offers lush rainforests, waterfalls, and the chance to spot native wildlife, including the elusive platypus. Mackay’s town center also offers a variety of shops, cafes, and cultural attractions, providing plenty of opportunities to explore.

**Pet Policy:**
Pets are welcome on selected sites, but prior approval is required, and availability may be limited. Be sure to confirm the pet policy when making your reservation.

**Check-In/Check-Out:**
Guests are welcome to check in from 2:00 PM, with check-out by 10:00 AM on the day of departure.

properties.name: Cairns Crystal Cascades Holiday Park
properties.description: The Drayton Family (Russell, Jenine and son Phillip), and our friendly staff welcome you to our piece of paradise. Set in an awe inspiring natural location and surrounded by rainforest and scenic mountains this is an exceptionally peaceful park that is popular with all ages. We take great pride in our park and maintain our beautiful landscaped grounds, accommodation and amenities to the highest standard. This park is also the perfect base for all of the popular tourist destinations in Cairns and beyond - our knowledgeable staff can help you with bookings for Skyrail, Kuranda Scenic Railway, the Great Barrier Reef, the Daintree and even Cape York Tours. In fact we have our own itinerary planner for you to peruse on check-in so you don't have to plan a thing - just relax and enjoy!

properties.name: Treetops Adventure Cape Tribulation
properties.description: Uncover the wonders of the Daintree Rainforest through our serene zipline canopy tour. Ascend to heights of up to 15 meters above the ground, soaring across nine ziplines spanning 15 to 130 metres long, and enjoy the stunning panoramic views as you traverse the timber walkways.

properties.name: The Big Rig - Roma Visitor Information Centre
properties.description:
You'll discover the Roma Visitor Information Centre situated within The Big Rig at 2 Riggers Road, Roma. This accredited Visitor Information Centre is your all-in-one source for travel advice, offering resources like maps, brochures, and trip itineraries. Operated by knowledgeable locals, the Roma Visitor Information Centre is here to offer recommendations on must-see attractions, activities, and dining spots. Engage in a friendly conversation with the staff to discuss your travel plans or to secure reservations.

## Sensory Audio Guides
[Big Rig Roma Audio Guide](https://www.australianvisitorcentresapp.com/roma-audio-guide)

properties.name: Australian Sunset Safaris
properties.description:
Australian Sunset Safaris is a Tour Operator in South East Queensland visiting spectacular pristine Islands such as Moreton Island, Fraser Island and Southern Great Barrier Reef. Our Eco Tours range from 1 Day tours to 6 Day Package Tours.

Our passion is for you to experience our snow white long dreamy Island Beaches.

properties.name: Corella Creek Country Farm Stay
properties.description:
Corella Creek Country Farmstay is a Campground and budget Guesthouse  in the Outback between Julia Creek and Richmond. QLD. Many types of adult and baby animals live at the property. 

All are tame and love people. We are wildlife carers and often have baby kangaroos, reptiles and birds that you can meet and help feed. Food and drinks are available from our kiosk/cafe. Families very welcome. 

Visit Us - best in Winter due to the lovely day temperatures but we have  Outback style chill out facilities for Summer fun.

properties.name: Lakeview Caravan Park
properties.description:
The Lakeview Caravan Park in Richmond is the clean, friendly outback park with the "million-dollar view".  Lakeview Caravan Park overlooks Lake Fred Tritton & caters to tourists traveling the Overlanders Way.

It has a range of accommodation to suit all budget. Pets are allowed, although conditions do apply. Please see the staff at reception.

properties.name: Ocean Beach Tourist Park
properties.description: Escape to the tranquility of Ocean Beach Tourist Park, a hidden gem nestled amidst the scenic bushland on Miami's coastline. This park offers a variety of comfortable accommodation options, from powered caravan and camping sites to self-contained villas boasting stunning ocean views.

Neat public toilets, rubbish bins, BBQ, sheltered picnic areas and a playground are available. The place is very crowded at night, make sure not to come too late. There is a little bit of road noise.

If you are looking for Cape Tribulation accommodation, Safari Lodge offers both Safari Huts and camp sites, as well as a swimming pool and clean amenities in the tropical rainforest.

properties.name: Kandanga Camp Area
properties.description: Large grassy parking area available to SC. Max stay: 72hrs. Gold coin donation requested. Pets are play, dogs ust be leashed.

properties.description: With it's relaxed and friendly atmosphere and close proximity to all areas of town.

properties.description: Large parking area with parking around asphalt and on the grassy field. Toilets, picnic tables, information and rubbish bin on site. Suitable for SC and non-SC. Max stay: 20hrs.

properties.description: Free camp in a beach front up to 48 hours‚Ä¶there are bbq and table and chairs and a cold shower.

properties.name: Boyne River Rest Area
properties.description: This rest area has the highway on one side and the river on the other. It provides toilets, free cold showers, picnic areas and rubbish bins. Many level spaces on a grassy area. Traffic noise.

properties.name: Goompi Trail
properties.description: Join an Aboriginal guide to explore the shore of Goompi a place of cultural significance for the Quandamooka people on Minjerribah (North Stradbroke Island). The Goompi Trail is a historical tour with a local Aboriginal guide The leisurely and interactive tour showcases Aboriginal artefacts, traditional hunting methods, bush tucker, medicines, traditional ochres and see the remnants of an old rock fish trap.

properties.name: Hartley's Crocodile Adventures
properties.description: Hartley's Crocodile Adventures is an interactive wildlife experience for visitors of all ages! Enjoy a leisurely walk around the park, relax on a Crocodile Boat Cruise and attend our educational wildlife presentations. Photos with Koalas, Croc or Python are available (Additional cost). We also offer premium wildlife encounter experiences.

properties.name: Turtle Rock Cafe
properties.description:
Turtle Rock Cafe and Bar is located in the remote rain forest region of Cape Tribulation in Tropical North Queensland, 110km north of Cairns. Situated 400m from the beach, the cafe is located within the heart of the Daintree National Park & Wet Tropics World Heritage area.

The Turtle Rock Cafe and Bar offers fresh wholesome food, great coffee and outdoor dining. With a menu offering healthy & delicious meals made to order, the Turtle Rock Cafe and Bar is also known for its great locally grown coffee & healthier food options for guests, including wraps & smoothies made from local exotic fruit.

properties.name: Kuranda Koala Gardens
properties.description:
Kuranda Koala Gardens provides visitors with the opportunity to encounter some of Australia’s most popular wildlife in one convenient and beautiful location. 

Photos with Koala or Python are available and the opportunity to "Cuddle a Koala" (Additional cost). 

It's the perfect attraction for those with limited time in the region!
properties.fees: General Admission:  Adult $20.00 / Child (4-15 years) $10.00 Closed Christmas Day

properties.name: Birdworld Kuranda
properties.description:
Birdworld Kuranda replicates the natural habitats of almost 60 species and over 350 birds. 

Enjoy the company of Australia's native species and spectacular exotic birds, flying freely in their expansive flight aviary. 

Enjoy being surrounded by free-flying friendly birds with excellent photo opportunities. Optional bird feeding is available.

properties.name: Tin Can Bay Tourist Park
properties.description: Welcome to the picturesque Tin Can Bay Tourist Park, located in Tin Can Bay on the beautiful Cooloola Coast. Enjoy brand new modern facilities, including the camp kitchen, pool-side BBQ hut, laundry and large family bathroom, accessible bathrooms. Just a short stroll from shops, cafes, restaurants & the foreshore. Feed the rare Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins! Tin Can Bay is best known for being a boating and fishing paradise! For those who love the serenity of the coastal lifestyle, the Cooloola National Park, the Great Sandy Straits and World Heritage Fraser Island are all just minutes away.

properties.name: Bluewater Park Rest Area
properties.description: Popular campsite, suitable for both SC and non-SC vehicles. Toilets, picnic tables, rubbish bins. Max stay 48 hrs.

properties.name: Elliot River Park
properties.description: Well established rest area along the highway. Not too noisy though. Toilets, washbasins, sheltered picnic areas and rubbish bins available. Max stay: 20hrs. A safe and clean place to stay. Gas station has basic things for sale.

Temporary Closed for renovations


Parking is behind the road house, right next to the highway. You can use facilities at the station. Road noise. Okay for overnight if tired.

properties.name: Half Day Aboriginal Rock Art Experience
properties.description: With its sandstone escarpments and woodland savannah, this area was a crucial place for the survival of Aboriginal people with plenty of water, food and rock shelters. Discover rarely seen mysterious and spiritual rock art as you are guided by a Traditional Owner. Learn how the Balngarrawarra are keeping their culture alive. Hear astonishing stories handed down through the generations. Discover traditional bush food and medicine whilst enjoying morning tea amongst a bush setting.

properties.name: Bundaberg Rum Distillery and Visitor Experience
properties.description: The Distillery was born in 1888, when seven Bundaberg locals decided with a stroke of genius to take the by-product from the growing sugar industry and open up a rum distillery.

properties.name: Ocean Safari
properties.description: Ocean Safari offers an exhilarating ride to snorkel the pristine untouched Great Barrier Reef off the Daintree Coast at Cape Tribulation. The half day Great Barrier Reef tour visits two different snorkel destinations, each with an extraordinary array of marine life and coral species.

properties.name: Roma Big Rig Tourist Park
properties.description:
Big Rig Tourist Park provides more than just a few nights of accommodation on your way through Roma. 500m from the pubs and restaurants in town, it is adjacent to the Big Rig Information Centre and home to native birds.

Roma is no longer just a refuelling stop as more and more people are enjoying what the town has to offer.

The Queensland outback is full of contrasts and the regional township of Roma is right in the heart of the action. The gateway to myriad adventures in every direction, Roma also offers visitors plenty to see and do in the town and the nearby regions. 

Big Rig Tourist Park in Roma has cabin and workforce accommodation and powered sites for caravans. The park is dog friendly, and has great facilities on hand to help you unwind and make the most of your stay in Roma.

All your needs can be purchased inside the store including pet food. Restaurant also inside. Bathrooms you must go through the restaurant and outside the back. Once outside the back (where outdoor eating area is) you will see signage on the left. Facilities clean.

properties.description: Great location. Good campsite with clean amenities and friendly staff. Short distance to town (1 km) and right on the beach!  A gorgeous location to wake up in!  Sites big enough for all RV's. . Powered and un-powered campsites. No cabins or on-site accommodation. No pets allowed.
properties.fees: From $30 for 2 guests unpowered Off peak.

properties.name: 1770 Camping Ground
properties.description:
Nestled in a secluded bay within the Round Hill Headland, our campground offers a tranquil escape with a pristine white sandy beach and designated areas to safely moor your boat.

We offer a mix of powered sites, with 60% of them providing power, water, and sullage connections. Some beachfront sites provide water but do not have sullage; please check availability when booking as you may need to bring a bucket to collect sullage, which can be emptied into our sullage trap. All beachfront sites have power but no water or sullage. For guests seeking full caravan facilities, we recommend reserving a non-beachfront site.

Our campground is shaded by beautiful trees, but please be aware that limbs may fall at any time due to natural events. Management accepts no responsibility for damage caused by fallen branches or other "acts of nature." Guests are advised to ensure their property is adequately insured during their stay.

The region is famous for its world-class reef fishing, making it an ideal destination for anglers.

Named after Captain James Cook's second landing on May 24, 1770, the town of 1770 offers a peaceful, laid-back atmosphere. While the nearest shopping facilities are 7 km away in Agnes Water, basic groceries are available at our camp kiosk for your convenience.

Enjoy the beauty of our beachfront, spectacular fishing, and unforgettable sunsets!

properties.name: Smalleys Beach
properties.description: Smalleys Beach Camping area is located in the Cape Hillsborough National Park. There are 11 campsites suitable for tents, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include picnic tables, toilets and drinking water. Generators are not permitted.

properties.name: Advancetown Caravan Park
properties.description: Small clean park in quiet hinterland bush setting amongst native birds.

properties.name: Alex Beach Cabins and Tourist Park
properties.description:
There is nothing better than a holiday in the sun and Alexandra Headland is stunning place to base yourself. Alex Beach Cabins & Tourist Park is located just a short walk to the long white beach of Alexandra Headland with its gorgeous blue water just waiting for you to go surfing or swimming.
 
A restful, palm-filled holiday park with a choice of accommodation from powered sites with or without ensuite for campers, or a range of modern and comfortable villas and cabins the whole family or group of friends can relax in.
 
If you'e holidaying with children, there's  loads for them to do in park including swimming in the heated pool or making fun in the playground and games room.

Head to the many inviting beaches or explore the local area for plenty of options for fun, food and relaxation including local shops, restaurants, the local Surf Club, and Sunshine Plaza with a cinema complex.

properties.name: Hugh Muntz Park
properties.description:
This campsite is free to stay at, but allows NO tents with a maximum stay of 3 nights.

SELF CONTAINED VEHICLES ONLY

This camp is ideally placed just off the Pacific Motorway M1 at Beenleigh and has a shopping centre nearby.

3 nights free camping in any 30 days - self contained vehicles only - no waste water to be dropped on ground
Site Facilities - Toilets, Tables, Rubbish Bins, Dump Point, drinking water tap to fill tanks.

properties.name: Toomulla Beach Camp Area
properties.description: Popular campsite suitable for both SC and non-SC. Toilets, BBQs, picnic tables and rubbish facilities. Max stay: 48hrs. One stay per week. Camping in designated areas only.

properties.name: Hervey Bay Half Day Whale Watching Cruise
properties.description:
Book this half day whale watching cruise in Hervey Bay for a memorable cruise you won't forget! Hervey Bay is one of the best places in Australia to spot Humpback Whales on their annual migration during July to October. 

Travelling onboard the purpose built whale watching vessel- the Spirit of Hervey Bay has 6 viewing decks across 5 levels so everyone is guaranteed the best viewing opportunities possible. In addition, you can listen to the whale song through the hydrophone and spy on whales in the underwater viewing room. 

The whale watch cruise departs at 8.30am and 1.30pm with a complimentary morning or afternoon tea served on board. Don’t miss out on this opportunity to witness Humpback Whales up close in their natural environment!

Book your whale watching cruise online here!

properties.name: Bundaberg Park Village
properties.description: Right at the gateway to Bundaberg sits the Bundaberg Park Village, a Motel, Caravan Park and Residents Village

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Fraser Street Hervey Bay
properties.description:
Think of Discovery Parks - Fraser Street, Hervey Bay as your own personal playground, minus the need to fight the kids for a turn on the slide. 

Discovery Parks - Fraser Street, Hervey Bay is the perfect destination for travellers seeking a relaxing and scenic getaway. The park offers a variety of accommodation options, including well-equipped cabins and comfortable camping facilities, all set within a peaceful and beautifully landscaped environment. 

Its proximity to the beach and local attractions makes it an ideal choice for families, couples, and solo travellers alike.

properties.name: Yeppoon Lagoon
properties.description: Yeppoon Lagoon, a cost-free, family-oriented resort-style lagoon pool, graces the southern stretch of the Yeppoon foreshore. Nestled conveniently beneath The Rocks waterfront Cafe, Bar, and Restaurant, it provides the perfect haven for youngsters to frolic and have fun while adults relish a tranquil moment in the shade. Encompassing a vast expanse of 2,500 square metres, the lagoon pool boasts an infinity edge that grants breathtaking vistas of the ocean and the scenic islands of Keppel Bay. Taking a dip in this lagoon offers a distinct and secure way to connect with nature and savor the most exceptional panoramas the town has to offer.

properties.name: Sunset Top Tourist Park
properties.description: Sunset Tourist Park Mount Isa is where east meets west

properties.name: River Gardens Caravan Park
properties.description: Welcome to River Gardens Caravan Park. We are situated in Carrara, Queensland. We have accommodation available to suit all holiday makers; you won't be disappointed. This park is perfect for families, overnight stays and travellers of all ages. River Gardens Caravan Park is the ideal place for you to visit.

properties.name: Burleigh Beach Tourist Park
properties.description: Burleigh Beach Tourist Park is a family-friendly caravan park.

properties.name: Little Yabba Picnic Area
properties.description:
This is a big camping and picnic area on both sides of the road. 

Public toilets, sheltered picnic tables and rubbish bins are available. 

There are picnic tables on a grassy field with views to the river. 

The information board shows all tracks around this campsite and provides information about the fishing rules.

properties.name: Calliope River Camp Area
properties.description:
If you're looking for awesome Free Camping in the Gladstone region, the Calliope River Rest Area is just off the Bruce Highway in River Ranch. There are two sides to the camping grounds and you can stay in each one for 48 hours, giving you four days of free camping.

You'll find the North Side, which is above the river and accessible from behind the Historical Village. The South Side can be accessed at the next exit (south) of the Historical Village.

Grass field at the lodge, talk to frank in the tent or call the number and Ted will answer ;) Ted the farm dog is so cute and welcoming as are the people. 1 toilet and 1 shower. Koalas and wildlife about.

properties.name: Beachmere Caravan Park
properties.description: This unique park in seaside village offers a pleasant beach and good fishing.

properties.name: Charleville Bilby Experience
properties.description:
The Charleville Bilby Experience offers a must-see show! Join a tour of our nocturnal house (where we alter the timing so that the bilby’s night is during our day) and see some super cute bilbies during their night-time activities. After an engaging talk by one of our keepers you will understand more about the plight of this delightful eco-engineer and exactly why they are worth saving from extinction.

The Save the Bilby Fund has been working hard on the breeding facility here in Charleville and we have produced over 50 babies in the last couple of years. Our management of the pairings (ensuring genetic diversity) means that we are helping build up the bilby populations across Australia with the intent of insuring them against extinction. 

Protecting bilbies and their environments mean that many many other native Australian species (some not as cute as our bilbies!) will also be saved.

"Timeless Tranquility" is the slogan of Circles in the Forest bush camp, situated 4 km south of Childers on 236 acres of natural bush land. As the slogan suggests, this camp site is surrounded by native Australian bush land with lots of birds and wildlife to be enjoyed.   You can enjoy a bush walk, read a book, ride your bike, gaze into the fire or just sit and listen to nature's beautiful sounds. 

The site consists of 21 camp sites, three chemical toilets and two hot water showers. Enjoy a shower in a deluxe converted water tank. A fire pit with a barbecue grill is also provided.  Individual fire pits at each site, wood available to buy for a small fee.

No bins are available. Pets on leashes allowed.  No audible music or any loud noise for that matter is allowed. 

Entering Childers from the South, turn left into Taylor Road, which becomes Rainbows Road.  The campsite entry is to your right, 3.8km after turning onto Taylor Road.

properties.name: Freedom Whale Watch Hervey Bay
properties.description:
Experience the magic of whale watching in Hervey Bay, Queensland with Freedom Whale Watch & Charters. Our comfortable 58ft catamaran, Freedom III, takes you on a whale watching adventure along the pristine waters of the Great Sandy Strait Marine Park. Witness majestic humpback whales up close as they migrate along the coast, often breaching, spyhopping, and pec slapping.

Our experienced crew and knowledgeable skipper will provide informative commentary throughout the tour, while you relax and enjoy the beautiful scenery.  A delicious morning tea, tropical buffet lunch, and afternoon tea are all included, making your whale watching experience in Hervey Bay truly memorable.

properties.name: The Summit 1770 Caravan Park

Welcome to The Summit 1770, your ultimate dog-friendly haven at Agnes Water on the picturesque Discovery Coast at the southern end of the Great Barrier Reef. But our caravan park and accommodations are more than just dog-friendly. 

We have created a home away from home where four-legged friends can enjoy our amenities, including dedicated dog facilities and training centre, while you immerse yourself in the tranquility of our spacious sites, which offer panoramic mountain views, creating an ideal setting for relaxation. Or indulge in the luxury of our cottages and houses, where stunning vistas extend from Agnes to the ocean.

At The Summit 1770 we have different site options to suit all requirements. We cater for caravans large and small, motorhomes, buses, vans, camper trailers, rooftop tents, plus camping in cars, tents and swags.

We have sites with concrete slabs, power and water and plenty of room with no one in front or behind you, and 7 metres between you and your neighbour. We have grass sites, with power and water that can be used for caravans, tents or swags.

If you prefer an unpowered site, these are also available, a little further away from the amenities and some levelling may be needed, depending on your setup.

MUST check in by 5pm!

Nestled in the heart of the Douglas Shire, Newell Beach Caravan Park and Holiday Units offers an idyllic escape ideal for couples, families, and nature lovers. Situated just an hour north of Cairns and a stone's throw from the pristine sands of Newell Beach, this park provides a range of comfortable and affordable accommodation options.

Choose from 30 shaded powered sites for your caravan or tent, or relax in one of their five fully self-contained holiday units. All guests enjoy access to Newell Beach Park's clean amenities, including camp kitchen, swimming pools, and laundry facilities.

Beyond the park, explore the wonders of the Daintree Rainforest, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, or take a boat trip to the idyllic Low Isles. properties.description:
Departing from Sea World on the Gold Coast, this is one of Australia’s premier whale watching experiences. Join marine experts for a close encounter with majestic Humpback Whales aboard one of Australia’s newest and luxurious whale watching vessels. Within minutes of the Gold Coast, cruise to the ‘Humpback Highway’ and spy on the world’s largest animals from 6 spacious viewing platforms from sea level to the sundeck with a spectacular backdrop of the Surfers Paradise skyline. During the cruise learn more about these fascinating marine creatures and listen to unique whale songs live with an underwater microphone on board.

The Gold Coast whale watching season runs from early June to November and whale watching cruises will depart daily from the Sea World Cruises Main Beach Terminal at 9am, 12pm and 3pm. Enjoy an early morning cruise before a day of activities on the Gold Coast or relax and sleep in with late afternoon departures available. If your whale watching cruise fails to sight a whale then an alternative date will be offered.

Don't miss out on the 2024 whale watching season - book your whale watching cruise online here!

Within a leisurely 15-minute stroll lies the vibrant Redcliffe Peninsula, boasting diverse culinary experiences, boutique shops, and sandy beaches for a rejuvenating dip.

Modern Facilities
Equipped with essential amenities, including toilets, showers, powered sites, and a convenient dump point for waste disposal, our campground ensures a comfortable stay for all adventurers.

Community Hub
Beyond show season, Redcliffe Showgrounds serves as a vibrant community hub, hosting various events such as darts, bingo, and soccer. Formerly the training ground for the Redcliffe Dolphins, the venue continues to foster camaraderie and recreation for all.

Book Your Redcliffe Camping Today
For caravan and motorhome site bookings, contact us at 3284 5387 during camping office hours from 10:00am to 4:00pm, Monday to Saturday. Please note that bookings are accepted via phone calls only, and emails regarding camping enquiries will not be entertained.

**Camping Facilities:**
The camping facilities at Discovery Parks - Ayr cater to various preferences. The park features both powered and unpowered sites suitable for caravans, motorhomes, and tents. 

- Powered sites come with access to electricity and water, ensuring added comfort and convenience. 
- Unpowered sites offer a traditional camping experience in well-maintained grassy areas. 

Each site is designed to provide ample space and privacy for a comfortable stay.

**Amenities:**
- Camp kitchen fully equipped with cooking facilities, BBQs, and a communal dining area for easy meal preparation and enjoyment.
- Modern bathroom facilities, including hot showers, that are clean and well-maintained.
- Laundry facilities with washing machines and dryers for your convenience.
- Free WiFi provided throughout the park to stay connected during your stay.

**Family-Friendly Features:**
Discovery Parks - Ayr is a family-friendly destination with features designed to keep children entertained. The park offers a swimming pool, perfect for a refreshing swim, and a children’s playground where kids can play safely. The park’s location in Ayr provides easy access to local attractions, including parks and recreational areas, making it a great choice for families looking for fun and relaxation.

**Nearby Attractions:**
Discovery Parks - Ayr is ideally located to explore the Burdekin region. The park’s location offers easy access to the local attractions of Ayr and its surrounding areas. The Burdekin region is known for its scenic landscapes, including the beautiful Coral Sea coastline and natural reserves. Nearby attractions include the picturesque Ayr Golf Club, the historic Burdekin Bridge, and the vibrant local markets. The park is also a short drive from the coastal town of Townsville, offering additional attractions and activities.

**Pet Policy:**
Pets are welcome on selected sites, but prior approval is required, and availability may be limited. Be sure to check the pet policy when making your reservation.

**Check-In/Check-Out:**
Guests are welcome to check in from 2:00 PM, with check-out by 10:00 AM on the day of departure.

properties.name: Lake Eacham Tourist Park
properties.description: Our small park is a favourite with travelers and campers enjoying the cooler mountain air in lovely natural surroundings one km from the crater lake.
properties.fees: Powered Sites: $29 for 2 people; Unpowered Sites: $24 for 2 people; Extra guests: $5

properties.name: Rest Easi Motel Caravan Park
properties.description: Park is small but comfortable on gravel. Amenities old but tidy management helpful. Nice and quiet.

properties.name: Armstrong Beach Caravan Park
properties.description: A delightful little caravan park

properties.name: St Helens Gardens Tourist Park
properties.description: Lovely campground, tropical setting, reasonable amenities, friendly hosts. Powered & non-powered sites. 3 x drive through sites.

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Mount Isa
properties.description:
This may be the Outback, but you'll still have a river view. Set by the banks of the beautiful Leichhardt River, our holiday park Discovery Parks - Mount Isa is an excellent base to explore.

If you've never experienced Rodeo, you've come to the right place. Mount Isa is renowned as the Rodeo Capital of Australia and their annual event is fast and furious fun. For a well-rounded taste of this rugged mining country, head to Outback at Isa, don a headlamp and descend into a purpose-built mine, then visit the fascinating Riversleigh Fossil Centre. 

Kids will love Queensland's largest all abilities playground, Mount Isa Family Fun Park.

properties.name: Hydeaway Bay Caravan Park
properties.description: Hydeaway Bay Caravan Park is in a peaceful bush setting 5 minutes walk from the beach (and no roads to cross over). Wildlife comes to the park. Wallabies, Kangaroos, Potaroos wander through, along with the lorikeets and bird life that can be experienced up close. There are many powered and unpowered sites for vans and campers. You will be greeted with a friendly welcome. We have a kiosk, a recreational room with a pool table TV and a book exchange. There are coin operated washing machines and a dryer. The BBQ camp kitchen area has a timber fired BBQ, a fire pit and a camp oven pit.
properties.fees: powered site $36/ $32 and unpowered site $32/ $28 depending on the season. * prices apply to 1 or 2 people. Additional guests + $8 per night. Infants + $1 per night Big Rigs + $3 per night

properties.name: Forrest Beach Hotel
properties.description: Nestled between the beach and tropical rainforest, FBH Caravan Park has 52 shady powered Caravan sites and unpowered campsites.
properties.fees: $28 for an unpowered and $38 for a powered site per night$5 per extra person

properties.name: Springsure Roadhouse Caravan Park
properties.description:
Springsure is located 67 kms south of Emerald and is nestled at the bottom of Zamia Rock. The Springsure Roadhouse and Caravan Park is situated on the Dawson Highway and offers a variety of accommodation options including Cabins, Camping, Caravan Park sites and Single Mens Accommodation. Travellers can enjoy lush grass and gardens, and a quiet setting.

We are also a Roadhouse/Restaurant and offer fuel, meals and takeway from 5.00am until 8.30pm daily.
properties.fees: unpowered site $25, powered site $27 per night

properties.name: Lions Den
properties.description: This historic  caravan park offers the best prices

properties.name: Aquavue Cafe Watersports
properties.description: Hervey Bay's Hub for Food, Watersports and Adventure. Hervey Bay’s finest cafe and water sports venue. Whether you’re looking for a great coffee or some fun on the water, Aquavue has you covered.

properties.name: Crystal Creek Caravan Park
properties.description: Whether you are camping, caravanning, or looking for a place to stay

properties.name: Anakie Gemfields Caravan Park
properties.description:
"Gem of the West" is the catch phase for the Anakie Caravan Park and the giant gemstone that stands at the entrance of the Park adds weight to the slogan. It is inside the park where you notice what a gem it really is.

Anakie is located 43km west of Emerald, midway between Rockhampton and Longreach. The park is an ideal stop over or a base to explore the many attractions of the Gemfields, Central Highlands and surrounds.

properties.name: Clermont Caravan Park
properties.description: Good amenities, quiet location. Powered sites, campsites

properties.name: Main Range National Park Camping Ground
properties.description:
There are three developed camping areas in Main Range National Park; Spicers Gap camping area and the Poplar Flat and Manna Gum camping areas at Goomburra. Private campgrounds are located opposite Queen Mary Falls and at Goomburra. 

Spicers Gap camping area is located on the eastern side of the range to the south of Cunninghams Gap. The Goomburra camping areas are located on the western side of the range to the north of Cunninghams Gap.

properties.name: Lamington National Park Camping Ground
properties.description: There is one camping area in the Green Mountains section

properties.name: Girraween National Park Camping Ground
properties.description:
Create camping memories of a lifetime—share the day’s adventures over a barbecue, spot possums or insectivorous bats at night and wake with the birds at Girraween’s well-equipped camping areas. 

Kambuwal camping area, nestled in among trees and granite rocks, has more intimate sites suitable for small caravans, camper trailers and various-sized tents. Whereas Terrawambella camping area has open spacious sites for camper trailers, large caravans and motor homes. The tent area is only available for large, organised groups. 

Bushcamping in remote sections of Girraween National Park is also permitted (restrictions apply). As sites are not identified by signs or markers, campers need good navigation skills and to practice minimal impact behaviour when using these areas.

properties.name: Eungella National Park Camping Ground
properties.description: The park protects many unusual plants and animals, including the Eungella dayfrog, Mackay tulip oak, Eungella spiny cray and Eungella honeyeater. This isolated mountain refuge lies close to the boundary between subtropical and tropical rainforests and supports species from both vegetation types.

properties.name: Carnarvon Gorge Camping Area
properties.description:
Camping in the Carnarvon Gorge day-use area is only permitted during the Easter, winter and spring Queensland school holidays. 

Big Bend camping area, reached by a 9.7 kilometre walk, is open all year. Remote camping in other areas of the park is also available. 

Camping permits are required and fees apply.

properties.name: Myella Farmstay - Baralaba
properties.description: At Baralaba, Myella backpackers hostel you can experience the true outback way of life on this genuine cattle farm, just 125kms from Rockhampton.

properties.name: Tropical Beach Caravan Park
properties.description: Situated on one of the many award winning beaches Bowen has to offer.
properties.fees: Waterfront Sites $39-$44, Ensuite Sites $39-42, Powered Sites $35-$38

properties.name: Torquay Caravan Park
properties.description: Unwind and reconnect with nature at Fraser Coast Beachfront Tourist Parks in Torquay, offering a range of accommodation options ideal for beach lovers and nature enthusiasts. Wake up to the sound of the waves and enjoy stunning beachfront views from your camping site or cabin.

properties.name: Takarakka Bush Resort
properties.description: Escape to Takarakka Bush Resort Carnarvon Gorge.

properties.name: Straddie Camping
properties.description: Straddie Camping offers easy access island camping

properties.name: Southend Camping Grounds
properties.description:
Situated on the southern end of Curtis Island, just 12 kilometres from mainland Gladstone, the South End Camping Ground offers 20 unpowered sites with ocean views! 
Access to Curtis Island is by private vessel or via Curtis Ferry Services which operates five days per week and can transport passengers and vehicles. 
A short distance from the camping ground is a corner store where visitors can purchase a variety of items, including drinks, ice, newspapers, toiletries and non-perishable food items.

properties.name: Sharp Park River Bend Country Bush Camping
properties.description: James Sharp Memorial Park is a family bush camping ground situated five kilometres from the township of Canungra. Sharp Park River Bend Country Bush Camping has five hectares of managed and well maintained camping and recreational grounds set amongst the hills on the Upper Coomera River.

properties.name: Pelican Rest Tourist Park
properties.description:
Pelican Rest Tourist Park in Goondiwindi is a welcoming and well-equipped accommodation option, situated in the heart of the picturesque town. With a reputation for excellent facilities and top-notch service, this tourist park caters to travelers seeking a comfortable and convenient stay.

The park offers a variety of accommodation options to suit different preferences, from spacious powered and unpowered caravan sites to cozy cabins. Visitors can enjoy modern amenities, including clean and well-maintained amenities blocks, a camp kitchen, and a barbecue area perfect for socializing with fellow travelers.

One of the notable features of Pelican Rest Tourist Park is its proximity to the Macintyre River, providing a serene backdrop for guests to relax and unwind. The park's location is also convenient for exploring Goondiwindi's attractions, with the town center, local shops, and restaurants just a short drive away.

The friendly and helpful staff at Pelican Rest Tourist Park ensure a pleasant and hassle-free experience for guests, contributing to the park's positive reputation among travelers passing through or staying in Goondiwindi. Whether you're a caravan enthusiast, a family on a road trip, or a solo traveler, Pelican Rest Tourist Park offers a comfortable and enjoyable stopover in this charming Australian town.

properties.name: St. Lawrence Recreation Reserve
properties.description: Big camping area along the road to St. Lawrence, run by donations ($10 or more). Max stay: 7 nights. Dump point, public toilets, picnic areas, portable and non-portable water, rubbish bins available. This is a very clean and welcoming location! The community takes very good care of this campground. The place is quiet, there are separate areas for generators.

properties.name: Pialba Beachfront Caravan Park
properties.description:
Pialba Beachfront Caravan Park offers an idyllic beachfront escape in the heart of Hervey Bay, Queensland. Nestled on the shores of stunning beaches, the park provides a variety of comfortable and affordable accommodation options for families, couples, and groups. 

Unwind by the Beach: 
-Enjoy the park's prime location with direct access to the beach. Spend your days swimming, sunbathing, or exploring the coastline. 

Explore Hervey Bay: Pialba Beachfront Caravan Park is just a short walk or drive from shops, cafes, restaurants, and all the exciting activities that Hervey Bay has to offer.

properties.name: Take-A-Break Bush Camping (Forshaw)
properties.description:
Our campsites are located in a rural setting with plenty of shady trees, friendly cows and mountain views close to the Fitzroy River. Relax around a campfire on a peaceful dam and listen to the kookaburras. Dip your toes into the cool water whilst sipping watching the sunset.

It is 10km to the upgraded Fitzroy River/Thompson Point boat ramp and pontoon. Enjoy some excellent fishing and crabbing on the river, bird watching and bush walking up the many hills. Only1/2 hr. drive to the beaches (Emu Park & Yeppoon), National Parks (Mt Etna Caves, Mt Archer Baga, Limestone Creek), and Rockhampton (Kershaw Gardens & Rockhampton Free Zoo).

Campfires in the firepits provided on each site. (Welcomed to BYO own firepit). Pre-cut fire wood for sale on site. Pets are welcome, however the must be kept within your allocated campsite area and supervised at all time. (Dogs are not allowed to chase livestock or native animals). Quiet genset are also allowed.

Definitely no boats to be backed into the dam for washing purposes. Fish cleaning and boat washing facilities at the solar bore near front entrance. Telstra mobile reception (3G & 4G). TV reception with antenna. We a setup for fully self contained camping, however there is a basic bush shower/toilet available for our campers.

The dam is a pristine eco area and no soap/detergents/chemicals to used in/around it. The dam is stocked with yabbies, silver perch and bass – catch and release.

Camp site caters for 2 Adults and up to 4 kids per site.

properties.name: Bluff Point Walking Track
properties.description:
The Bluff Point Walking Track is a scenic 2.3-kilometer return walking track located in Yeppoon, Queensland, Australia. It offers stunning views of the Capricorn Coast, including Keppel Bay, the Great Barrier Reef, and the islands of the Capricorn Group.

The track starts at the Bluff Point Lookout car park and follows the coastline around Bluff Point. The track is well-maintained and suitable for all ages and fitness levels. The walk takes around 1 hour and 15 minutes return.

properties.name: Goomeri Showground
properties.description:
Easy place to stay for a night or two. Roadhouse opposite. Town has all the facilities some of interesting old buildings. 

Art Deco Pub has nice meals as well. 

The Showgrounds is just $20 dollars per night ($25 for powered) with water. 

Level sites all grass and onsite caretaker.

Dogs welcome if on a leash.

Showers and toilets on site, along with a dump point.

NON-CAMPERS FEES:

- Dump fee $2 (payable to caretaker)
- Water refill $5 (payable to caretaker)
- Dump and Water included for paid campers
- Shower $5

properties.name: Broken River Bush Camp
properties.description: Camp for all vehicle, with wood Bbq, possibility to have hot shower for 5 $ if you cross the road. Public WC near the information center if you cross the road. The camp is next to the river where you can observate platipus ! 2 short walks around
properties.fees: $6.5 must pay via QLD gov website before arrival, or at the visitor centre

properties.name: Swinging Bridge Rest Area
properties.description: This campground is located behind a pub and it has good amenities, incl. children's playground. It is large, flat and grassy, with a few trees scattered here and there for shade. If you'd like to use power, this can be easily arranged with the pub at a small fee. Showers are also available at the pub and toilets are by the parking area. You can reach town on foot via a swing bridge. 48hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Neville Hewitt Weir Camping Area
properties.description: Large, grassy and safe campsite with fantastic facilities located in town. It is relatively quiet, shaded and big enough to allow privacy. The water views and access are great and you can fish, swim and do water sports here. There is a pub just a short walk away and donations are welcome to help with the upkeep. 48hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Karara Recreation Grounds
properties.description: This is a large and grassy campground with basic amenities, located by Karara State School. There is plenty of shade and a kids' playground, too. These Recreation Grounds are occasionally hosting some events, so check the schedule before arriving.

properties.name: Wugudaji-Adels Grove Camping Park
properties.description:
Wugudaji-Adels Grove Camping Park offers a range of accommodation from cabins to tent sites. 

There are 2 camping areas;

 – The Grove
This is a large shady area situated on beautiful Lawn Hill Creek. There are no set sites in this area and is very popular for family groups wanting to camp together. Small campfires are permitted but no pets or generators. Amenities blocks are located between The Grove and Top camping areas.

– Top Campground
This area is set in natural bushland with over 60 set sites. Many sites have a fireplace and/or tap available, though water is limited by gravity fed pressure. There are pet-friendly sites that can accommodate visitors wanting to use a generator (rules apply). Amenities blocks are located between The Grove and Top camping areas.

- Sunny/Solar sites
- Generator Permitted sites
- Pet Friendly sites

Tours and restaurant deals are available as well. 

All sites are unpowered with facilities including fire pits, tap water, and an amenities block. Call for more details and bookings.

properties.name: Ravenshoe Steam Railway Travellers Rest
properties.description: Ravenshoe Steam Railway Travellers Rest offers a camping area for caravans and large rigs.  Facilites include showers, toilet, drinking water, fire place and mobile phone coverage. There are powered and unpowered sites.

properties.name: Tara Lagoon
properties.description: Tara Lagoon camping area, located on the bank of Undulla Creek offers sites for caravans and large rigs. It also serves as a day rest area. Facilities include hot showers, toilets, picnic tables, water and mobile phone coverage.  There is a maximum stay of 14 days allowed. Pets are permitted.

properties.name: Barcoo River Camp (Blackall)
properties.description: Barcoo River Camp is located aproximately 500m from the centre of Blackall. The campsite is suitable for vehicle based camping, camper trailers, and caravans. Facilities include hote showers, water, picnic tables and a sheltered area. You will find an information centre on Shamrock St, where you must register. Camping fees can also be paid at the visitor centre.

properties.name: Downfall Creek Campground
properties.description: Downfall Creek Campground located in Danbulla State Forest offers sites for vehicle based camping and camper trailers. You will need to be self-sufficient. There are fire rings, but you will need to provide your own firewood. Local attractions include swimming, waterskiing, sailing, fishing, canoeing, and walking trails. Advanced bookings and a camping permit are required.

properties.name: Possum Park Camping
properties.description:
Possum Park Caravan Park offer unique accommodation in underground bunkers, train carriages, ensuite cabins as well as powered and unpowered caravan sites. All in a beautiful quiet bush setting 20km north of Miles on the Leichhardt highway.

To protect your privacy as paying guests David & Julie discourage casual sightseeing. This is also a No Dog Policy Park.

Their aim is to offer you a place that’s guaranteed to recharge your batteries. A relaxing, worry free time, above or underground.

properties.name: Samford Showground
properties.description:
Located approximately seven kms from the Samford Village, Samford Showgrounds is suitable for caravans and campervans. 

The Showgrounds – set in 40 acres of lush countryside – have camping facilities, powered sites for caravans, various buildings that can be hired out year round together with an arena and pavilion.

The grounds are situated approximately 25km from Brisbane City and 7km from Samford Village. It is located in lush country settings surrounded by the Mountains.

The campground has powered and unpowered sites. Facilities include showers, toilets and water (must be boiled/treated before drinking). To make a booking, contact the caretaker.

It is pet friendly.

properties.name: Munall Campground
properties.description: Located 8km beyond the park entrance, Munall campground features 16 sites for tents, vehicle based camping, small motor homes and vans. Facilities include individual fire rings, log seats and composting toilets. You will need to bring your own water. Generators are not permitted.

properties.name: Charter Towers North Riverside Camping
properties.description: Front parts of this riverside camping area are suitable for all kinds of vehicles, rear side (across the river) is better with 4WD. There is enough room for everyone to find a fitting spot. No facilities available at this well-established campsite. Explore the beautiful surrounding of the river basin and make sure to take your rubbish home.

properties.name: Herberton Range National Park
properties.description: Just a gravel roadside area along the road. No facilities. Only recommend if there are no other options available. Muddy when wet. Entrance to parking a little steep. No possibilities for caravans to turn if crowded.

properties.name: Colinton Rest Area
properties.description: This is a basic rest area for SC only. Picnic tables are available. There is a public toilet across the road at the truck parking area. Take your rubbish with you.

properties.name: Prairie Hotel Camping
properties.description: Campground behind the Prairie Hotel. Register upon arrival. There is a donation box or have a drink , Meal. In return for a safe night camping .

properties.name: Emerald Botanical Gardens Rest Area
properties.description: Nice place at the edge of the beautiful botanic gardens. Unfortunately it's located right next to the main road, partly underneath the frequented main bridge. Heavy road noises. Only other noise comes from the parrots that live in the palm trees of the botanical gardens. Max stay: 20hrs over 4 week period. Toilets are in the botanical gardens, BBQ and sheltered picnic areas are very close to the parking area. Rubbish bins also. You can spend a lovely day in the botanical gardens and a good night with earplugs.

properties.name: Gold City Roadhouse
properties.description:
The roadhouse allows overnight parking in certain areas on the gravel area in the back of the station. Station is open 24/7, please ask for permission. Staff are very friendly and helpful. Toilets and hot showers for free, open 24/7, located outside the roadhouse. 

Area clean, laundry facilities (ask inside for prices). This is a very welcoming place. Only downside are road and truck noises and dust that trucks produce when arriving or leaving. Other than that it's a great place to stay.

properties.name: Virgin Rock Rest Area
