properties.description: Overnight parking in the Lions Park is permitted. The park offers beautiful views to all sides (of Mt Zania and the Virgin Rock especially). Public toilets, BBQ, sheltered picnic benches and rubbish available. Overnight parking options are infront of and behind the park. Whereas the rear part is more quiet than the front part. There is a level, gravel area in the back with a few trees at the edge. Front part parking is underneath trees, but directly exposed to the road. Great place, friendly atmosphere, well-established.

properties.name: Neil Turner Weir
properties.description: Series of camping areas on the S bank of Maranoa River. Toilets, picnic tables and BBQ facilities available, and a boat ramp. Some shade, plenty of space. Located on Alexandra St in Mitchell, 3km N of Warrego Hwy.

properties.name: Fountain Springs Rest Area
properties.description: This site is suitable for non-self contained vehicles as well as self contained. Located directly off highway with paved drive through areas and hard level sand for extra camping. Toilets are on site. Covered picnic tables with BBQs and general rubbish bins nearby each table.

properties.name: Maidenwell Hotel
properties.description: Hotel offers free camping for motorhomes. Toilets, showers and bins available, and there are meals available for purchase inside. Gold coin donation for showers. Located on Kingaroy-Cooyar Rd in Maidenwell. Max stay: 48hrs.

properties.name: Leyburn Rest Area
properties.description: Large grassy rest area in Leyburn. Toilets, picnic tables and BBQ facilities here, a lot of space to park so room for big vehicles. Some shade from trees. Located on the W side of Tummaville Rd. Max stay: 72hrs.

properties.name: Fletcher Creek Rest Area
properties.description: Large rest area on both sides of Gregory Developmental Rd, on the banks of the river. Toilet, cold shower, picnic table and rubbish bin facilities available as well as a dump point. Located 40km N of Charter Towers. Max stay: 30 days.

properties.name: Warrego Riverside Tourist Park
properties.description:
Welcome to Cunnamulla Caravan & Tourist Park, the only outback park with an absolute water frontage! The Warrego Riverside Tourist Park Cunnamulla in the Paroo Shire is a priority stop on many a traveller's itinerary.

Cunnamulla is well known as the home of the Cunnamulla Fella and "the gateway to the outback". Please bookmark this site or add it to your favourites now so you can check back later when you can.

Located 3 kilometers. From Town situated on the beautiful Warrego River with extra-large powered sites, drive through access. Fantastic outback camp kitchen, bush camping, dump point excellent amenities and it's pet friendly.

About Bush Camping:
th such beautiful bush surrounding you there is nothing better than a quiet corner of the park or riverbank fireplace to setup for a night or three.

The river can even provide you with a little tucker, with fisher-men & women reeling out popular breeds like Murray Cod, Yella-belly (Golden Perch) and Australian Bass. With the right know-how, half an onion, a dob of butter and a squeeze of lemon you've got a gour-met meal fit for the landed gentry.

If fishing's not your cup of tea then town is just 2mins up the road, with butcher's, bakers and some great take aways. There's also a very handy bottleshop (off-license) on the same road as the park just on the edge of town.

properties.name: Somerset Park Campgrounds
properties.description: Nestled amidst natural beauty, Somerset Park Campground offers an idyllic escape for campers seeking a peaceful getaway. Located between Brisbane, Toowoomba, and the Sunshine Coast, this campground provides the perfect base to explore Queensland's vibrant regions.

properties.name: Lake Boondooma Lookout Campground
properties.description: Lake Boondooma Caravan and Recreation Park.

properties.name: Comboyuro Point Camping Area
properties.description:
Comboyuro Point is a large campground providing shady sites of various sizes. All sites are marked with totems. The area offers sheltered bay waters.

Location: on the western side of island within walking distance from Bulwer township.

Access: the campground can be reached on foot and by 4WD. Parking is available beside camp sites. It is accessible for camper trailers.

Number of sites: a maximum of 49 sites are available, all marked with totems. Seasonal closures mean that not all sites will be full all year round.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car, walk-in camping, camper trailers and large groups.

Camp site surface: sand.

Facilities: water (treat before drinking), septic toilets, rubbish bins, portable toilet waste disposal and cold showers.

Open fires: allowed (in existing fire sites only), except when fire bans or prohibitions apply. Fuel or gas stoves, rather than open fires, are recommended.

Generator use: not permitted.

Essentials to bring: drinking water and containers, water sterilisation tablets, rubbish bags, sunscreen, insect repellent, firewood (untreated mill off-cuts), axe, sealable containers for rubbish, first-aid kit and sand pegs.

properties.name: Ball Bay Campground
properties.description:
Ball Bay is a picturesque, coastal town that offers secluded camping on a small grassy campground.

Camping facilities include toilets, cold beach showers, barbecues and drinking water, however animals are not allowed.

Ball Bay offers easy and close access to Cape Hillsborough National Park bushwalking tracks. In the early hours of the summer months, Flatback turtles can occasionally be seen hatching on the beach.

properties.name: Tropical Travellers Park Mareeba
properties.description:
Tropical Travellers Park is located close to the township of Mareeba and offers powered sites, small hostel accommodation, cabins and fully self contained motel style rooms also available.

Powered Sites:
- Concrete Slab or Grassed Area
- Access to Power, Water and Waste Outlets
- Brand New Camp Kitchen and Laundry Facilities
- Access to Showers and Toilets and an RV Waste Dump Point

properties.name: Dilli Village Campsite
properties.description:
A perfect base to explore and experience K’gari
Camp sites, cabins and bunkrooms behind oceanfront dunes on the eastern side of K’gari – one of the world’s most stunning beaches.

- Spacious, open grassy grounds with dingo-proof fence
- Barbeques, fire pits, toilet and shower blocks
- Large commercial kitchen, dining hall and weatherproof decks for hire
- Starting point for drives and hikes to Island’s lakes, sandblows and forests
- Start/end of K’gari Great Walk
- Closest campground to Hook Point barge
- Beach access

properties.name: Adavale Way Farm Stay
properties.description:
Escape your world & discover something new. A scenic 45-minute drive from Charleviile.

Our property is located 67km North West of Chareville on Adavale Road. We are in the Queensland Outback on 40,000 acres. Our large sites offer the perfect place to base yourself and explore or to just relax and enjoy the serenity.

Our sites have access to amenities including toilet, shower and laundry. We also have areas for table tennis, hand ball and yabbying for the kids to enjoy. We welcome guests to join us for the animal feeding each afternoon, please let us know if you would like to do this.

The lookout camp sites are located 3kms from the main camping area and facilities and is for fully self contained campers only. Come soak up the sunset and stunning views in the afternoon. You can also explore the unique caves and rock formations. and enjoy some wildlife watching. New cave walk is a must see.

Enjoy a BBQ on the mountain overlooking the property and have your own personal campfire or join in with your fellow campers at the communal campfire. Plenty of firewood to collect.

This location provides you with some great photo opportunities.

We welcome guests to join us for the animal feeding each afternoon, please let us know if you would like to do this.

We are also only a short drive from the Langlo River which is a great spot to catch a fish, go kayaking, swim or just relax by the water.

Pets are welcome but must be on a leash at all times to protect the livestock and wildlife. 0-2 years Infant 3-16 years Child 17+ Adult

- Camping sites
- Farm animals (daily feeding available - ask us for details)
- Campfires allowed
- Pets allowed (on leash)
- Power sites available (limited sites)
- Generators allowed
- Water available
- Toilet and shower available
- Fully equipped camp kitchen
- Laundry Facilities
- Bins available
- No cell service (limited WIFI)

properties.name: Dolphins Beach-House
properties.description:
Dolphins Beach House opened its doors at Sunshine Beach, Noosa in 1998.

Since then, the hostel has matured and grown into a backpackers like no other in Australia. The style is bohemian and the vibes are chill.

properties.name: Civic Guest House
properties.description: Voted one of the TOP 10 HOSTELS in Australia, the Civic Guest House is a friendly charming hostel conveniently located in a quiet street close to Townsville's CBD. We offer clean, quiet, safe and cosy accommodation for the traveller looking for quality cheap accommodation. Free Wi-Fi, free transport to/from the Ferry and Greyhound bus terminal.

properties.name: Wallam Creek Free Campground
properties.description: Free caravan and camping area there are plenty of shady spaces to park the van for a few days on the edge of the Wallam Creek. An easy 1.2 kilometre stroll along the creek-side walkway provides access to the little town's main street. Along the walkway, you can appreciate Aboriginal dreamtime artwork and exert some energy on the exercise equipment that flanks the walkway. Free showers and toilets as well

properties.name: Tabbil-ban Dhagun Mangrove Boardwalk
properties.description: Tabbil-ban Dhagun Mangrove Boardwalk, winding through the mangroves for 2km, the boardwalk juts out at several points to reveal magnificent views of Shorncliffe and the turquoise waters of the bay. The Boondall Wetlands lie on the edge of Moreton Bay between Nudgee Beach, Boondall and Shorncliffe. The wetlands include more than 1000 hectares of tidal flats, mangroves, salt marshes, melaleuca, grasslands, open forests and woodlands.

properties.name: Storm King Dam
properties.description:
Storm King Dam rests in a picturesque rural setting with many water birds (including pelicans) and is an ideal spot for picnics, water sport and fishing. Fish species include golden perch, Murray cod, silver perch, jew and river blackfish. Anglers over 18 years of age require a fishing permit. 

Facilities include toilets, picnic tables, wood barbecues, drinking water, jetty, boat ramp, swimming area and playground. Please note that camping is not permitted however there is a private tourist park offering camping and caravan sites, and a recreational/youth camp available for large group bookings.

properties.name: Murray Falls
properties.description:
Murray Falls, within Girramay National Park, is one of north Queensland's prettiest waterfalls, with large volumes of water racing over naturally sculpted granite boulders. 

Rainforested mountains and tropical lowlands meet in the attractive foothills of the Kirrama Range. The clear waters of the Murray River cascade down right in front of the viewing platform.

properties.name: Mothar Mountain Rockpools
properties.description:
Mothar Mountain Rockpools is a popular swimming spot located in Woondum National Park, Queensland, Australia. The rockpools are formed by a series of waterfalls that cascade down a granite outcrop. The pools are surrounded by rainforest and tall eucalypt trees, creating a tranquil and scenic setting.

The rockpools are a popular spot for cooling off on a hot day, and are also a great place to relax and enjoy the natural beauty of the area. Visitors can swim, picnic, or simply relax on the rocks and listen to the sound of the waterfalls.

There is a short 500-meter forest walk that leads to the rockpools from the car park. The walk is easy and suitable for all ages. There are also public toilets and picnic tables available at the car park.

Mothar Mountain Rockpools is a great place to visit for a family day out, a romantic picnic, or a solo nature escape.

Here are some additional tips for visiting Mothar Mountain Rockpools:

The rockpools can be slippery, so be careful when entering and exiting the water.
Wear sunscreen and insect repellent, especially if you are visiting during the summer months.
Take all your rubbish with you when you leave.
Be aware of your surroundings and watch out for snakes and other wildlife.
Please note that Mothar Mountain Rockpools is a protected area, so it is important to follow the park rules and regulations.

properties.name: Lake Wabby
properties.description: Lake Wabby is a stunning freshwater lake located on K'gari (Fraser Island), Queensland, Australia. It is one of the deepest lakes on the island, at 11 meters deep, and is known for its crystal-clear water and emerald green color. Lake Wabby is a barrage lake, which means that it was formed when a sand dune blocked off a creek, trapping the water behind it. The lake is surrounded by lush rainforest and towering sand dunes, creating a truly breathtaking scene.

properties.name: Lake Ross
properties.description:
Lake Ross is listed as a Wetland of National Significance. The extensive shallow margins of the lake provide habitat for a diversity of water birds. The lake is also surrounded by thousands of hectares of unspoiled open Savannah teeming with wildlife. Over 220 species of bird have been recorded on or around the lake to date.

Lake Ross stores over 200000 million litres of water and supplies up to 80 per cent of the region's potable water supply.

properties.name: Lake Paluma
properties.description:
Lake Paluma is a beautiful lake located in the Paluma Range National Park in Queensland, Australia. It is a popular tourist destination, known for its stunning scenery, clear waters, and abundant wildlife.
The lake is surrounded by lush rainforest and towering cliffs, making it the perfect place to relax and escape the hustle and bustle of everyday life. There are a variety of activities to enjoy at Lake Paluma, including swimming, kayaking, fishing, hiking, and camping.
Lake Paluma is a beautiful lake located in the Paluma Range National Park in Queensland, Australia. It is a popular tourist destination, known for its stunning scenery, clear waters, and abundant wildlife.

The lake is surrounded by lush rainforest and towering cliffs, making it the perfect place to relax and escape the hustle and bustle of everyday life. There are a variety of activities to enjoy at Lake Paluma, including swimming, kayaking, fishing, hiking, and camping.

properties.name: Lake Fred Tritton
properties.description: Lake Fred Tritton has a relaxed, yet energetic vibe and is bursting with activities to excite the whole family. It is perfect for swimming, skiing, canoeing and the fantastic playground's and water park will keep the kids entertained for hours.

properties.name: Lake Elphinstone
properties.description:
Lake Elphinstone, Australia, is a picturesque lake located in the Brigalow Belt region of Queensland. The lake is surrounded by native bushland and is home to a variety of wildlife, including kangaroos, koalas, and waterbirds.

Visitors to Lake Elphinstone can enjoy a variety of activities, including swimming, fishing, boating, and camping. There are also several walking trails around the lake, which offer stunning views of the surrounding area.

properties.name: Lake Cania
properties.description: Lake Cania is situated north of the Cania Gorge National Park about 11 kilometres from the Cania Gorge Picnic Area. The lake sits on the banks of Three Moon Creek which is a tributary of the Burnett River. The lake has a capacity of 88,500 megalitres and is constructed from earth and rockfill that reach over 44 metres above the level of the dam. There are numerous facilities available at the dam from great fishing and other water sports with boat ramp access, picnic areas, Public conveniences, kiosk and two camping and caravan parks.

properties.name: Kangaroo Point Cliffs
properties.description:
Kangaroo Point Cliffs is a popular tourist destination in Brisbane, Australia. It is a sandstone cliff that rises 60 meters above the Brisbane River and offers stunning views of the city skyline. The cliffs are also home to a variety of native plants and animals, including kangaroos, koalas, and kookaburras.

Visitors can access the cliffs by taking a short walk from the Kangaroo Point Cliffs Park. The park has a number of walking trails, picnic areas, and a playground. There is also a cafe and a restaurant located in the park.

properties.name: Groper Creek
properties.description: Groper Creek is a laidback location, where you can sit back, relax and unwind. You can launch your tinnie from the boat ramp, or fish from the jetty. The area is well known for its fantastic fishing and crabbing. Groper Creek is located towards the mouth of the Burdekin River about 15 kilometres from Home Hill. Head out along Groper Creek Road and you'll travel past sugar cane farms, and through a wetland area full of birds and wildlife. Have a look around the Groper Creek settlement, at the huts built high on stumps. The kiosk and the public phone box are also up high. Bring your camera, as these buildings have their own personality! With the caravan park on the banks of the creek, if you decide to stay longer, check in, set yourself up and enjoy the surroundings.

properties.name: Gordonbrook Dam
properties.description:
Gordonbrook Dam is the sole water supply for Kingaroy and a peaceful spot to unwind. Take in the beautiful dam views from the viewing platform or a variety of walking tracks along the waters edge. Enjoy a picnic at the tables provided and use the wood fired barbecues. 

The dam provides a haven for over 100 different species of birds. Bring your binoculars and camera to record sightings.

properties.name: Golden Gumboot
properties.description: Originally the Golden Gumboot was a competition between Tully, Innisfail and Babinda as to which town is the wettest in Australia. The winner for the competition (since 1970) was awarded with a rubber boot and with an annual rainfall of up to seven metres - Tully was the winner.

properties.name: Gayndahs Big Orange
properties.description:
Gayndah's Big Orange is a 16-metre tall fibreglass orange that sits on the Burnett Highway in Gayndah, Queensland, Australia. It was built in 2003 to promote the town's orange industry and is now a popular tourist attraction. 

Visitors can climb to the top of the Big Orange for panoramic views of the town and surrounding countryside. There is also a small gift shop at the base of the Big Orange where visitors can purchase orange-themed souvenirs. 

Gayndah's Big Orange is a fun and family-friendly attraction that is sure to please visitors of all ages. It is a great place to learn about the town's orange industry and to take some memorable photos.

properties.name: Emerald Creek Falls
properties.description: Emerald Creek Falls offers both an impressive lookout over the Upper Falls and some spectacular swimming holes at the Lower Falls. Around a 2.5 km walk to visit all falls.

properties.name: Donnellys Castle
properties.description: Donnellys Castle offers a combination of natural beauty and historical intrigue, making it a destination for those interested in exploring the unique landscapes and stories of the Australian bush. It's a place where you can immerse yourself in both the geological wonders of the rock formations and the legends of Australia's colonial past.

properties.name: Coonarr Beach
properties.description:
Coonarr Beach is a 4.2 kilometre long, east facing beach that begins underneath the tidal shoals of the Elliott River mouth, then runs straight down to the smaller mouth of Coonarr Creek. A perfect spot for whale watching under the winter sun or secluded dips in the summer. 

There is a gravel road out to the small beachfront settlement of Coonarr, located towards the southern end of the beach. The beach receives waves averaging over 0.5 meters, which maintain a relatively steep and narrow high tide beach fronted by a continuous low tide bar, up to 100 meters wide.

properties.name: Coomba Falls
properties.description:
Coomba Falls, at Maidenwell, is an exceptionally beautiful place, featuring a deep natural swimming hole and striking granite cliffs. The water is icy most of the year, so it's the ideal site to cool down on a hot day. 

Located just a few kilometres from the heart of Maidenwell, picturesque Coomba Falls provides the ideal setting for a picnic and a day of swimming and relaxing. It's also a lovely spot for photography and bird watching

properties.name: Charlie's Hill
properties.description:
Constructed by the RAAF in 1943, the No 211 Radar Station on Charlie's Hill was one of twenty radar installations along the North Queensland coastline. These operated to give an early warning of approaching enemy aircraft during World War II. 

When visiting this historic site, igloos of reinforced concrete which provided bomb-proof protection for the radar equipment can still be seen. The wooden towers which supported the transmitting and receiving aerials have been removed. However, foundations from various structures near the igloos may still be found. The buildings are listed in the Queensland Heritage Register because of the site's historical and military significance

properties.name: Carlo Sand Blow
properties.description:
Carlo Sand Blow is a massive dune of windblown sand located in Cooloola National Park, Queensland, Australia. It is one of the largest sand blows in the world, covering over 15 hectares. The sand blow is formed by strong winds that blow sand from the beach and up the side of the hill, where it is deposited in a large mound.

Carlo Sand Blow is a popular tourist destination, offering stunning views of the surrounding coastline, including Double Island Point, Fraser Island, and Tin Can Bay. The sand blow is also a popular spot for sandboarding, tobogganing, and kite surfing.

To reach Carlo Sand Blow, visitors can take a 600-meter walk through rainforest from the Rainbow Beach Information Centre. The walk is moderately difficult, but there are stairs and viewing platforms along the way.

properties.name: Capricorn Coast Pineapple Rail Trail
properties.description: A popular track for walker, joggers, cyclists and families, the Capricorn Coast Pineapple Rail Trail takes visitors through picturesque bushlands and urban landscape.

properties.name: Buderim Falls
properties.description:
Buderim Falls is a 45 hectare haven of tranquillity less than a kilometre from the north side of Buderim village on the Sunshine Coast - just 15 minutes from the coast. 

With its towering trees, meandering tracks and stunning waterfall, this sub-tropical oasis is a paradise for nature lovers and photographers alike.

properties.name: Brandon Heritage Precinct
properties.description: The Brandon Heritage Precinct is a cultural gem in Queensland, Australia. This historic site showcases the rich heritage of the region, featuring beautifully preserved colonial-era buildings, artifacts, and exhibits. Visitors can explore the past through immersive experiences, guided tours, and events, gaining insights into the area's captivating history and traditions.

properties.name: Blue Mountain Park
properties.description:
Blue Mountain Park, Australia, is a World Heritage-listed region located west of Sydney, New South Wales. The park is known for its stunning scenery, including towering sandstone cliffs, lush rainforests, and cascading waterfalls. Visitors to the park can enjoy a variety of activities, including hiking, biking, rock climbing, and caving.

The park is also home to a variety of wildlife, including kangaroos, koalas, and wombats. Visitors can often see these animals while hiking or camping in the park.

properties.name: Big Mango
properties.description: The 10-metre high Big Mango represents the delicious fruit which carries the name sake of the town "Bowen Mango". The Big Mango is located at the Bowen Visitor Information Centre. Ask about the time the Big Mango was stolen while you enjoy a mango ice cream.

properties.name: Big Crab
properties.description: The Big Crab in Cardwell stands as a colossal representation of a mud crab, a crustacean primarily found in Africa, Australasia, and Asia, often referred to as mangrove crabs. The Big Crab is a two metre high crab, located in the town of Miriam Vale on top of the Shell Service Station and Restaurant. The crab was created in 1979 by the owner at the time wanting to promote his crab sandwiches.

properties.name: Arkarra Lagoons and Tea Gardens
properties.description:
Arkarra Lagoons, a tranquil oasis in the heart of the Gold Coast, is a must-visit for any traveler. With its pristine beaches, crystal-clear waters, and lush rainforest, it's easy to see why Arkarra Lagoons is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike.

The nearby town of Tea Gardens is the perfect place to base yourself while exploring Arkarra Lagoons. With its charming cafes, art galleries, and boutiques, Tea Gardens has something to offer everyone.

Whether you're looking to relax on the beach, go for a swim, or simply enjoy the natural beauty of the Gold Coast, Arkarra Lagoons is the perfect place for you.

properties.name: Aquativity
properties.description: Aquativity is a fun, interactive water-play park right in the heart of Brisbane's South Bank. It is specially designed to encourage families and children to come together and enjoy the outdoors. It celebrates the city's close relationship with the Brisbane River.

properties.name: Sarawak west campground
properties.description:
This sheltered camping area is beachside accommodation at its greatest! Set yourself up here and explore the surrounding area.

Set up your tent, caravan, campervan or camper trailer in one of the shady sites and head off to explore the surrounding area. Drive and walk the beach or throw in a line and see if you can catch a fish for dinner.

If relaxation is more your goal, sit back and read a book in the shade of the coastal sheoaks and Moreton Bay ash.

Why Sarawak? The names of six camping areas on the Inskip Peninsula recall the area’s past shipping history. This former navy minesweeper plied the coastline from Brisbane to Maryborough via Inskip weekly between 1949 and 1970. It brought supplies including drums of fuel and returned to Brisbane with sugar from Maryborough.

Camping area features
Open camping area behind the foredunes. No formally defined sites.

Please note:

Coastal trees provide dappled shade in most areas.
A few camp sites offer views across the ocean towards K'gari (formerly Fraser Island), while other ‘inland’ sites provide shelter from the sun and prevailing ocean winds.
4WD vehicles are strongly recommended as all tracks are sand.
Location: Behind the foredunes, off Inskip Point Road. This is the furthest camping area from the entrance of the recreation area.
Also see: Inskip Peninsula Recreation Area map (PDF, 1.9MB) and Sarawak West camping area map (PDF, 252KB).

Access: 4WD access via Inskip Point Road on sand tracks. No beach access for vehicles into or out of Sarawak West camping area.

Number of sites: Open area without separately defined sites.
Please note:

Occupation of a camp site is on a ‘first in, best placed’ basis.
Reserving or roping off areas is not permitted.
All structures under a single camping permit must be in one place and no more than 3m apart.
Don't spread your camp too far, so others can fit in too; rangers will ask you to move structures that have taken up an unreasonable amount of space.
Camping more than 30 days is prohibited.
Camp sites are suitable for: Tent camping beside a vehicle, off road camper trailers, campervans and caravans.

Camp site surface: Grass and/or sand.

Facilities: Hybrid toilet blocks are provided in this camping area. One has a wheelchair access ramp.
Please note:

- No showers.
- No drinking water taps.
- Rubbish bins are located near the camping area exit.

If you bring a portable toilet, the nearest waste disposal facility is available at the council service facility located on Clarkson Drive just outside of Rainbow Beach. 

Do not empty portable toilet waste into the camping area toilets. Penalties apply.

The service facility also has drinking water—take your own water storage containers.

properties.name: Speehwah Regional Park Campground
properties.description:
Speewah camping area offers three individual sites suitable for tents, camper trailers or campervans, plus a large communal tent area that can accommodate multiple groups. It provides a convenient base for exploring the various walking tracks of Barron Gorge National Park.



This is an e-permit camping area� all camping must be booked in advance; self-registration is no longer available. Camping is only permitted in the camping area/camp site(s) you have booked.
properties.fees: $6.15 per person per night, or $24.60 per family per night; $3.40 per person per night for students and accompanying adults on approved educational excursions.

properties.name: Dululu Rest Area
properties.description: Large area available for SC and non-SC. Toilets and rubbish bins on site. Max stay: 48hrs.

properties.name: Georgina River Camp
properties.description: This site is suitable for self-contained vehicles only as there are no toilets. Site entrance is on the left over the bridge when heading west from Camooweal.  Access road is gravel and sites are slightly uneven mixed grass and sand/gravel with trees for shelter and they are located along the river.  There are two billabongs -Lake Francis and Lake Canellan. The first camping areas are at Lake Francis and if you go further down the gravel road you will find Lake Canellan. MAXIMUM STAY 48 HOURS.

properties.name: Riverview Caravan Park
properties.description:
Nice camp right on the river. 

Front sites have views over the river but are tight for a caravan. 

Friendly staff and reasonable price. 

Good trees for shade

properties.name: Lotus Creek Homestead
properties.description: Fuel, food, restaurant, powered sites, unpowered sites, dogs welcome (advise ahead of visitor) swimming creek.

properties.name: Staircase Range
properties.description: Grassy area big enough for several camps. Turn in at the historic marker and drive in 500m. Some road noise but quiet at night. No amenities.

properties.name: Kurrimine Beach Caravan Park
properties.description: NO FORWARD BOOKINGS, PLEASE SEE CARETAKER ON ARRIVAL

properties.name: Cooktown Campout
properties.description:
Neighbouring Indigenous titled land (Bama Land) you will camp under the brightest starry skies with zero light pollution. Explore the waterfalls around Cooktown. Take in the beauty of the area. Or simply take time to recharge before your next leg of your journey.

We also offer animal feeding. We have Goats, Turkeys. Chickens, Pigs and Ducks to feed each afternoon. The kids love it.

So come and stay with us and do as much or as little as you like.

properties.name: Creeks Edge Park
properties.description:
Situated on a working farm, along the edge of a winding freshwater creek; Creeks Edge Park is one of Far-North Queensland's hidden gems, offering a limited number of affordable RV and Caravan sites. $45 (Camp-A) flat rate p/n: Includes power & water hook up, toilet & shower. $35 (Camp-B) flat rate p/n : Includes toilet & Shower, No-power.

Bookings are essential.

properties.name: Burrum Point Camping Area
properties.description:
Enjoy this relaxed coastal park by staying in one of the two camping areas provided in the Woodgate and Kinkuna sections of Burrum Coast National Park. Both the Burrum Point camping area and the Kinkuna camping zone provide close access to the water and beach activities.

In Kinkuna camping zone, camp behind fragile foredunes, just a short walk to the water and beach.

At Burrum Point, the camping area is behind fragile foredunes, just a short walk to the water and beach. Boating, canoeing and fishing are popular activities on the Burrum River.

You need a four-wheel-drive vehicle to access these camping areas. Walking track entrances are accessible by conventional vehicles.

Camping permits are required, and fees apply. A tag with your booking number must be displayed at your campsite. Book your campsite and purchase your camping permit in advance. Bookings can be made on-line, over the counter or by phone.

You can't camp in the Burrum River and Buxton sections of the park..

The camping area has 13 numbered sites, which are suitable for tent camping and off-road camper trailers. There are no powered sites or caravan access. The camping area also has basic facilities, including cold showers, toilets, and a water tank.

properties.name: Daggs Falls
properties.description: Daggs Falls is a beautiful waterfall located in the Killarney region of Queensland, Australia. It is a popular tourist destination due to its stunning scenery and easy accessibility. The waterfall is situated on Spring Creek, which flows through the McPherson Range. Daggs Falls is a plunge waterfall, meaning that the water drops vertically into a pool below.

properties.name: Finch hatton showgrounds
properties.description:
A great location, this is a showgrounds low cost camp which is on a creek (unpowered) heaps of space and often uncrowded. 

There are toilets and showers in the main oval area.

properties.name: Central Station Camping Ground
properties.description:
Originally established as a forestry camp when there was logging on World Heritage-listed K’gari (formerly Fraser Island), Central Station's beautiful rainforest area houses a display explaining the development of the island and its various flora and fauna.

The camping area is fenced for Dingo safety and set in the rainforest. There is an area for tents and trailers and a separate area for walkers to camp at the western end of the camping main camping area.

Facilities include coin-operated hot showers, flushing toilets, wheelchair access and washing-up facilities. The nearby day-use area has a public phone and access to short walks. Rubbish bins are provided at the camping area entrance.

There is also a wealth of information on display along with picnic areas. Central Station has a short boardwalk around Wanggoolba Creek and through the beautiful K’gari rainforest. This is also the starting point for some other walks such as the Basin Lake Walk.

Access is by 4WD or walk in.

properties.name: Dam Crazy Camping
properties.description: 625 of bush land with large dam for swimming and kayaking. Walking tracks, amazing bird life and also pet friendly. Bookings taken through Hipcamp.

properties.name: Tirranna Springs Roadhouse
properties.description: Roadhouse and camping 34km south-west of Burketown on the Savannah Way (Doomadgee Road).

properties.name: Gum Tree Lodge and Bush Camp
properties.description: Beautiful, peaceful bush camp for the over 50's crowd travelling in a van or motorhome with ensuites. Discounts apply to stay of 4 nights or more.

properties.name: Swan Gully Park Camping
properties.description:
Swan Gully, located in Bromelton near Beaudesert, South East Queensland, is just 45-60 minutes from Brisbane, Ipswich, and the Gold Coast. Spanning over 900 acres, it offers a range of camping options, 4WD tracks (from easy to challenging), and outdoor activities like hiking and mountain biking. Amenities include coin-operated toilets and hot showers, but guests need to bring their own drinking water. 

Pets and horses are welcome, and 2WD access is available. Please ensure check-in before 5 pm as no driving is allowed after this time.

Camp within 900+ acres of parkland!

properties.name: Thargomindah east Camping Area
properties.description: On the entry to Thargy, good spot in the dry only , each side of the road prior to the one way bridges. No facilities

properties.name: Caravan & Camping in Queensland
properties.description: Camp Area, Caravan Park, Camp-site

properties.name: Rosewood Showgrounds Camping Facility
properties.description:
Rosewood Showgrounds Camping Facility is located in the picturesque township of Rosewood, 20 minutes west of the Ipswich CBD and one hour from Brisbane making it the perfect place to set up camp while you explore South East Queensland.

Rosewood has been designated as an RV Friendly Town and the Showgrounds is a short drive or walk to a supermarket, chemist, doctors, coffee shops, and the electric train to Brisbane.

The Showground has 31 powered sites (some with access to sullage) and 14 un-powered sites . Other amenities include toilets, showers and free dump point and potable water.

Nearby attractions include the historic Rosewood township, Cobb & Co Tourist Drive and historic coach display, the heritage Rosewood Railway and museum, St Brigid’s Catholic Church (the largest timber church in the southern hemisphere), Grandchester Model Steam Railway, Spicers Hidden Vale and the Hidden Vale Adventure Park, Queensland Museum Rail Workshops, Ipswich Art Gallery and Ipswich Nature Centre.

All Campers MUST contact the Camp Ground Manager on arrival for site allocation and setup” Your booking site number is indicative only and your camping zone will be confirmed upon arrival

Caters for tents, camper vans, caravans and motor homes - site fees apply. 16 powered sites, equipped with water and drainage. Up to 50 additional sites without power. 

The maximum stay is 7 consecutive nights. Dump point available. Pet friendly - please enquire for further information. 

Please note the Park is closed for the Rosewood Show and other events during the year. Phoning ahead is recommended for access, fees and booking.

properties.name: Riverside Burrum Heads
properties.description:
Riverside is a brand new campsite offering a traditional camping experience.



‚Äã

There's space and privacy for you and yours, surrounded by nature and breathtaking tranquility, with civilization just a stone's throw away.



Nestled in between the Burrum Coast National Park (Burrum River Section) and the Isis River on a section of pristine waterway, with river access. Come and see the beauty of this incredible natural environment for yourself.Please be informed that you'll need 4WD to access

properties.name: Rowallan Park Campsite
properties.description:
Rowallan Park is located 10 minutes north of Mackay and consists of 104 Acres (42 Hectares) of natural bushland. The natural bushland setting of Rowallan Park provides the ideal place for camping and outdoor activities.
Rowallan Park is also currently the home for Mackay and District Mountain Bike Club and Camp Eagle.

The park is also available for use by non-Scouting groups, organisations and schools.

No Dogs.

CAMPING:
There are grassed camping areas available, with fire places, close to showers and toilets.

For those looking for a little more independence there are bush campsites available.

properties.name: Burtons Well Camping Area
properties.description:
Pitch your tent near giant grasstrees and stately stringybarks on a sheltered, grassy slope with scenic views to the north-east.

Relax in this spacious camping area nestled among a forest of stringybark trees and ancient grasstrees. Enjoy spectacular sunrises, and at night tread quietly with your spotlight and you might be lucky to see koalas, greater gliders, squirrel gliders, sugar gliders and other possums foraging in the tree tops. Listen for bandicoots fossicking in the leaf litter.

Choose from to two popular walking tracks—Mount Kiangarow track and Cherry Plain to Burtons Well track. You’re sure to make good use of your camera and binoculars! Listen for the familiar whip-crack call of eastern whipbirds in dense forest nearby and watch for wedge-tailed eagles soaring gracefully overhead.

Campground features: A large, well-grassed open area surrounded by forest. There are a number of ancient grasstrees scattered through the camping area.

Location: About 8.5km north-west of the QPWS information centre.

Access: The camping area can be reached by conventional vehicle. It is not accessible for trailers, caravans or buses. Although the campground is accessible by car, it is not possible to drive onto the camp sites. Parking is available only a short distance from each camp site.

Number of sites: Open area without separately defined sites for up to 50 people.

Camp sites are suitable for: Walk-in camping only; cars must remain in carparks nearby.

Camp site surface: Grass.

Facilities: Water (treat before drinking), toilet (hybrid system), picnic tables, wood barbecues and shower cubicles (BYO shower and water).

Open fires: In supplied fireplaces only, except when fire bans or prohibitions apply. Ground fires are not permitted. Please bring your own clean milled timber, free from pests or disease to use as firewood. Timber cannot be collected from anywhere within the national park. Make sure your fire is out before you leave it—extinguish with water, not sand or dirt. Fuel or gas stoves are recommended.

Generators: Not permitted.

Essentials to bring: Rubbish bags (no bins are provided) and insect repellent. Fuel or gas stoves are recommended.

properties.name: Gidgee's Bush Camp
properties.description:
Our campground spans over 60 acres of open downs and native scrub in Morven, SW Queensland, providing ample space for families to spread out. Gidgee's Bush Camp is the hub for our multi-faceted business, including the manufacturing of Gidgee Smith Bags, which are available in our shop alongside metal and tin sculptures. Guests can enjoy a coffee van in the afternoons, interact with our sheep, cattle, and goats, and relax at our numerous meeting spots like Wilmavale Place with its BYO bar and TV for footy nights.

We offer both powered and unpowered sites, surrounded by sculptures and artwork. Fire pits are available for use, and nature enthusiasts can explore tree walks, wellness walks, or the short 1.2km walk into town. Birdwatching and sunset views over the dam are popular activities, and we’re passionate about educating guests on the outback and the significance of Mulga to our farming.

Whether you're stopping over or seeking a holiday getaway, we’re conveniently located on the Warrego Highway, halfway between Brisbane and Birdsville.

properties.name: Grey Range Rest Area
properties.description: Overnight rest area with toilets, bins and two shelters with picnic tables. Gravel parking area wuth no other shade. Max 20 hour stay.

properties.name: Lake Moondarra Lookout
properties.description:
Lake Moondarra Lookout is a popular spot to enjoy panoramic views of Lake Moondarra, a reservoir located in the Mount Isa region of Queensland, Australia.

The lookout is located about 17 kilometres (11 miles) north of Mount Isa and is accessible by a sealed road. The lookout is free to enter and is open 24 hours a day.

The lookout offers stunning views of the lake, the surrounding mountains, and the town of Mount Isa. There is also a picnic area at the lookout, making it a popular spot for a leisurely lunch or a romantic sunset picnic.

properties.name: Dulacca Hotel
properties.description:
$15 p/n for p&w at the back of the hotel.

This includes a $10 meal voucher.

Check in with staff before parking up.

properties.name: Fraser Coast RV Park
properties.description: Fraser Coast RV Park ‚Äì suitable for all types of RV's, campers, roof top tents, Camper trailers, Caravans, Tents, Swags, Motor Homes

properties.name: Honeyeater Lookout Trail
properties.description:
The Honeyeater Lookout Trail is a 7.5-kilometer return walk located in the Conway National Park, Queensland, Australia. The trail offers stunning views of the Whitsunday Islands, the Conway Ranges, and the surrounding rainforest.

The trail is well-maintained and suitable for all ages and fitness levels, although the first section of the trail is quite steep. The walk takes around 3 hours and 30 minutes return.

To start the walk, head to the Kara Crescent trailhead in Airlie Beach. From the trailhead, follow the signs to the Honeyeater Lookout Trail.

properties.name: Paperbark Forest Boardwalk
properties.description:
**The Paperbark Forest Walk will be closed to public access until further notice while works are undertaken. Sorry for any disappointment this causes.**

The Paperbark Forest Boardwalk is a 400-metre long boardwalk located in the Reedy Creek Reserve. It winds its way through a forest of paperbark trees, providing stunning views of the surrounding bushland and the Great Barrier Reef. 

The boardwalk is a great place to see native Australian birds, such as kingfishers, cockatoos, and parrots. There are also several educational panels along the boardwalk that provide information about the plants and animals of the area.

properties.name: Kin Kin Oval
Camp Barrabadeen
properties.description:
Camp Barrabadeen Activity Centre is located on the southern end of Lake Tinaroo and is accessed by a short drive from Tinaroo Township on the Danbulla Rd. It is a small peninsula jutting into the lake, we are entirely surrounded by Danbulla National Park and therefore is a private and safe contained bush land area.

They are a campsite used for groups, but also have 27 camping sites for the public, most with water frontage.

Campfires allowed utilising provide fire areas/drums.

Composting toilets and hot/cold showers.

Gas BBQ area available for hire.

properties.name: Winton Hotel
properties.description:
A gem of a pub set in outback Queensland. Great food and drinks.

Park out back for $5 per person, per night -  proceeds go to charities.

Self contained vehicles only.

properties.name: Mareeba Bush Stays
properties.description:
Mareeba Bush Stays is a privately-owned, dedicated Caravan Park located near Mareeba, North Queensland.

Set on 150 acres of private property in the heart of the Atherton Tablelands, just 8km from the centre of Mareeba, this exceptional RV & Caravan park caters directly for self-contained Motorhomes, Recreational Vehicles (RV) and Caravans in comfort and with ease.

What Makes Mareeba Bush Stays Unique?

Expansive 50-Acre Ridge Location: Enjoy panoramic views over hills and plains with a refreshing north-easterly breeze.

Flexible Parking: No marked spots—choose your ideal location for the best views, privacy, and access.

Prime Tourist Access: Centrally located, making day trips to Cairns, the Reef, the Rainforest, Atherton Tablelands, and Chillagoe easy.

Great Connectivity: Reliable phone/TV reception and excellent Wi-Fi.
Privacy & Relaxation: Opt for a secluded or social spot. Enjoy sunsets, starry skies, and relaxing with friends.

Big Rig Friendly: Ample space with no reversing required.

Fishing Dams: Two stocked dams with freshwater fish and Redclaw.

Amenities: Powered sites and a free dump facility for black and grey water disposal

properties.name: Roonga Point
properties.description: Need four wheel drive for access. Free camping on the beach.

properties.name: Birds on Barron
properties.description: The property is on 113 acres and includes an orchard and open spaces. It's  right on the banks of the Barron River and you can choose to pull a park down at the river area, amongst the fruit trees in the orchard or in the open.  There are no marked sites so you're not limited to van size.

properties.name: Lions Park Sunshine Coast Lookout
properties.description:
Buderim Lions Park lookout offers breathtaking panoramic views of the stunning Sunshine Coast in Queensland, Australia. 

Nestled atop the picturesque Buderim Mountain, this lookout provides visitors with a captivating vantage point to admire the region's lush rainforests, rolling hills, and shimmering coastline. 

As you soak in the natural beauty, you'll find it's a perfect spot for serene picnics or simply unwinding amidst nature's splendor. Don't forget your camera to capture the awe-inspiring vistas that this hidden gem has to offer. A visit to Buderim Lions Park lookout promises a peaceful escape and a memorable glimpse into the Sunshine Coast's scenic wonders.

properties.name: Lake Kawana Picnic Area
properties.description:
Two BBQ's with 4 benches under shelter as well. Including bins and water tap. 

Also little outdoor gym. Be sure and clean up your mess, this is a beautiful area and deserves to be kept clean!

properties.name: Horseshoe Bay Camping Area
properties.description:
This site can only be reached by boat. 

Nice camping on the beach along side the National Park on Peel Island with many shady spots all with water views with boat parking out front. The composting toilets are very good not smelly with hand washing tap. Bring your own drinking water. Great place to fish, swim, boat and relax.

Generators and fires not permitted. Bring your own water, rubbish bags and insect repellent.

properties.name: Kenilworth Camping
properties.description:
Our family has operated this property as a dairy farm for over 60 years.

We hope you enjoy the serenity and spectacular scenery which we are blessed with every day, and hope to welcome you back again.

We have some basic guidelines for our guests to follow to ensure a great and safe time is had by all.

We are situated along 5 km of the great Mary River on 580 acres of a working Dairy farm, one of the most beautiful and picturesque of any dairy farm in Qld.

properties.name: Mt Ngungun Summit Track
properties.description:
The Mt Ngungun Summit walking track in Queensland offers an exhilarating hike through lush rainforest and rugged terrain. 

Ascend to the summit on a well-maintained trail, boasting stunning panoramic views of the Glass House Mountains and surrounding landscape. The moderately challenging 2.8-kilometre round trip rewards hikers with breathtaking vistas at the top. 

Don't forget your camera, as the summit is perfect for capturing the beauty of the Australian wilderness. With its accessible location in the Glass House Mountains National Park, Mt Ngungun Summit track is a must-visit for nature enthusiasts and adventure seekers. Remember to wear comfortable shoes, stay hydrated, and follow park guidelines for a memorable Queensland experience.

properties.name: Mission Point Camping Area
properties.description:
Set out in your boat to your secluded camp site with expansive views of the Glass House Mountains. You'll find a relatively protected anchorage with access to great fishing in Pumicestone Passage.

Try your luck at reeling in a flathead, bream, whiting, tailor or mangrove jack in the passage or explore its sheltered waters by canoe or kayak. If you're lucky you may spot a dugong grazing on seagrass beds.

Stroll along the water's edge at low tide to see migratory shorebirds refuelling here during summer before their April departure. You'll also see birds of prey, such as ospreys, sea eagles, and brahminy and whistling kites all year round.

Camping area features: this camping area is accessible by boat only and has relatively protected boat anchorage near the camp sites.

Location: on the western side of Bribie Island overlooking the Pumicestone Passage, with views to the Glass House Mountains.

Access: the camping area can be reached by boat only. The closest boat ramp and vehicle parking is at Donnybrook.

Number of sites:12 numbered sites.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping only.

Camp site surface :sand, dirt, grass.

Facilities: micro flush toilets, screened cold showers, water tap (treat before drinking), picnic tables and fireplaces.

Open fires: allowed (except when fire bans or prohibitions apply) in fire rings only, but fuel stoves recommended.

Generators: not permitted.

Essentials to bring: water for drinking, cooking and washing; gas stoves (preferable) or firewood (such as untreated mill off-cuts not bush wood); rubbish bags; insect repellent. Read more about¬†things to know before you go.

Bookings: book online

properties.name: Captain Billy's Landing Camping Area
properties.description:
The camp sites are on the edge of the beach, and have great views, but are also exposed to the wind. In this region, during the dry season, the trade winds are strong and from the south east, meaning this site can be a bit blowy.

There are 5 camping sites available. It is an open area, with grassed sites and a shelter/picnic table. There are no defined sites, but there is a maximum of 18 people. The camping area can only be reached by four-wheel-drive and off-road camper trailers. 

It is not accessible to caravans or conventional buses.

Access: the camping area can only be reached by four-wheel-drive and off-road camper trailers. It is not accessible to caravans or conventional buses.

Number of sites: open area without separately defined sites, a maximum of eight vehicles and 18 people are allowed at any one time.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car and camper trailers.

Camp site surface: sand.

Facilities: hybrid toilet, individual and communal fire rings, picnic tables and a shelter.

Open fires: allowed (except when fire bans apply) in existing fireplaces only. Do not collect firewood from the national park. Fuel stoves are recommended.

Generators: not permitted.

Essentials to bring: adequate food and drinking water, rubbish bags, insect repellent, screened tents or mosquito nets, fuel stove, adequate fuel and spare parts for your vehicle. Read more about before you visit.

properties.name: Boulia Caravan Park
properties.description: Lots of birds, next to the Burke River. Lots of grass plenty of room for caravans, trailers and tents. Nice town and nice place to stay!

properties.name: Mount Tinbeerwah Lookout
properties.description:
Mount Tinbeerwah Lookout is a scenic viewpoint located in Tewantin National Park, Queensland. It offers stunning panoramic views of the Noosa Hinterland, the Noosa coastline, and the Pacific Ocean. 

The lookout is accessible via a short and easy walk from the Mount Tinbeerwah car park. From the lookout, visitors can enjoy views of the Noosa Hinterland's lush rainforests, rolling hills, and dramatic peaks. They can also see the Noosa coastline's white-sand beaches, turquoise waters, and rocky headlands. On a clear day, it is possible to see all the way to the Sunshine Coast hinterland to the north and the Cooloola Coast to the south.

properties.name: Ilfracombe Caravan Park
properties.description: Ilfracombe Caravan Park is located on the very edge of town, and has lovely powered & unpowered grassed sites, and a number of self contained, air conditioned cabins with ensuites.

properties.name: Ravenshoe Millstream Country Club
properties.description:
Welcome to Ravenshoe Millstream Country Club
First Golf Club in Far North Queensland
A Picturesque 9 Hole Golf Course With Grass Greens

Surrounded by abundant wildlife and birdlife, the Ravenshoe Golf course is one for the bucket list!

Licensed On Premises Bar

Powered & Unpowered Camping Sites Also Available

properties.name: Red Bank Camp Ground
properties.description: This a beautiful free campsite right on the river, just on the edge of the town of Jericho. It has basic but clean facilities. There are flushing toilets, picnic areas and a playground and exercise yard.

properties.name: Kolonga Campground
properties.description: Level sites close to Bruce Highway, fenced property with a few quiet cattle walking around, restrained pets welcome. Sorry rental vehicle & backpackers not accepted! $

properties.name: The Granite Arch Walking Track
properties.description:
The Granite Arch Trail in Girraween National Park offers a captivating natural experience in Australia. 

This short but stunning walk takes you through unique granite rock formations, including a striking archway. The trail showcases the park's distinctive landscape with its massive granite boulders and diverse flora. 

As you hike, you'll be immersed in the beauty of eucalypt forests and may encounter native wildlife. The highlight, the granite arch itself, presents a picturesque frame for photos and a memorable spot to appreciate the park's geological wonders. 

The trail's accessibility and remarkable scenery make it a must-visit destination for nature enthusiasts and hikers seeking a brief yet captivating adventure.

properties.name: The Junction Walking Track
properties.description:
The Junction Trail in Girraween National Park offers a captivating journey through the rugged beauty of the Australian bush. This 150-metre trail showcases the stunning junction of two creeks, with tranquil cascades and rock pools that create a serene atmosphere. Visitors are greeted by towering granite boulders and vibrant vegetation, creating a harmonious blend of nature's elements. 

The trail's easy accessibility makes it suitable for all ages, offering an opportunity to immerse oneself in the unique landscape of the park. As you traverse the well-maintained path, the symphony of birdsong accompanies your exploration, enhancing the peaceful ambiance. 

The Junction Trail provides a brief yet enchanting encounter with the park's geological marvels and natural wonders, making it a must-visit destination for those seeking a glimpse into the pristine wilderness of Girraween National Park.

properties.name: Behana Gorge Walking Track
properties.description:
The Behana Gorge Walking Track is a captivating hike located in Far North Queensland, near the town of Cairns. This scenic trail takes you on a journey through lush rainforest and leads to the breathtaking Behana Gorge. 

The hike begins at the trailhead and meanders through the pristine rainforest, offering opportunities to observe native wildlife and appreciate the diverse plant species that thrive in this tropical environment. Along the way, you'll cross a suspension bridge, adding an adventurous element to the hike. 

The highlight of the Behana Gorge Walking Track is, of course, the gorge itself. Upon reaching the gorge, you'll be rewarded with the sight of a pristine waterfall cascading into a deep, clear pool. This is a great spot for a refreshing swim on a hot day or simply for soaking in the natural beauty. 

The Behana Gorge hike is suitable for hikers of varying skill levels, but it's important to be prepared with appropriate hiking gear, including sturdy footwear and plenty of water.

properties.name: The Gorge Camping Ground
properties.description: This private camping ground is situated about 3k South of Aratula, via Charlwood Road & George Road. Well grassed, level and in a beautiful setting beside a creek this exceptional camping area is suitable for all sizes of caravans and Motorhomes. Shelter sheds; plenty of water, (not suitable for drinking), tables, swimming holes and camp showering facilities are all here.

properties.name: Mount Kelly Lookout
properties.description:
The Mount Kelly Lookout Walk is a short but rewarding hike located in the Burdekin region of Queensland, Australia. The walk starts at the Mount Kelly Lookout car park and winds its way up the hill to the summit, where you are rewarded with stunning views of the surrounding countryside, including the Burdekin River, the Great Barrier Reef, and the Great Dividing Range.

The walk is well-maintained and easy to follow, making it suitable for all fitness levels. The total distance of the walk is approximately 1.6km and it takes around 30 minutes to complete.

properties.name: Running Creek Parklands
properties.description:
Running Creek Parklands is a family owned and operated camping and leisure facility. Find your happy place with us on our 62 acres of secluded bush land just out side of the beautiful and historic country town of Woodford, and nestled at the base of the glorious Bellthorpe Range. 

Our family has always been passionate about family time, making memories, and getting out into nature. We have brought all these things together to create a wonderful eco friendly place for people of all ages to come and enjoy the world around us. We have our very own Running Creek that meanders through the property, its perfect to let the kids come down and play in the shallows or go for a big dip in one of the many large swimming holes. We are proud to be a dog and horse friendly parklands, conditions do apply so let us know if you would like to bring your furry friends!

properties.name: Ellinjaa Falls
properties.description: Ellinjaa Falls, located in the Wet Tropics of Queensland, Australia, is a breathtaking natural wonder. With its stunning 20-metre plunge into a crystal-clear pool, it's a serene oasis within a lush rainforest. A short walk through pristine surroundings offers visitors a tranquil spot to admire the falls' mesmerizing beauty and capture memorable photographs.

properties.name: Yowie Park
properties.description: Yowie Park is a must see when you visit Kilcoy. Drop into the Kilcoy Visitor Information Centre to find out more about Kilcoy and the Yowie.

properties.name: Wooroolin Wetland
properties.description:
Wooroolin Wetland, nestled in the heart of Queensland, Australia, is a serene natural oasis waiting to be explored. 

Spanning across lush, verdant landscapes, this wetland is a haven for wildlife enthusiasts and nature lovers. Its tranquil waters mirror the surrounding eucalyptus trees, offering a picturesque backdrop for birdwatching and wildlife spotting. 

You'll have the chance to encounter a diverse array of native bird species, including the iconic Australian pelican and the graceful black swan. Take a leisurely stroll along well-maintained boardwalks, and immerse yourself in the soothing sounds of nature.

properties.name: Wild Horse Mountain Lookout
properties.description:
The Wild Horse Mountain lookout is in Beerburrum State Forest, east of the Bruce Highway/M1. This walk starts at the southern end of the car park up the cement road, and all the way up to the top, approximately 700m one way. 

You'll walk past casuarinas, grass trees and eucalypts. On your way you might be lucky to see kookaburras, wagtails and dragonflies.

properties.name: Warner Bros Movie World
properties.description: Become lost in a world of fantasy and fun, meet your favourite stars and super-heroes and experience the exhilaration of world-class adventure rides and movie attractions at Warner Bros. Movie World.

properties.name: TYTO Wetlands
properties.description:
TYTO Wetlands is a 120-hectare rehabilitated wetland area located on the outskirts of Ingham, Queensland, Australia. It is home to a diverse range of flora and fauna, including over 240 species of birds (27.4% of Australia's bird species in one location) and many Agile Wallabies.
The wetlands were originally drained for agriculture in the early 1900s, but they were restored in the 1990s to create a habitat for wildlife. The wetlands are now a popular tourist destination, and they offer a variety of activities for visitors

properties.name: Texas Rabbit Factory
properties.description: The historic Texas Rabbit Works, includes the Riverside Freezing Works, brings to life a very important era in the history of Texas and Australia. During the 1930s the Texas Rabbit Works employed 30 men and exported three tons of rabbit meat a week to England. The industry was credited with saving the Queensland town during the depression years. The works closed in 1992. The rabbit industry in 1929 was the largest employer in Australia.

properties.name: Somerset Dam
properties.description:
Somerset Dam is a large earthfill dam located on the Stanley River, approximately 75 kilometres west of Ipswich, Queensland, Australia. It is the largest water storage impoundment in the Lockyer Valley catchment and provides water for irrigation, drinking, and environmental purposes.

The dam was constructed in the 1930s and was completed in 1942. It is 305 meters long and 41 meters high, and has a storage capacity of 203 gigalitres. Water babies - grab your gear and get moving to Somerset Dam. Approximately one hour from Brisbane in Kilcoy Shire, and neatly cradled by a ring of surrounding hills, conditions there are perfect for water skiing, wake-boarding, sailing and fishing.

properties.name: The Ken Burgess Orchid House
properties.description:
Ken Burgess Orchid House is a beautiful and serene oasis in the heart of Mackay, Queensland, Australia. The Orchid House is home to a stunning collection of over 600 varieties of orchids, including exotic and Australian native species.

The Ken Burgess Orchid House is set in a lush, tropical rainforest environment, with towering palms and cascading waterfalls. Visitors can wander through the winding pathways and admire the orchids in bloom, each one more unique and beautiful than the last.

The Ken Burgess Orchid House is a popular tourist destination, but it is also a popular spot for locals to relax and enjoy the natural beauty. There are several seating areas throughout the Ken Burgess Orchid House where visitors can sit and enjoy a peaceful moment.

The Ken Burgess Orchid House is open year-round, but the best time to visit is during the spring and summer months when the orchids are in full bloom.

properties.name: Pepina Falls
properties.description: Pepina Falls, nestled in Queensland's Wooroonooran National Park, Australia, is a tranquil oasis for nature enthusiasts. This picturesque waterfall features a graceful 15-metre drop into a pristine pool, set amidst lush rainforest. A short walk through the verdant surroundings leads to a serene viewing area, making it a serene and photogenic destination.

properties.name: Pandanus Creek walking track
properties.description:
The Pandanus Creek Track walk is a beautiful and easy 2-kilometre return walk located in Byfield National Park, Queensland, Australia. The track winds through lush pandanus forest and along the banks of Pandanus Creek, offering stunning views of the rainforest and the surrounding countryside.

The track is well-maintained and suitable for all ages and fitness levels. There are several interpretive signs along the way that provide information about the local flora and fauna.

The walk begins at the Pandanus Creek campground and follows the creek upstream. The track passes through several pandanus groves, where visitors can admire the unique and beautiful pandanus trees. The track also passes through several rainforest areas, where visitors can see a variety of other plants and animals, including birds, butterflies, and snakes.

The track ends at a small waterfall, where visitors can stop and enjoy the scenery. There are also several swimming holes along the track, where visitors can cool off on a hot day.

The Pandanus Creek Track walk is a great way to experience the beauty of Byfield National Park. The track is easy to follow and offers stunning views of the rainforest and the surrounding countryside.

properties.name: Outback Stockman's Show
properties.description: This live Outback Stockman's show tells the story of real life stockmen and women who work on the land. It encompasses the modern-day aspects of being a stockman, as well as telling the tales of what it used to be like in the past.

properties.name: Ottaba Llamas
properties.description: Discover the beautiful Brisbane Valley region with our unique llama walks! Walk the Rail Trail at Ottaba or do our Llama and Lattes walk at Esk .

properties.name: Mystery Craters
properties.description:
Visiting the Mystery Craters is a journey of discovery! Halfway between Bundaberg and Gin Gin is Australia's most baffling phenomenon. Since their discovery in 1971, the origins of the 35 oddly shaped craters have remained the subject of controversy. 

The mottled mixture of sandstone and ochre stain have been the subject of many investigations and various theories have been offered.

properties.name: Mt Hypipamee Crater and Dinner Falls
properties.description: The Mt Hypipamee Crater and Dinner Falls walk is a captivating hiking experience in Queensland, Australia. This trail winds through lush rainforests, leading to the mesmerizing Mt Hypipamee Crater, a perfectly circular volcanic sinkhole. Nearby, Dinner Falls adds to the enchantment with its cascading beauty, making it a memorable nature adventure.

properties.name: Mossman Gorge
properties.description:
Mossman Gorge is a beautiful rainforest located in the Daintree Rainforest. It is one of the oldest rainforests in the world and is home to a variety of unique flora and fauna.
The rainforest is lush and green and the Mossman River is crystal clear. There are a number of walking trails that wind through the rainforest, offering stunning views of the surrounding scenery.
Mossman Gorge is home to a variety of unique wildlife, including the cassowary, the southern cassowary, the northern bettong, and the Lumholtz's tree-kangaroo. You may even be lucky enough to spot a platypus in the Mossman River.

properties.name: Maryboroughs Water Hole
properties.description: Maryborough's Glory Hole is now a featured part of the Ululah Lagoon which is surrounded by a walk and cycle path which is also frequently in use by the abundant Fraser Coast wildlife. It is believed to have been built as early as the 1880s.

properties.name: Mary Cairncross Scenic Reserve
properties.description: Mary Cairncross Scenic Reserve comprises 55 hectares of National Estate listed subtropical rainforest overlooking the Glasshouse Mountains. A remnant of the rainforests that once covered the Blackall Range, the Reserve is a living museum of diverse plant and animal life

properties.name: Maheno Shipwreck
properties.description: The Maheno, the most famous of the Fraser Island wrecks, was driven ashore just north of Happy Valley during a cyclone in 1935. Once a well-known trans-Tasman liner, the Maheno was bound for a Japanese wrecking yard when she met her stormy end.

properties.name: Mackenzie Park
properties.description: Mackenzie Park is home to a rare tree that is only found in the Duaringa township. The Duaringa Stringy Bark, known to the Aboriginals as 'Budgeroo', grows up to 10 metres tall and has bushy foliage with small white flowers that bloom in spring.

properties.name: Lamberts Lookout
properties.description:
Lambert's Lookout, perched atop a rugged cliff, provides awe-inspiring vistas of nature's grandeur. Located in a remote wilderness area, this viewpoint offers a breathtaking panoramic view of rolling hills, dense forests, and distant mountain ranges. 

The sheer drop beneath the lookout adds an exhilarating sense of adventure, making it a favorite spot for hikers and photographers. Lambert's Lookout is a captivating escape for those seeking unparalleled natural beauty and a thrilling sense of elevation.

properties.name: Lake MacKenzie Fraser island
properties.description: Lake McKenzie (also known as Boorangoora) is a perched lake located on Fraser Island, Queensland, Australia. It is one of the most popular tourist destinations on the island, known for its crystal-clear water and pure white sand.

properties.name: Josephine Falls
properties.description:
Josephine Falls is a beautiful waterfall located in Wooroonooran National Park, Queensland, Australia. 

The falls are a popular spot for swimming, picnicking, and bushwalking. 

There are two main walking trails to the falls: the Upper Circuit and the Lower Circuit. The Upper Circuit is a 1.2-kilometer loop track that takes you to the top of the falls. The Lower Circuit is a 2.4-kilometer loop track that takes you to the bottom of the falls.

Both tracks are well-maintained and offer stunning views of the falls and the surrounding rainforest. The Upper Circuit is a bit more challenging than the Lower Circuit, but it is worth it for the views.

properties.name: Isla Gorge National Park Walk
properties.description:
The Isla Gorge National Park walk is a 9-kilometre loop trail that takes you through the heart of the park. The trail starts at the visitor centre and winds its way through the bush, past towering trees and lush ferns. You'll cross several creeks and have the opportunity to spot a variety of wildlife, including kangaroos, emus, and lizards.

The highlight of the walk is the section that follows the edge of the gorge. Here, you'll be treated to stunning views of the 500-meter-deep canyon, as well as the surrounding countryside.

The Isla Gorge National Park walk is a great way to experience the natural beauty of the park. It is suitable for all fitness levels and can be completed in 3-4 hours.

properties.name: Inkerman Hill
properties.description:
Inkerman Hill is a scenic lookout located in Home Hill, Queensland, Australia. It offers panoramic views of the surrounding countryside, including the Burdekin River and the Great Barrier Reef.

The hill is accessible by car and there is a small parking area at the top. There is also a walking track that leads to the lookout, which takes about 15 minutes to walk.

properties.name: Cane Cutter Monuments
properties.description:
In the township of Home Hill, there are two monuments respresenting the Australian sugar cane industry history. Located on the Bruce Highway, near the Lions Park and Home Hill Diorama, is a wooden carving of a hand cane cutter which was carved by chainsaw at the 2021 Sweet Days Hot Nights Festival by artist Matty George. 

Another, two hand cane cutter sculptures are located at the Home Hill Showgrounds which represent the multicultural history of the sugar industry in the Burdekin. Completed in May 2016, the local Gudjuda Reference Group Aboriginal Corporation's indigenous artists were mentored by Dr Farvardin Daliri OAM in designing, constructing and painting the sculptures. 

The sculptures are 3.5 metres high and 20 tonnes heavy, and are made from steel and cement.

properties.name: Great Sandy Biosphere Reserve
properties.description: The Great Sandy Biosphere Reserve is a UNESCO-designated biosphere reserve located in the Southeast Queensland Bioregion of eastern Australia. It is renowned for its cultural and ecological significance, and contains the Great Sandy Strait, a Ramsar-listed wetland, and Fraser Island, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The reserve incorporates the largest sand island and coastal sand mass in the world.

properties.name: Francis Hotel Thallon
properties.description:
Eat and drink where the locals do! The Francis Hotel Thallon is a friendly, country pub where you can enjoy a cold beer, great meals and stay a while in clean, budget accommodation. 

The Dining Room is open for family friendly meals seven days a week for lunch and dinner. Breakfast is available for Hotel guests o...

properties.name: Fossilised Forrest Sculptures
properties.description: Created by Antone Bruinsma, the Fossilised Forest sculptures celebrates the Alpha areas rich collections of fossilised wood. Antone's sculptures reflect the treasures and mysteries of the ancient fossilised materials, which reveal a glimpse into prehistoric life.

properties.name: Finch Hatton Gorge Walk
properties.description:
The Finch Hatton Gorge Walk is a 2.8-kilometre return walk that takes you through a beautiful sub-tropical rainforest. The walk starts at the Finch Hatton picnic area and follows a path that winds through the rainforest, past granite boulders, and waterfalls. The highlight of the walk is the Araluen Falls, a 30-metre waterfall that plunges into a rock pool. The pool is a popular spot for swimming, but be careful as the water can be cold. 

The walk is open all year round, but it is best to avoid visiting during wet weather, as the path can be muddy.

properties.name: Eungella Dam
properties.description: Eungella Dam is a scenic lake fringed by rainforest, the ideal spot for boating and skiing with peaceful natural surrounds. It is located in the Eungella Range, approximately 60 kilometres west of Mackay, Queensland, Australia. The dam was constructed in 1969 to supply water for irrigation and town water supply. It has a storage capacity of 112,400 megalitres and a surface area of 848 hectares.

properties.name: Eumundi Markets
properties.description:
The Eumundi Market is Australia's biggest and best art, craft and produce market.

It's held every Saturday and Wednesday of the year (rain, hail or shine) in the heart of the charming historic hinterland town of Eumundi.

properties.name: Double Island Point
properties.description:
Double Island Point is a beautiful and rugged headland located on the Sunshine Coast of Queensland, Australia. It is the northernmost point of Double Island, a 25-kilometre-long sand island that separates the Coral Sea from the Cooloola Coast.

Double Island Point is known for its stunning scenery, including its dramatic cliffs, white sand beaches, and clear blue waters. The point is also home to a variety of wildlife, including whales, dolphins, turtles, and seabirds.

properties.name: Deon's Lookout
properties.description:
Deon's Lookout is a popular tourist destination located in the Diamantina region of Queensland. It is situated on the Diamantina Development Road, approximately 50 kilometres east of Betoota. 

The lookout offers stunning views of the surrounding countryside, including the Diamantina River, the Channel Country, and the Simpson Desert. On a clear day, you can see for miles in every direction. 

Deon's Lookout is a great place to stop and break your journey while traveling through the Diamantina region. It is also a popular spot for birdwatching, photography, and simply enjoying the peace and quiet of the Australian outback.

properties.name: Darling Downs Zoo
properties.description: Come face-to-face with some of the world's most amazing animals at the family owned Darling Downs Zoo. Located just two hours from Brisbane, this family-friendly zoo is home to over 1,000 animals from Africa, South America, South-east Asia, and Australia. See lions, tigers, giraffes, elephants, and more in their natural habitats. Take a behind-the-scenes tour, feed the animals, or even go on a night safari.

properties.name: Curtain Fig Tree
properties.description: Curtain Fig National Park is home to the world-famous Curtain Fig Tree, an enormous strangler fig tree that is over 500 years old. Located a short drive out of Yungaburra, a small town in the Atherton Tableland of Queensland, Australia, the giant tree has several aerial roots hanging down from its branches that look like curtains.

properties.name: Coongarra Rock
properties.description:
Coongarra Rock is a significant Aboriginal cultural site located in the Kimberley region of Western Australia. It is a large sandstone rock formation that is covered in Aboriginal rock art. The rock art is estimated to be over 20,000 years old and depicts a variety of subjects, including animals, people, and ceremonies. 

Coongarra Rock is a sacred place to the Aboriginal people of the Kimberley region. It is a place where they have gathered for thousands of years to learn about their culture and to connect with their ancestors.

properties.name: Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mount Coot-tha
properties.description: The Brisbane Botanic Gardens Mount Coot-tha are recognised as Queensland's premier subtropical botanic gardens. They are a key attraction in the Brisbane City Council Mt Coot-tha precinct. Founded in 1970 and officially opened in 1976, the 56-hectare gardens open daily from 8am-6pm in summer (September to March) and 8am-5pm in winter (April to August). Entry to the gardens is free. Dogs are not permitted at any time (except for guide and assistance dogs) to protect the gardens and native wildlife.
