properties.fees: Fees apply, must book before arrival via QLD gov website

properties.name: Goldsborough Valley Campground
properties.description:
Goldsborough Valley camping area features a shady camping area adjacent to the Mulgrave River with fire ring and toilet facilities.

Camping area features: shady camping area adjacent to the Mulgrave River with fire ring and toilet facilities.

Location: past the day-use area, over the causeway.

Access: the camping area can be reached by conventional vehicle with care.

Number of sites: There are 12 numbered sites. Vegetated alcoves provide some separation between some sites. NOTE: There is also a large open area that can accommodate 5 groups.

Camp site surface: grass and dirt.

Facilities: flush and composting toilets and individual fire rings.

Open fires: allowed (except when fire bans or restrictions apply) in fire rings only. Firewood is not provided and must not be collected from the park. Fuel stoves are recommended.

Generators: not permitted.

Essentials to bring: drinking water, firewood, rubbish bags and insect repellent.

A camping permit is required.

properties.name: Jimna Base Camp
properties.description: Pre booking essential. Phone 0417 756 876  weekend camping coffee, cold drinks, Icecreams and bagged ice available weekends only

properties.name: Toowoomba Showgrounds
properties.description: Two people with power in caravan 25 AUD per night. A lot of space and clean toilets with hot showers. Cash collected in the evenings.

properties.name: Mount Alexandra Lookout
properties.description:
Mount Alexandra Lookout is a popular tourist destination in the Daintree Rainforest, Queensland, Australia. It is located on the Alexandra Range and offers stunning panoramic views of the rainforest, the Daintree River, and the Coral Sea.

On a clear day, visitors to Mount Alexandra Lookout can see for miles in every direction. To the north, they can see the coastline of Cape Tribulation and the Great Barrier Reef. To the south, they can see the rainforest-covered mountains of the Atherton Tablelands. And to the east, they can see the Daintree River winding its way through the rainforest.

properties.name: Kilcoy Showgrounds
properties.description:
Situated just 2.7 km from Kilcoy town center, the Kilcoy Showground offers an affordable camping option in the Somerset region, owned and managed by the Somerset Regional Council. The showground features grassy sites with power and water, suitable for camper trailers, caravans, motorhomes, and big rigs. A maximum stay of seven days is permitted.

Facilities include toilets, showers, bins, and a dump point. A caretaker is on-site, and camping fees can be paid by cash or card. The site is pet-friendly, requiring dogs to be leashed, but is closed during events.

properties.name: Deepwater Hideaway Bush Camp Stay
properties.description: Bush Camp Stay peaceful, quiet, relaxing & pet friendly

properties.name: Hell's Gate Sea Turtle Watching
properties.description:
Perfect place to watch sea turtles in wildlife. You just have to go the coastal walk until Hell's Gates. 

There you have to watch the sea between the cliffs. The turtles will come to the surface every 5 minutes to catch breath. 

Best time to see is when it's sunny, so you can see them before they coming up to the surface. All you have to bring is patience.

properties.name: Lake Maroon Camping Ground
properties.description: Located approximately one and a half hour's drive from Brisbane or the Gold Coast, the Lake Maroon Camping Ground is a unique family fun destination. The Lake Maroon Camping Ground is located 20kms south of Boonah, and is situated in the heart of the Great South East Scenic Rim and is located right on the Maroon Dam. The park descends down the mountains to the lake edge of the Maroon Dam, thus providing guests with a variety of bush scenery, wild-life and magnificent views, and a wide variety of water based activities. Lake Maroon is rated as one of Australia's best bass fishing dams.

properties.name: Cardwell Spa Pool
properties.description:
The Cardwell Spa Pool, located in Queensland, Australia, is a natural wonder renowned for its unique blend of freshwater and seawater. 

Nestled within the coastal rainforest, this picturesque pool offers a soothing and refreshing experience for visitors. The crystal-clear waters are fed by underground springs, creating a delightful mix of temperatures perfect for relaxation. 

Surrounded by lush greenery and teeming with native wildlife, the Cardwell Spa Pool is a tranquil oasis where visitors can immerse themselves in the serenity of nature while enjoying a natural spa-like experience.

properties.name: Trinity Bay Lookout
properties.description:
Trinity Bay Lookout is a popular tourist destination in Port Douglas, Queensland, Australia. It is located on Flagstaff Hill and offers stunning panoramic views of Trinity Bay, the Four Mile Beach, and the Coral Sea.

On a clear day, you can see for miles in every direction, taking in the turquoise waters of Trinity Bay, the lush green rainforest, and the white sand beaches. You can also spot a variety of marine life, including dolphins, turtles, and whales.

properties.name: Croydon Rodeo Showgrounds
properties.description: $2.50 per person hot showers large camping area.

properties.name: Moura Rotary Park
properties.description:
Rotary Park offers affordable camping in Moura, in the Banana Shire. A large parkland on the Dawson Highway suitable for caravans.

Camping at the Rotary Park has a total of 15 unpowered sites with a maximum of 3 nights stay. The amenities include toilets, showers (cold water), portable water, barbeques, and picnic tables. Campfires are allowed in fire rings provided. However, please check local fire bans rules. Pets are allowed on the premises, conditions apply.

Please note, there are no flushing toilets available. There is also a dump point located offsite, but nearby to the Rotary Park.

properties.name: Mt. Baldy & Yabi Walk
properties.description: The Mt. Baldy & Yabi Walk presents an exhilarating trek for nature enthusiasts. This trail winds through pristine wilderness, ascending to the summit of Mt. Baldy, offering panoramic vistas of rugged landscapes. Descending to the Yabi Gorge, hikers can enjoy the tranquil beauty of cascading waterfalls and lush greenery, creating a memorable outdoor adventure.

properties.name: Purling Brook Falls
properties.description:
Tucked away in Springbrook National Park in Queensland, a 4km walk will take you to the Purling Brook Falls.

The well-maintained Purling Brook Falls Circuit meanders through lush subtropical rainforest as the trail unveils panoramic vistas and diverse flora. 

You'll traverse suspension bridges that sway gently above the canyon, providing thrilling perspectives of the verdant landscape. Immerse yourself in the harmonious blend of vibrant foliage, the soothing melody of bird calls, and the invigorating mist from the falls

The cascading waters of Purling Brook Falls plunge 109 meters into a lush gorge, create a quite spectacle.

properties.name: Laguna Lookout
properties.description: Laguna Lookout is a scenic viewpoint located in Noosa National Park, Queensland. It offers stunning panoramic views of Laguna Bay, Noosa's main beach, and the surrounding coastline. The lookout is accessible via a short walk from the Laguna Bay car park. From the lookout, visitors can enjoy views of Laguna Bay's calm waters, rocky coastline, and lush native bush. On a clear day, it is possible to see all the way to the Noosa River mouth to the north and the Noosa Hinterland to the west.

properties.name: Bustard Bay Lookout
properties.description: Bustard Bay Lookout, situated in the charming coastal town of Seventeen Seventy in Queensland, Australia, is a scenic beach boasting around 500 meters of pristine golden sand.

properties.name: Mt Larcom Walking Trail
properties.description:
The Mt Larcom Walking Trail is a 12-kilometre loop trail that takes you to the summit of Mt Larcom, a 753-metre mountain. The trail is rated as Grade 4, challenging, and it is steep and strenuous in some sections. 

The hike starts at the Mt Larcom picnic area and winds its way through a forest of eucalypt trees. The trail then climbs steeply up the side of the mountain, offering stunning views of the surrounding countryside.

properties.name: Henry Ross Lookout
properties.description:
Henry Ross Lookout is a popular tourist destination in Cairns, Queensland It is located on the Kuranda Range Road, approximately 10 kilometres from the city center, and offers stunning views of Cairns, the Coral Sea, and the surrounding rainforest. The lookout is named after Henry Ross, who was the foreman in charge of building the Kuranda Range Road in the 1930s. The road was built to provide access to the Atherton Tablelands, and Henry Ross Lookout was one of the many viewpoints that were constructed along the way.

Today, Henry Ross Lookout is a popular spot for visitors to Cairns to enjoy the views. The lookout is also a popular spot for locals to picnic, have a barbecue, or simply relax and enjoy the fresh air.

properties.name: Wyper Park Scout Camp
properties.description: Great camp site... Vans, rv's, tents, 5 acres of Bush 15 km South of Bundaberg. Very level site. Hot showers and flushing toilets, can have a fire but need a bin that won't burn the grass. Plenty of shade.

properties.name: Indian Head Lookout
properties.description:
Indian Head Lookout on Fraser Island, Australia, offers breathtaking panoramic views of the island's coastline and the surrounding turquoise waters of the Coral Sea. Perched atop a towering sandstone cliff, it's a perfect spot to spot marine life like sharks, rays, and migrating whales. 

The short hike to the lookout takes you through stunning landscapes, making it a must-visit destination for nature enthusiasts and photographers.

properties.name: Hann River Roadhouse
properties.description: Plenty of room in the campground which is close to the river. Bush shower. Food and petrol available

properties.name: Mount Cooroora Walk
properties.description:
The Mount Cooroora Walk in Pomona, Queensland is a challenging yet rewarding hiking adventure. This iconic peak is known for its distinctive pyramid shape and stands as a prominent landmark in the region. The hike takes you through lush rainforest and, as you ascend, offers panoramic views of the surrounding landscape. 

The summit provides a spectacular vantage point, making it a favorite among outdoor enthusiasts and photographers. The Mount Cooroora Walk is a test of endurance, offering a thrilling experience and a sense of accomplishment as you conquer this natural wonder in the Noosa Hinterland.

properties.name: Farmways Caravan Park
properties.description: A budget park that is quiet and clean with friendly, helpful owners

properties.name: Pentland Hotel
properties.description:
We offer free, unpowered camping sites at the Pentland Hotel. Park your caravan up or pitch your tent and come inside to say hello. Maybe even have a meal, enjoy a beer in the beer garden, or play a game of pool.



There is lots of camping space in front of the stables at the back of the pub, but you are also able to park on the land behind the stables. There is a small gate near the mango tree, which is a short cut through to the pub and amenities.







The ground is flat and there are some shaded spots. There is room for the biggest rigs like imported fifth wheelers.



It's easily accessible, but back from the main road so away from a lot of the noise and you get a great view of the sunset in the evening.



We are pet-friendly.



Toilets and hot showers are available 24 hours. We just ask that you pay $3 at the bar for the shower.

We also have motel rooms available.

properties.name: Mungalli Falls
properties.description:
Mungalli Falls, located in North Queensland, Australia, is a hidden gem among rainforest landscapes. With a picturesque 90-metre drop, it's a breathtaking spectacle. 

A short hike through lush greenery leads to a viewing platform, allowing visitors to immerse themselves in the serenity and natural beauty of these cascading falls.

properties.name: Nandroya Falls
properties.description:
Nandroya Falls is a 50-meter high waterfall that drops into a deep pool below. The water is crystal clear and refreshing, and it is a great place to swim on a hot day. There are also plenty of rocks to sit on and relax, and to enjoy the views of the waterfall and the surrounding rainforest.

The best way to get to Nandroya Falls is to hike the Nandroya Falls Circuit Track. The track is a 4-kilometre loop that takes about 2 hours to complete. The track is well-maintained and easy to follow, but there are a few steep sections.

properties.name: Duaringa Hotel and Caravan Park
properties.description:
Duaringa Hotel provides accommodation along with overnight camping for customers, in a large grassy area behind the pub. 

Power is available for $15.00

properties.name: Ravenswood Showground Campground
properties.description:
Ravenswood recreation park / showground. Caretaker on site to take payment. Clean amenities. Shady sites.

Maximum stay 7 days

Powered & unpowered sites

To make a booking or check availability, please contact Council's Caretaker, Mr Woody Pigram, on phone 07 4770 2113.

properties.name: Mount Isa Lookout
properties.description: The Mount Isa Lookout has a good vantage point to take in great views over the surrounding outback landscape. Situated atop a hill, visitors can see mining town of Mount Isa, capturing a glimpse of its industrial and natural beauty, making it a must-visit destination. 360-degree panorama of the city and mine area.

properties.name: Innot Hot Springs Leisure and Camping Park
properties.description: 40$ per night on a powered site includes using the 6 pools with various temperatures of the hot springs water

properties.name: Monto Self Contained 72 Hr Stopover
properties.description: Caretaker on site $5.00 a night

properties.name: Mapleton Falls Lookout
properties.description: Next to the carpark, this wheelchair-accessible lookout provides spectacular views over the Obi Obi valley and the rainforest canopy below. Look for Australian peregrine falcons, which often soar and roost near Mapleton Falls' cliff edges during August and September.

properties.name: Fordsdale Farmstay
properties.description:
Fordsdale Farmstay offers a peaceful retreat on 1,000 acres of tranquil bushland and grazing plateaus, perfect for bush camping. Choose from a variety of spots, whether nestled along Ma Ma Creek or in the scenic hills. This property is ideal for tents and camper trailers, though please note we do not have powered sites. 

Guests have access to shower and toilet facilities, and there’s plenty of space for families and friends to spread out and enjoy the serenity. To maintain a peaceful environment, especially for the many families with young children who visit, we kindly ask that you leave motorbikes at home. 

Family dogs are welcome but must be supervised due to the presence of livestock. Horse owners can bring their horses and explore the property or ride along the Bicentennial National Trail.

properties.name: The Pyramid Walking Track
properties.description:
The Pyramid track is accessed from the Granite Arch track, about 500m from the Bald Rock Creek day-use area. The first part of the walk is fairly easy, crossing the creek by bridge and winding through pleasant bushland. 

When the track reaches the base of The Pyramid, it becomes quite steep - with lots of stairs and it can be hard going. The track reaches the tree-line and continues upwards across the steep, exposed rock faces of the granite dome. Be extremly carefull as there is no handrail.

properties.name: Port of Hay Point Lookout
properties.description:
Perched atop the Port Administration building in Hay Point, Australia, the Port of Hay Point Lookout offers visitors a fascinating glimpse into the country's coal industry. 

From the lookout, visitors can enjoy panoramic views of the two coal terminals at the port, as well as the ships that arrive and depart with their loads of coal.

properties.name: Platypus Viewpoint
properties.description:
The Platypus Viewpoint is a short walk from the Broken River car park in Eungella National Park, Queensland, Australia. It is a popular spot for spotting platypus, as the viewing platform overlooks a section of the Broken River where the platypus are known to feed. The best time to visit the Platypus Viewpoint is during the early morning or late evening, when the platypus are most active. However, you can also spot them during the day, especially if it is a cloudy day. 

To see platypus, you will need to be patient and quiet. The platypus are shy creatures and will quickly disappear if they feel disturbed.

properties.name: Mossman Gorge Centre
properties.description: Mossman Gorge Centre is an award-winning ecotourism facility located at the entrance to the World Heritage listed Daintree Rainforest. It offers a variety of activities and experiences, including guided walks, cultural tours, and rainforest dining. Visitors can learn about the Kuku Yalanji culture and history, and experience the beauty of the Daintree Rainforest.

properties.name: Millaa Millaa Falls
properties.description: Millaa Millaa Falls, nestled in the Atherton Tablelands of Queensland, Australia, is a captivating natural wonder. With a 18-metre plunge into a pristine pool, it's a serene oasis surrounded by lush rainforest. The falls' timeless beauty has made them a sought-after location for photography and a tranquil spot for cooling off on hot day

properties.name: Lake Monduran
properties.description:
Lake Monduran is a reservoir located in the Bundaberg Region of Queensland, Australia. It is the largest artificial lake in the state, and it is a popular spot for fishing, boating, and waterskiing. 

The lake was created in 1978 by the construction of the Fred Haigh Dam across the Kolan River. The dam is used to provide water for irrigation and drinking water, and it also helps to control flooding.

properties.name: Hummock Lookout
properties.description:
The Hummock Lookout is a popular lookout in the Bundaberg region of Queensland, Australia. It is located on the remains of a small basaltic volcano that was active over a million years ago. The lookout offers stunning views of the surrounding countryside, including the city of Bundaberg, the Bargara coastline, and the Fraser Island World Heritage Area. 

The Hummock Lookout is also a significant Aboriginal cultural site. The Taribelang Bunda people, the traditional custodians of the land, called the Hummock "Woongarra", which means "burning mountain". They believed that the Hummock was a sacred place where the spirits of their ancestors lived. 

Today, the Hummock Lookout is a popular spot for picnics, walks, and birdwatching. It is also a great place to learn about the region's Aboriginal history and culture.

properties.name: Airlie Creek Short walk
properties.description: Airlie Creek Track is a picturesque walking trail nestled in Airlie Beach, Queensland, Australia. Stretching over 850 metres, it meanders through lush rainforests, across wooden boardwalks, and leads to a captivating natural rock pool called Cedar Creek Falls. Walking time: allow one hour. Access: from Waterson Way, Airlie Beach.

properties.name: Mistake Creek
properties.description: Free camp on creek not suitable if wet

properties.name: Higher Ground Farm Stay
properties.description: Self contained vehicles only with no facilities. Hosts are excellent!

properties.name: Mt. Beerwah Summit Track
properties.description:
The Mount Beerwah Summit Walking Track in Queensland offers an exhilarating adventure for nature enthusiasts. 

This challenging hike leads you through lush rainforest and rocky terrain, ultimately culminating in breathtaking panoramic views from the summit. 

Towering at 556 metres, Mount Beerwah rewards your efforts with stunning vistas of the Glass House Mountains and the Sunshine Coast hinterland. The ascent requires a good level of fitness and agility, with some steep sections and rock scrambling. It's essential to come prepared with sturdy footwear, plenty of water, and a sense of adventure. 

This track promises an unforgettable experience for those seeking a thrilling outdoor excursion in Queensland's natural beauty.

properties.name: Platypus Deck
properties.description:
Platypus Deck is a popular tourist destination located in Malanda, Queensland, Australia. It is a platform that extends over the Russell River, offering visitors a unique opportunity to see platypuses in their natural habitat.

Platypuses are shy creatures, so it can be difficult to see them in the wild. Platypus Deck provides visitors with a chance to see platypuses up close, without disturbing their environment.

properties.name: Kenilworth Campsite
properties.description:
We are a small scale simple campground set in beautiful surrounds. Space, tranquility and privacy are core values that we endeavour to foster. The surrounding villages, markets, artisans and producers make for endless opportunities while the setting is as far away from the hustle and bustle as you would like.

 

There are camp sites  suitable for couples to larger groups with each being idyllically located on a bend of a beautiful clear creek with abundant swimming holes and fish.

properties.name: Bribie Island Caravan Park
properties.description: Bribie Island Caravan Park

properties.name: Jourama Falls Track
properties.description:
Jourama Falls, nestled within Queensland, Australia's Paluma Range National Park, is a captivating natural wonder. 

These falls cascade gracefully down rugged cliffs, creating a picturesque oasis in the midst of lush rainforest. The pristine waters flow over tiered rock formations, forming crystal-clear pools that invite visitors to cool off in their refreshing embrace. 

A well-maintained hiking trail offers a moderately challenging trek through the tropical wilderness, rewarding adventurers with breathtaking vistas and a chance to witness the diverse local flora and fauna.

properties.name: Canungra showground
properties.description: Nice quiet place. Close to the creek. Peaceful place. They got a rodeo range here.

properties.name: Homestead Caravan Park
properties.description:
Homestead Caravan Park is a spacious 7 acre park, situated in Nanango, Queensland, just off the D’Aguilar Highway, where the only noises you hear are the birds and the sounds of nature. It is a quiet friendly park for the whole family.

We are situated with easy access to the town centre, restaurants and local attractions.

properties.name: Mt Nimmel Lodge Campground
properties.description:
Welcome to Mt Nimmel Lodge Campground. We are a privately owned, family operated campground on 67 acres of Gold Coast Hinterland.  
 (**CASH ONLY**)

properties.name: Critters Camp
properties.description: Truck stopping bay with some space between the railway and the street. No facilities and any other comfort.

properties.name: Myella Farmstay
properties.description: Lovely Farmstay with the friendliest hosts ever! They offer Horse & Motorbike Riding, 4WDriving and much more plus they have a big swimming pool, offer (really delicious) dinner & brekkies, have baby kangaroos that you can pet... Just an awesome place to stay! They have cabins but also offer Camping for just $15/pp including hot showers. However anything else like the riding & washing has to be paid in addition. Best if you can stay for more than one night because it's just really nice & there's a lot to do.

properties.name: Meunga Creek Caravan Park
properties.description: Basic caravan park with toilets & hot showers. Just a 3 min drive to a supermarket & a bottle shop and 4 minutes to Cardwell. There's a big grassy green camping area and drinking water taps next to nearly every site.

properties.name: Natural Bridge Glowworm Circuit
properties.description:
This circuit walk is in the Natural Bridge section of Springbrook National Park. Dominating the Gold Coast's western skyline, Springbrook's cool forests and mountain streams offer views of impressive landscapes and walks among subtropical and temperate rainforest, open eucalypt forest and montane heath. The park is part of the Gondwana Rainforests of Australia World Heritage Area.

A sealed circuit track takes you through the forest, across Cave Creek and into the arched cave to witness the waterfall plunging from above. With long sets of stairs, it is easier to walk this circuit in a clockwise direction. Remember to check for Park Alerts in wet weather as some areas may be closed for visitor safety. The hoop pines that emerge through the thick greenery of the surrounding rainforest are living relics of the Jurassic Age—the Age of the Conifers—about 180 million years ago. These pines are 'living dinosaurs'—they are among the most primitive of all conifers.

Natural Bridge is very popular with walkers and bird lovers during the day. At night the cave comes alive with the tiny green lights of thousands of nocturnal glow-worms, and the silent wings of microbats. Glow-worms are visible year-round, their display is significantly reduced during the winter months.

To protect the glow-worms and maximise visitor safety, parts of Cave Creek are a restricted access area.

Visit yourself or book a tour here to see more of the cave system.

Taking place after dusk, the rainforest comes alive in the evening with the shuffle and stir of nocturnal animals. The Gold Coast glow worm tour is one of the top things to do in the Gold Coast taking guests on a gentle rainforest walk along well formed pathways to the magical Natural Bridge, home to glow worms.

properties.name: Wallaman Falls
properties.description:
Wallaman Falls is Australia's tallest single-drop waterfall, located in Girringun National Park, Queensland. 

It plunges a breathtaking 268 metres (879 feet) from an escarpment into the pool below, surrounded by lush rainforest and rugged cliffs. 

The falls offer a stunning natural spectacle with their pristine waters cascading down the rocky terrain. Visitors can explore viewing platforms that provide panoramic vistas of the falls and the surrounding landscape. The area is home to diverse flora and fauna, making it a haven for nature enthusiasts and photographers. Wallaman Falls is a must-visit destination for those seeking the awe-inspiring beauty of nature in Australia.

properties.name: Cape Palmerston Camping Area
properties.description:
Cape Palmerston National Park is one of the few remaining areas of natural coastline in the Mackay area. Windswept headlands, rainforest, swamps and sand dunes are shadowed by the imposing peak of Mount Funnel. Middens throughout Cape Palmerston are a reminder of the special connection Indigenous people have with this place.

You can bush camp on the eastern beach of Cape Palmerston, in Cape Palmerston National Park. The park is 115km south-east of Mackay, on the Central Queensland coast. You need a high clearance 4WD to get to the camp sites.

Camp sites are located along the eastern beach of Cape Palmerston on the Cape Palmerston drive.

Turn off the Bruce Highway at Ilbilbie (76km south of Mackay and 157km north of Marlborough) and drive east towards Greenhill.
Before Greenhill, turn left into Cape Palmerston Road.
The park boundary is about 6km along this road.

Camping permits are required and fees apply. A camping tag with your booking number must be displayed at your camp site.

Camping area features: camp in the fore dunes along the eastern coast of Cape Palmerston National Park.

Location: eastern beach of Cape Palmerston

Access: the camping area can be reached by high clearance 4WD only.

Number of sites: undefined. Maximum of 6 people per site.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car, camper trailers.

Camp site surface: sand.

Facilities: none.

Open fires: on-ground campfires prohibited. Above-ground fire containers permitted—bring your own clean, milled timber. Remove your fire container when you leave. Fuel stoves are recommended.

Generators: not allowed.

Essentials to bring: drinking water, food, rubbish bags, insect repellent, sun protection, first-aid kit and a reliable torch. Read more about before you visit.

Park-specific conditions
Cape Palmerston National Park is very remote. Access is by 4WD only. Sand-driving experience is recommended. Beware of large tidal changes.

Camping is limited to a maximum of 22 nights in Cape Palmerston National Park.

properties.name: Travellers Haven Backpackers
properties.description: Travellers Haven Backpackers is located close to the centre of Mount Isa. Single, double, twin and bunk accommodation is available. Relax in the friendly atmosphere around the pool and barbecue area, or walk into town to enjoy the many things to see and do.

properties.name: Toowoomba Motor Village
properties.description: Toowoomba Motor Village Tourist Park offers a wide range of accommodation, including spacious two-roomed units, self-contained cabins, on-site vans and landscaped powered and unpowered sites with concrete slabs.

properties.name: Yuleba Rest Area
properties.description: This rest area is located in a park, a fair distance off the highway. It's quiet and shaded, however it doesn't provide much in terms of facilities - only picnic tables. 48hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Wyandra Camping Ground
properties.description: This campsite is conveniently located close to the Warrego River and Wyandra Beach. It is very large and open and has fantastic amenities, incl. showers. Plenty of fishing and swimming opportunities here! Donations are requested.

properties.name: Waterloo Plain Environmental Park
properties.description: This beautiful camping area with basic facilities, incl. toilet, picnic tables and rubbish bins, is located approx. 500m from the highway and offers scenic views, walking tracks (there is a heritage trail, too) and a rich variety of wildlife. Suitable for big rigs.

properties.name: Poddy Creek Rest Area
properties.description: This overnight rest area with no facilities, other than a rubbish bin, is located by the road. There is limited shade.

properties.name: Newstead Creek Rest Area
properties.description: This large rest area is situated by the Collumpton Creek, some 200m away from the highway. There are no amenities other than picnic tables, however shade is available. It is easily accessible by all vehicles.

properties.name: Mutee Head - Cape York
properties.description: This beautiful, small camping area with no amenities, except for rubbish bins, is located among trees by a long sandy beach. It offers plenty of shade and scenic views and has good fishing and swimming opportunities.

properties.name: Mungallala Rest Area
properties.description:
This overnight rest area with good facilities is situated off the highway in a small town of Mungalla. 

This is a historical location, famous for a sawmill. 

There is plenty of shade and it's suitable for big rigs with maximum stay of 48hrs.

properties.name: Maryvale Crown Hotel
properties.description: This campground with no amenities, except for drinking water and power, is located on the back of Maryvane Crown Hotel in the centre of town. It's spacious and suitable for big rigs, there is plenty of shade as well. For self-contained vehicles only with the maximum stay of 48hrs.

properties.name: Long Waterhole Camp Area
properties.description: This bush campground is located a short drive off Winton Jundah Rd and has no amenities. It is situated by a pond that is a part of Western River, 2km away from town. It's a popular picnic and fishing destination among travellers and locals alike and there is a motorbike trail going beside the billabong, too. Dry weather access only!

properties.name: Lloyd Jones Weir Camp Area
properties.description: This scenic and well-maintained camp area with good facilities and a dump point is located beside the river. There is a fishing spot, plenty of shade and the area is quiet and peaceful. Suitable for big rigs.

properties.name: James Norman Hedges Park
properties.description: This spacious rest area with good amenities is located off the highway, on the bank of the river. There is plenty of shade. Please be very careful when entering/ leaving the park, as there is a blind spot that sadly proved lethal in the past. Same commenter from Wahpunga Park: You can also approve my comment on this one about it being a drug dealing spot, or sayonara! If you don‚Äôt think that‚Äôs relevant information for people to know then you have no credibility as an app for opinions on campsites!

properties.name: Goovigen Showground Camping Area
properties.description:
Goovigen Recreation Grounds is a quiet, low-cost campground located on Stone Crescent in Goovigen. Grassy and slab sites are available with easy access from the highway.

The grounds have a total of six powered sites, for a maximum seven nights stay. There is also a communal grassy area, barbeque, covered communal area with picnic tables and information and amenities block with toilets and hot showers.

Please note, there are no bookings required.

properties.name: Futter Creek Rest Area
properties.description: This small overnight rest area with basic facilities is located off the main road, on the bank of Diglum Creek. Suitable for big rigs. 72hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Mareeba Bush Stays
properties.description: Formerly a cattle farm, Mareeba Bush Stays is now a 150 acre privately owned bush campground for self- contained vehicles. Lots of wildlife can be spotted here including kangaroos, birds, goannas and the occasional carpet python. Mareeba caters only to self- contained vehicles.

properties.name: Quinkan Hotel & Camp Ground
properties.description: Behind the Quinkan Hotel is a large grassy campground featuring a block toilet and shower, as well as laundry facilities. For those with caravans wishing to leave them for a while, Quinkan also offers a flat fee for secure sites to leave the vehicle.

properties.name: Hells Gate Roadhouse
properties.description:
Whether it's your first or last stop in Queensland, make sure you stop at Hell's Gate Roadhouse.! Our family owned roadhouse is located on the Cliffdale Station, 50km east of the Northern Territory/Queensland border. We have been welcoming travellers since 1986. 

You are invited to take a break, enjoy delicious meals, homemade cakes, real coffee and refreshing drinks. Our outback oasis offers budget and ensuited accommodation as well as a campground for your overnight stays. 

Connect with your fellow travellers, have a great rest and be ready for a new day and adventure!

properties.name: Kalbar Showground
properties.description:
Kalbar Showgrounds offers large powered sites, toilets and hot showers (for an additional $5). 

Great stop over, with good amenities and friendly caretakers. The town is a short walk with lots on offer. Some beautiful buildings & lots of conveniences like supermarket, butcher and bakery.

Weekly rates are available at a discount.

properties.name: Byfield Campstay
properties.description:
A Piece of Paradise

Experience camping as it used to be at Forest Fields Campstay (formerly Byfield Campstay). Set up in a peaceful, private bush setting just minutes from Byfield National Park and State Forest. This paid campground offers basic amenities including toilets, bucket showers, and drinking water.

We’re dog-friendly and love pets! Just ensure your furry friends are kept on a lead, and for the comfort of others, please don’t leave them unattended while touring. We recommend a great boarding kennel just 20 minutes away.

Campfires are allowed, with firewood available for purchase (or bring your own). Generators are permitted during daylight hours.

The site is accessible to RVs, camper trailers, caravans, and tents.

Forest Fields Campstay is a quiet, natural bush retreat, perfect for relaxing or exploring the nearby forests, national parks, and other unique attractions.

Maximum stay is two weeks—bookings are essential.

FLORA and FAUNA
This area is home to the Great Imperial Fruit Dove (Wompoo Pigeon) and the unique Byfield Fern (Bowenia serrata). Located on the migratory trail, Forest Fields Campstay attracts a diverse array of birdlife. You may also spot native wildlife such as wallabies, bandicoots, bush turkeys, and various reptiles.

properties.name: Jaxut Camping Area
properties.description:
Jaxut camping area offers grassy, shady campsites in Cathu State Forest, during the dry season.  Picnic tables and a unisex composting toilet are available. Fires are allowed in the fire pits provided, except in the case of fire ban. Bring your own firewood and drinking water. Conventional vehicles can access the site, but 4WD is recommended.
Dogs are allowed on lead only.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 Adult; AUD $23.80 Family; Children under 5 are free.

properties.name: Camp Kanga
properties.description:
Situated close to Lake Proserpine, Proserpine, North Queensland, Australia and run by Lions District 201Q2, Camp Kanga offers endless fun and activities.  Camp activities include Water Skiing, Great Barrier Reef trips (snorkeling, etc), ocean rafting, canoeing, indoor and outdoor sports, bush dancing, days at the beach, group activities, presentations and much more.
Camp Kanga offers catered or self catered camps for groups up to 230 people.  We welcome, school camps, community camps and other organised camps.
Only offers shared or individual accomodation in their cabins. ($25-30 each)

properties.name: Bucca Hotel
properties.description: Bucca Hotel offers short term camping with powered and unpowered sites. Hot showers are available for an additional AUD $2.50.

properties.name: Clancys Campground
properties.description: Clancys Campground in Benarkin State Forest is located near the Bicentennial National Trail and features large, grassy campsites accommodating up to 60 people. Facilities include flush toilets, fireplaces and tap water. Bring your own drinking water and wood. Generators are not allowed. Permits must be obtained and displayed prior to setting up camp.

properties.name: Forsayth Tourist Park & Store
properties.description:
In the historic town of Forsayth, the tourist park provides van sites, tent sites and ensuite cabins.

Facilities include, an amenities block with hot showers, a camp kitchen, BBQs, laundry and clothes lines.

properties.name: Ipswich Showgrounds
properties.description:
The Ipswich Showgrounds Caravan Park offers 25 powered sites with water access, suitable for campervans, caravans, motorhomes, and camper trailers. Amenities include modern toilet and shower facilities, an outdoor kitchen, and free Wi-Fi. Pets are allowed (one dog per site; additional dogs require approval). 

Rates are $30 per night for two people, with extra fees for additional guests. The park is conveniently located near Ipswich's city center, making it ideal for exploring the area. Note that tents are not permitted, and bookings are essential.

Please note our Caravan Park will close May each year for the annual Ipswich Show. Closure dates are the 28th April 2025 to 1st June 2025.

properties.name: Kynuna Roadhouse Caravan Park
properties.description: Kynuna Roadhouse Caravan Park has easily accessed powered and unpowered sites for caravans, and tents. A shop/restaurant is onsite for visitors convenience. An amenities block and dump point are the facilities available. Call for enquiries.

properties.name: Adavale Town Camping Area
properties.description: Adavale Town Camping Area is a free camping area at the Adavale Shire/Community Hall. Facilities include toilets, and hot and cold showers. A donation to the Royal Flying Doctor Service for your stay can be made at the town's pub.

properties.name: Lara Wetland Camping Grounds
properties.description: Lara Wetland Camping Grounds provides shaded unpowered sites in a tranquil setting. Facilities include hot and cold showers, flush toilets, dump facilities, fresh artesian drinking water, and a mineral hot pool.

properties.name: Broadwater Campground
properties.description:
With eucalypt forest and a creek as a backdrop, Broadwater camping area is great place to stay. Fall asleep to nocturnal rustlings and wake to a dawn chorus of forest birds. It's very popular during weekends and school holidays so ensure you book well in advance to avoid disappointment.

Wet a line in the creek (but not near the main swimming hole) or cool off with a dip. Enjoy a fry-up on the wood-fired barbeque or sit around the fire ring and swap stories by firelight. Stretch your legs on the nearby Rainforest and Creek walks and, in winter (when conditions are safe), canoe in sections of Broadwater Creek.


Facilities include water (non-drinkable), flushing toilets, cold showers, picnic tables, gas barbecues, communal fire rings and a bulk rubbish bin. Fires are allowed in the fire rings, except in the case of fire ban. Pets are not allowed. E-permits are required; book ahead.

properties.name: Peach Trees Camping  Area
properties.description: Peach Trees Camping Area is situated on grassy land, surrounded by trees in Jimna State Forest. Facilities include toilets, payphone, wood BBQs (bring your own wood), water (undrinkable), fire rings and walking tracks. Generators are not allowed.

properties.name: Lenthall Dam
properties.description: Camping at Lake Lenthall is permitted for short stays (2 nights max). No electricity or drinking water is available. Pets and generators are not allowed. Basic facilities provided. Call for enquiries or bookings.

properties.name: Tolderodden Campground
properties.description: Tolderodden Campground features shady, grassy campsites with toilets, picnic tables, wood barbeques, and rubbish bins. Pets are not allowed. Fires are permitted except during fire ban. Call for enquiries and bookings.

properties.name: Byfield Campstay
properties.description: Byfield Campstay offers peaceful bush camping with eco toilets, bucket-showers, and solar hot water. Call for enquiries and bookings.

properties.name: Musgrave Roadhouse
properties.description:
Offering good old fashioned hospitality the Musgrave Roadhouse, located in the Cape York Peninsula, is owned and operated by one of the early pioneering families of the region – the Shepard's.

Musgrave Roadhouse offers outback bush camping with hot showers, toilets and BBQ facilities. 

We have accommodation for everyone and every budget ranging from units with ensuites , cabins and spacious camping grounds.  

Sites are available on a first-come-first-serve basis. Make payments at the cafe.

properties.name: Bivouac Junction Holiday Camp
properties.description:
An Outback Oasis Bivouac Junction is about 20 klm east of Charters Towers. It is on the Fanny River just before it meets the Burdekin River and about 7 klm off the highway. It is just one of those fabulous outback camping grounds that it is a pleasure to wake up in. 

Amenities are basic but functional. The atmosphere there is casual and most enjoyable.

Bivouac Junction Holiday Camp offers a rang of accommodation including powered and nonpowered sites for tents, caravans camper trailers and motorhomes. There are also cabins for hire. Facilities include amenities block, swimming pool, camp fire, campers kitchen, BBQ area, and laundry. Bookings can be made by phone or email.

properties.name: Kenilworth Show & Recreation Grounds
properties.description:
Kenilworth Show & Recreation Grounds provides powered camping sites suitable for tents and caravans. Facilities include coin operated hot showers. Camp fees are collected each afternoon.
On arrival please call the caretakers on 0438849947 they will direct to the most suitable site.  
Powered sites per night $25 -  up to 2 persons
Unpowered sites per night $20 - up to 2 persons
Extra person per night $6, Children under 14 FREE
properties.fees: $25 for a powered site and $20 unpowered per night

properties.name: Elizabeth (O Briens) Creek Campgound
properties.description: Elizabeth Creek Campgound is located on O'Briens Creek road and is on private property. It provides sites for tents, cravans and long rigs. Facilities include toilets, showers, fireplace, BBQ and bins. Pets are allowed. 4WD is recommended in wet weather.

properties.name: 20 Mile Bush Camp Slygo Station
properties.description:
New bush camp available on the road between Jericho and Blackall for $10 per night. 

Currently, it's open to self-contained vehicles only, with more features coming soon. 

The 2-hectare area offers ample space for large vehicles, making it perfect for those seeking quiet and peaceful camping

properties.name: Cecil Plains Rural Retreat Caravan Park
properties.description:
Cecil Plains Rural Retreat Caravan Park provides basic powered sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. 

Facilities include toilets, showers dump point and free laundry. 

You will need to bring your own drinking water. 

Enquires can be made at the Toowoomba Regional Council office. 

There is a caretaker who lives across the road.

properties.name: Chillagoe Tourist Village
properties.description:
The Chillagoe Tourist Village offers a friendly outback experience on the "Wheelbarrow Way" in Queensland’s rugged outback region.

Magical Chillagoe is home to the renowned and world-famous Chillagoe Caves and the equally famous Chillagoe Rodeo and our park is in a great central location to enjoy everything our region has to offer.

We offer shady sites for caravans or motorhomes and we have some concrete annex pads. You can enjoy the comfort of our air-conditioned budget cabins that feature a double sized bed and two singles. If you're traveling without your own accommodation we offer clean and spacious family units and studio units.

The Village's camping grounds are well maintained, and campers will have easy access to all our amenities including pool and restaurant.

properties.name: School Point Campground
properties.description:
School Point Campground is located in Danbulla State Forest. Set up camp in this peaceful camping area that has stunning lake and forest views and rich birdlife.

Swim, canoe and fish from this camping area, or jump in your 4WD and explore the feature-packed Danbulla Road. Enjoy a cool rainforest walk, or take in the stunning views from the Gillies lookout. Remember to take your lunch because there are quaint picnic areas scattered along the drive.

There are 8 sites available for vehicle based camping and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets and picnic tables. 

You will need to be self-sufficient, including fire wood. 

Generators are not allowed. 

Local activities include swimming, fishing, water skiing and canoeing. 

Bookings and camping permit are required.

properties.name: Chinchilla Weir
properties.description: Located near the Condamine River, Chinchilla Weir camping area provides sites for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilties include toilets, wood fireplace, boat ramp, picnic tables and shelter. Pets are allowed. Activities include swimming, water skiing and canoeing. There is a maximum stay of 2 nights. You will need to bring your own water and firewood.

properties.name: Warokutal Safari Camp – Port Stewart Campground
properties.description:
Port Stewart Campground is located besides the Stewart River.

- Non-potable water
- Toilets
- Pet friendly
- Campervans and trailers welcome. Please note, the closest dump point is at Coen.
- Short walk to the banks of the Stewart River
- Short drive to Yintjingga boat ramp

All visitors should first check in at the Lama Lama Ranger Base at Port Stewart. The base is attended daily from 8am to 4.30pm. Visitors to Silver Plains can also check in at the Homestead. Enquiries can also be made at our Coen and Cairns offices.

Our rangers will provide you with information and instructions about suitable camping sites and activities. Permits are required if you wish to camp and fees apply.

properties.name: Water Park Creek Campground
properties.description: Water Park Creek Campground is located in Byfield State Forest. Campsites are suitable for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, BBQ, water, picnic tables and wood fireplace. Generators are allowed between 8am and 7pm. You will need to provide your own firewood and gas/fuel stove.  Camping permits are necessary.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per person AUD $23.80 per family

properties.name: Burdekin Falls Dam Caravan Park
properties.description: Burdekin Falls Dam Caravan Park provides powered sites for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilities include toilets, showers, BBQ, baot ramp, picnic tables and shelter. Activities include swimming, waterskiing, fishing, canoeing, and sailing. There is a care taker on site.

properties.name: Mungalla Station
properties.description:
When you arrive at Mungalla Station, please check in with the caretaker or sign the visitor's book at the Homestead entry. If the caretaker is unavailable, sign in and leave your payment in the donation box. 

Guests are welcome for up to 7 days, with longer stays negotiable. While self-contained vehicles are preferred, basic showers and toilets are available 100 meters from the campground. These facilities are in the process of being upgraded, so expect rustic amenities with hot water and flushing toilets. If you’re looking for luxury, this may not be the place for you.

Mungalla Station is a working cattle property, where cattle operations take priority. However, the land holds deep spiritual significance for its Aboriginal owners, and visitors are offered the unique opportunity to connect with this sacred place.

For your stay:

- Fires are allowed in contained fire pits (BYO wood).
- Generators may be used between 1 pm and 5 pm.
- Bore water is available but is not recommended for drinking.
- Occasionally, "Goobardthe" the crocodile may be spotted, so please stay within the fenced area.
- You can also book a campsite at Crystal Creek, 40 minutes south of Mungalla Station, through Hipcamp. Additionally, Mungalla Aboriginal Tours provide a unique opportunity to learn about the rich culture and history of the station.

There is an adjacent camp kitchen and eating area for groups. There is a campfire site and a large open area for games and activities.

properties.name: Jardine River Ferry Campground & Service Station
properties.description:
Jardine River Ferry camping area provides a basic campsite suitable for vehicle based camping, caravand and camper trailers. 

Facilities include toilets, showers, wood fireplace, laundry area, and water (treat or boil before drinking). Swimming is not permitted. 

Generators are allowed. Bookings are required and you will need to obtain an e-permit. There is no self-registration available at the site. Mobile phone coverage is not available at the site.

properties.name: Fong-On Bay Campground
properties.description:
this large camping area is favoured by waterskiers and most of the camp sites along this peninsula have water access and views. Beyond the lake, rolling hills, forests and pine plantations form a picturesque backdrop. The camping area is divided into two sections‚ÄîBulmba and Gungul‚Äîand seasonal closures apply to the Gungul section

Fong-On Bay and Downfall Creek are the only camping areas in Danbulla State Forest where generators are permitted. Generators are only to be used between 8.00am and 7.00pm and only if the noise level is less than 65dB(A) measured at a distance of 7m from the generator.

Flushing toilets, shower room (bring own shower), and individual and communal fire rings. A small shelter is available to facilitate organised events. Camping is not permitted in the organised event facility.

properties.name: Amamoor Creek Campground
properties.description:
Nestled beside the Amamoor Creek, this spacious camping area with ironbark and blue gum trees is a great place to camp with your dog.

In the last week of August, this camping area attracts thousands of visitors for the annual Gympie Music Muster. If you are not attending the Gympie Music Muster, consider camping at Cedar Grove camping area (dogs are not permitted).

The Gympie Music Muster(external link) manages camp bookings and enquiries for Amamoor Creek camping area from late July to early September.

This camping area is also busy over school and public holidays but at other times it's ideal for peaceful camping and star gazing on clear nights.

Your family dog can camp with you here—conditions apply:

Your dog must be on a leash and under control at all times.
Always clean up after your dog—collect waste in a secure bag. Pack bags and a suitable storage container so you can take it away and dispose of it responsibly.

properties.name: Bramwell Junction Roadhouse
properties.description:
Bramwell Roadhouse camping area offers sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. 

Facilities include toilets, showers, wood fireplace and picnic tables. You will need to bring your own firewood and water. 

Food is available to purchase at the roadhouse.

properties.name: The Lake Campground
properties.description: The Lake Campground located in Lake Broadwater Conservation Park provides sites for vehicle based camping, camer trailers and caravans. Facilities include showers, drinking water, picnic tables, boat ramp and wood fireplace. You will need to bring your own firewood. Activities available include swimming, waterskiing, canoeing, sailing and walking tracks. A permit is required. There is a self-registration station for paying camp fees.
properties.fees: $6.55 per person per night, or $26.20 per family per night

properties.name: Flaggy Rock Community Centre.
properties.description: Flaggy Rock Community Centre provides a campground and rest area. SItes are suitable for self-contained carvavans and large rigs. Facilities include toilets and picnic tables. There is a maximum stay of 72 hours. Please note we have a new phone number   0481226658

properties.name: Yowah Rest Area
properties.description: Yowah Rest Area offers a camping area for tents, caravans  and large rigs. Facilities include toilets, hot showers, fire place and picnic tables. Generators are allowed. Free overnight camping is permitted, although a donation is requested.

properties.name: Catch a Barra
properties.description: Located in Little Mulgrave, Catch a Barra offers powered and unpowered sites best suited for self contained vehilces. Facilities include toilets, drinking water, BBQ and picnic tables. Activities include swimming, fishing, birdwatching and walking trails.

properties.name: Artesian Waters Caravan Park
properties.description:
Artesian Waters Caravan Park is a popular spot for opal fossickers and tourists alike. It is located in the heart of the Yowah opal fields, and offers a variety of accommodation options to suit all budgets from unpowered sites to motel rooms. The park has a friendly and relaxed atmosphere, and is perfect for those who want to experience the true outback spirit.

The park is well-maintained and has a variety of facilities, including Artesian Bathe Houses to bathe in privacy under the stars. There is also a general store on-site that sells groceries food, drinks, and opal fossicking equipment.

Artesian Waters Caravan Park is a great place to stay if you are looking for a comfortable and affordable base from which to explore the Yowah opal fields.

properties.name: Malanda Falls Caravan Park
properties.description: Located in the Cairns Highlands, Malanda Falls Caravan Park provides a range of accomodation. Choose from powered caravan sites and non-powered camp sites as well as self contained Villas and units. Facilities include camp kitchen, BBQs, laundry facilities, and amenities. Local attractions include Malanda Falls and the rainforest. Bookings can be made online.

properties.name: Iron Ridge Park
properties.description:
Iron Ridge Park offers Bush camping for caravans. There are 11 sites available. Facilities include toilets, showers, power, laundromat, drinking water, BBQ and picnic tables. Camp fires are allowed. Bookings can be made online or by phone. Reception hours vary

Pricing
$35.00 per site for single night bookings for 1 - 2 people

$30.00 per site per night (2 - 6 night bookings) for 1 - 2 people

Weekly rate $196.00 1-2 people include power & water

7 nights or longer $28.00 per site per night for 1 - 2 people

Additional person $8 pp/pn, Children aged 2 and over $8 pp/pn*
properties.fees: $35.00 per site for single night bookings for 1 - 2 people  $30.00 per site per night (2 - 6 night bookings) for 1 - 2 people

properties.name: Palmer River Roadhouse
properties.description: Palmer River Roadhouse provides a scenic campground for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilities include toilets, water, hot showers, BBQ, restaurant, picnic tables and shelter.  There are 22 powered carvan and camp sites and 4 tent sites available. There is caretaker on site. Bookings can be made online or by phone.

properties.name: Michelle's Tourist Park
properties.description: Michelle's Caravan Park offers powered sites for tents, and large vehilces. There are also ensuite cabins available. Facilities include BBQ, shower, toilets and public phone. Pets are allowed on a lead. There is a service station nearby.

properties.name: Lowood Showgrounds & Caravan Park
properties.description:
Nestled near the Brisbane River with tranquil mountain views and a friendly country town feel, Lowood Showgrounds offers up to seven days caravanning and camping to soak up the laid-back country atmosphere. The showgrounds are located in the township of Lowood and in walking distance to cafés and shops.

Lowood Showgrounds & Caravan Park offers sties for tents, caravans and big rigs.

Large, grassy sites, showers, toilets, dump point.

There is a maximum of 7 days. Pets are allowed.

properties.name: Bauhinia Store
properties.description: Bauhinia Store campground offers powered sites for tents, camper trailers and Big Rigs. Facilities include toilets, showers, and water. There is a fuel station and convenience store in the area.

properties.name: Barcoo River Nature Park
properties.description: Barcoo River camping area offers sites suitable for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilities include toielts and hot showers. Pets are allowed. Enjoy excellent fishing or canoeing in the Barcoo river. Camp fees can be paid at the council office.

properties.name: Hedleys Campground
properties.description: Hedleys Campground is located in Tuan State Forest and set on a creek. Sites are suitable for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans. Facilities include wood fireplace. You will need to bring drinking water and untreated firewood. In the area you can enjoy fishing, swimming, sailing, and canoeing. There is a ranger on site. Advanced bookings are required.
properties.fees: AUD $ 6.65 per person per night $23.80 per family per night

properties.name: Wongi Waterholes Camping Area
properties.description: Wongi Waterholes Camping Area located in Wongi State Forest Recreation Area offers opern campsites for tents, caravans, camper trailers and small motor homes. Facilities include toilets, showers and picnic tables. Open fires are not allowed. Generators are allowed between 9am and 8pm. You will need to bring your own water. Bookings can be made in advance.

properties.name: Baralaba Showgrounds
properties.description:
Situated at the Baralaba Showgrounds these unpowered Caravan and camping sites suitable for (BYO) Tent/Swag camping and self powered caravan/Camper-van-trailers. 

It is suitable for big rigs and is dog friendly.

This location includes on-site public amenities for your convenience – Prices are per site.

properties.name: Dayboro Showgrounds
properties.description: Dayboro Showgrounds offers powered and unpowered campsites suitable for camper trailers, caravans and RVs. Facilities include toilets and hot showers. There is a caretaker on site. Bookings can be made in advance.
properties.fees: AUD $15 powered site 2 adults. $12 non powered site 2 adults. $3 additional person per night

properties.name: Glastonbury Creek Campground
properties.description:
Glastonbury Creek Campground is located on the edge of Brooyar State Forest. The campground is suitable for vehicle based camping, camper trailers and caravans.

Camping area features: Open grassy area at the base of a hill. Main activities include exploring the surrounding forest on foot and by vehicle, abseiling nearby, relaxing, watching birds and wildlife. Note: High tension powerlines cross 40m above this camping area.

Location: On the south-east edge of Brooyar State Forest alongside Glastonbury Creek.

Access: Conventional vehicles, trailers, caravans and buses access is from the southern entrance. Take the Gympie–Woolooga Road and turn right into Diggins Road and onto Greendale Road. Follow the signs to the camping area, on the right just past the forest entrance. This access route includes sections of unsealed roads.

All other roads within the forest, including the road to Point Pure lookout, are unsuitable for conventional vehicles, caravans and trailers.

Alternative access for four-wheel-drive vehicles only is available from the north. Head 10km north of Gympie along the Bruce Highway, then turn left onto the Wide Bay Highway and continue 7.8km, then turn left onto Peterson Road. Follow the signs to the camping area, located on the left 2km past the forest entrance.

Number of sites: Sites are not numbered. Maximum capacity for the camping area is 120 people.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car; caravans; camper trailers; small and large motorhomes and large groups.

Campsite surface: Grass.

Facilities: Fire rings, composting toilets and non-potable water.

Open fires: Allowed—except when fire bans or prohibitions apply—in fire rings only, but fuel stoves are recommended. Never gather wood (or even kindling) from the bush—it provides home for wildlife and nutrients for the soil. Bring your own clean-milled firewood.

Generators: Not permitted

Essentials to bring: Drinking water, a fuel stove for cooking, rubbish bags (bins are not provided), insect repellent and sunscreen. If you wish to use the fire rings bring your own firewood (untreated mill off-cuts).

properties.name: Herberton Wild River Caravan Park
properties.description: Wild River Caravan Park offers campsites for tents, camper trailers, caravans, and large rigs. Facilities include toilets, showers, drinking water, BBQ, picnic tables and bins. Local attractions include bird watching and walking trails. Pets are allowed.

properties.name: Windsong Cabins
properties.description:
Windsong Cabins is situated just 20 mins North of Gympie on the Bruce H'way , Gunalda. 

The buildings Iconic Structure is known as a landmark between Bundaberg and Brisbane and attracts many visitors needing accommodation or a meal break while traveling along the Bruce H'way.  

Windsong has recently undergone renovations with the end result not only adding to its rustic character & charm but adds tranquility to a retreat that houses Accommodation, Caravans, Big Rigs, A Tea Garden and Function Room surrounded by beautiful gardens with scenic country views.

properties.name: Log Dump Campground
properties.description: Situated on the banks of Kauri Creek, Log Dump camping offers camp sites for vehicle based camping, caravans, camper trailers and small motor homes. Facilities include toilets, boat ramp, and fire rings. Generators are permitted. You will need to bring your own drinking water. Kauri Creek is a popular fishing spot. Bookings can be made in advance.

properties.name: Moura Apex River Park
properties.description: Moura Apex River Park campground offers free camping with 30 sites available. Facilities include toilets, picnic tables, and wood BBQ. Bookings are not required. You will need to bring your own water and firewood. Near the campsite there is canoeing, kayaking, swimming and fishing. There is a donation box available.

properties.name: Corfield Rest Area
properties.description: Corfield Rest Area offers a free overnight stop. Facilities include toilets, tables and a fireplace with wood. The rest area offers access for caravans and large rigs. There are hot showers at the pup for a fee as well as hot meals. A maximum stay of 48 hour is permitted.

properties.name: Kinchant Waters Leisure Resort
properties.description: A popular place for waterskiers and anglers, Kinchant Waters Leisure Resort offers a camp area for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers, as well as cabins and backpacker rooms. Facilities include toilets, drinking water, hot showers, boat ramp and a wood freplace. There is also a restaurants, bar and laundry area.  In the area you can enjoy swimming, fishing, canoeing, and sailing.

properties.name: Bramwell Station
properties.description: Bramwell Station tourist park is situated est of Cape York's Peninsula and is Australia's most northerly cattle station. The campground offers sites for vehilce based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include hot showers, drinking water, and wood fireplace. You will need to bring your own firewood. There is also a licensed bar where meals can be bought. There is a ranger on site.

properties.name: Wallumbilla Showgrounds
properties.description: Wallumbilla showground offers power, hot showers, drinking water and flushing toilets. Situated on the Wallumbilla Creek, offering grass, large sites.  Maximum stay is 48 hours.

properties.name: Upper Stony Campground
properties.description: Upper Stony Creek Campground is located in Queensland. There are 11 campsites suitable for tents, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, picnic tables, BBQ facilities and water but you must bring your own drinking water supply. Activities include swimming and walking.

properties.name: Platypus Campground
properties.description: Platypus Camping area is located in Danbulla National Park. There are 18 campsites suitable for tents, camper trailers and caravans. Not suitable for larger vehicles. Facilities include toilets, wood BBQs, fire rings and picnic tables. Water is not available so bring your own supply.

properties.name: Allora Showgrounds
properties.description:
Allora Show Campgrounds is located in Queensland. Campsites are suitable for tents, caravans, camper trailers and motorhomes. 

There are powered sites available. Facilities include picnic tables, toilets and showers.

properties.name: Cedar Grove Campground
properties.description: Cedar Grove camping area is a basic campsite in Amamoor. Campsites are open areas suitable for tents, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, fire rings and limited water supply, but you must bring your own drinking water. Generators are not allowed.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 pp or AUD $23.80 per family

properties.name: General Gordon Hotel
properties.description: General Gordon Hotel Camping area is located in Homebush, Queensland. Facilities include picnic tables, toilets, showers and drinking water. Campsites are suitable for tents, caravans and camper trailers.

properties.name: Miles Showgrounds
properties.description: Miles Showgrounds is located in Queensland. This campsite is suitable for tents, caravans and camper trailers. There are limited powered sites. Facilities include picnic tables, toilets and basic amenities available. Bring your own drinking water supply.

properties.name: Manna Gum Camp Site
properties.description: Shadded by manna gum trees, Manna Gum camping area offers sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, drinking water, and wood fireplace. You will need to bring your own firewood. In the area you can enjoy walking trails, Queen Mary Falls,  and Sylvesters and Fassifern Valley lookouts. Adavanced bookings are required.

properties.name: Tully Gorge Campground
properties.description: Located beside the Tully River, Tully Gorge camping area offers a large, shaded, open grassy camping area. The site is suitable for vehicle based camping, caravans, camper trailers and motorhomes. Facilities include toilets, cold showers, tap water (must be treated before drinking), and picnic tables. Open fires are allowed in the fire rings only. Generators are allowed between 9am and noon. Bookings can be made in advance.

properties.name: Gordon Creek Campground South
properties.description:
Gordon Creek camping area in Kutini-Payamu (Iron Range) National Park, Queensland, offers a remote and peaceful camping experience. It is set in a lush rainforest environment, with basic facilities including pit toilets and picnic tables. 

The site is accessible for tents and camper trailers, but there are no powered sites or showers. It's a great spot for birdwatching and exploring the surrounding rainforest, with opportunities to spot unique wildlife. Bookings are required.

properties.name: Monks Tank Camping Area
properties.description: Monks Tank camping area features open bush camping sites in Mulga Woodlands. This campsite offers an open area without defined sites, suitable for vehicle based camping and camper trailers. There are pit toilets available. Open fires are permitted and generators are not allowed. During wet conditions a 4WD will be needed. You will need to bring your own water. Bookings are available.

properties.name: Bough Shed Hole Campground
properties.description:
Bough Shed Hole camping is situated beside Surprise Creek, where you'll see wallaroos, red kangaroos and various birdlife. 

The campsite consists of two open sections for vehicle based camping and camper trailers. 4WD is recommended. Generators are not allowed. Fires are permitted. You will need to bring drinking water.

properties.name: Alligator Creek Campground
properties.description: Located in the Mount Elliot section of the park, Alligator Creek campground offers sites for tents and small campervans only. The park is open from 6:30am to 6:30 pm. The gate is locked at 6:30pm everyday by the onsite caretaker. Facilities include toilets, showers, picnic tables, amenities block and tap water (must be treated before drinking). Open fires and generators are not permitted.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per person, $23.80 per family. Bookings required.

properties.name: Poplar Flat Camping Area
properties.description: Poplar Flat camping area features open, flat grassy areas next to Dalrymple creek .These non powered sites are suitable for caravans, camper trailers, motorhomes and vehicle based camping. There are toilets, BBQs and tap-water available. Generators are not allowed. Advanced bookings can be made.

properties.name: Trafalgar Waterhole Day Use Area Welford National Park
properties.description:
Visit the Trafalgar Waterhole day-use area. Enjoy a picnic on the banks of the Barcoo River under the shade of coolibah trees. 

Try your hand at fishing (remember size and bag limits apply) or paddle the tranquil waters of the Barcoo. To get there turn east off the Jundah-Quilpie road and travel approximately 18km, follow the signs to the day-use area. This track is accessible for 4WD vehicles only.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per adult or $23.80 per family

properties.name: Boodjamulla Lawn Hill Gorge Camping Area
properties.description:
Lawn Hill Gorge is located in Boodjamulla (Lawn Hill) National park. The 20 camping sites are suitable for tents and,camper trailers and campervans. Facilities include water, toilets, cold showers and recycling bins. 

Open fires and generators are not permitted. 

It is essential to bring fuel or gas stove and rubbish bags. Phone reception is accessible in the national park office. Bookings are essential during peak season.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per person or $23.80 per family

properties.name: Henrietta Creek Camping Area
properties.description:
Surrounded by rainforest, Henrietta Creek camping area is located in Wooroonooran National Park off the Palmerston Hwy. There are 10 numbered sites suitable for tents, camper trailers, and caravans. 

Facilities include picnic tables, toilets, and gas BBQ. Open fires are not allowed. Essentials to bring include water, rubbish bags and insect repellent. All camping must be booked in advance.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per person or AUD $23.80 per family per night

properties.name: Miyumba Bush Camp
properties.description:
Set up your self-sufficient camp, whether it is a tent, camper-trailer or campervan. Take a short stroll to the river, relax by the cool deep waterhole and small rapids on the Gregory River.

Sit by the river's edge with binoculars in hand and watch the spectacular variety of birds darting down from the treetops to the water for a drink. Look among the treetops surrounding the waterhole to spot the whistling kite's nest.

When you tire of relaxing, drive to nearby Riversleigh - D Site visitor area to learn about the Riversleigh World Heritage Area and explore the fascinating Riversleigh fossil trail.

Sleep under a star-studded sky and emerge with the dawn to watch wildlife venturing to the river’s edge for the start of a new day.

Getting there and getting around:
The Miyumba camping area is in the Riversleigh section of Boodjamulla National Park (Aboriginal Land) in remote north-west Queensland, close to the Northern Territory border, 270km north-west of Mount Isa. The Miyumba camping area is:

- Number of sites: six sites (separate but not numbered).
- Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car, campervans, and camper trailers.
- Camp site surface: dirt.
- Facilities: drinking water (tank can be empty) and a hybrid toilet. Treat all water before drinking.
- Open fires: not allowed—fuel or gas stoves only.
- Generators: not allowed.
- Essentials to bring: drinking water, a fuel or gas stove for cooking and rubbish bags. Read more about before you visit.

Bookings: must be made in advance. Book online, over the counter or by phone. Camping permits cannot be obtained from the national park.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 pp or AUD $23.80 per family

properties.name: Rainforest Campground
properties.description:
Relax around your shady camp site in rainforest on the banks of the Claudie River at this popular camping area, suitable for high-clearance camper trailers as well as tents.

Indulge many happy hours wildlife spotting here. Sit quietly, and well back, from the river bank and spot the resident crocodile. Grab your binoculars and watch the many different birds of the rainforest. You may even see a cassowary! In the evenings, walk quietly and spotlight for common spotted cuscus and green pythons—listen for rustling leaves and look for eye shine. Later, swap stories around the camp fire.

Kutini-Payamu (Iron Range) National Park (CYPAL) is jointly managed by the Northern Kuuku Ya'u Kanthanampu Aboriginal Corporation RNTBC Land Trust and the Queensland Government.

Visitors need to book their camping permit before they visit. Book online, at an over-the-counter booking office or by phone.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 pp or AUD$23.80 per family

properties.name: Gum Hole Camping Area
properties.description: Gum Hole camping area provides 5 camping sites shaded along Whistling Duck Creek. Suitable for tents and small vehicles. Facilities include pit toilets. Generators are not allowed.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 pp or AUD$23.80 per family

properties.name: Hunters Gorge Camping Area
properties.description:
Sitting next to Mundawerra Waterhole on the Diamantina River, Hunters Gorge camping area offers incredible opportunities for fishing and birdwatching.

On the access track to Hunters Gorge look for the two impressive landmarks: Moses Cone rising from the river to the east, and Mount Mary forming the eastern side of the gorge.

As you settle in for the night have your camera ready to capture a spectacular sunset— the earth's red hues contrasting against the yellow weathered sandstone ranges.

Facilities include pit toilets. 

Generators are not permitted. 

You must bring your own water supply.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 pp or AUD$23.80 per family

properties.name: Big Crystal Creek Camping Area
properties.description: Big Crystal Creek camping area is a popular swimming and picnic spot and a good place for birdwatching. Campsites are suitable for tents, small caravans and small camper trailers. Not suitable for large motorhomes. Facilities include picnic tables, gas BBQ's, showers and toilets. Bring your own drinking water. Generators not permitted.
properties.fees: AUD $5.95 per Adult or AUD $23.80 per family

properties.name: Burdekin River Camping Area
properties.description: Burdekin River Camping area is located in the Dalrymple National Park. There are 4 cleared campsites. No facilities are provided. Fees apply.
properties.fees: AUD$5.95 per Adult or AUD $23.80 per family

properties.name: Foxtrap Roadhouse at Cooladdi
properties.description: This friendly family run business is a one stop shop with a motel, store, licensed restaurant and a free campground. It is located in Queensland's smallest town of 4. The amenities at this site are great and visitors can use power sites and hot showers for a small fee of AUD5 and AUD2 respectively.

properties.name: Clem Walton Park & Camp Corella Dam
properties.description: Those two sites are located approx. 2km off the main road at the opposite ends of Y junction, with Clem Walton Park on the left (through a gate that appears locked, but isn't really!) and Corella Dam to the right. Both campgrounds are scenic and have a great water access. There is no shortage of shade or spectacular views at either of them, however, while Clem Wilton Park has a toilet, there are no amenities at Corella Dam.

properties.name: Chinchilla Weir Campground
properties.description: This small site has good amenities (incl. powered sites with limited free power) and pleasant riverside which is great for swimming, fishing and water sports. It is suitable for all vehicles, however space is limited, so arrive early. 48 hrs limit applies.

properties.name: Bulloo River Self Contained Campground
properties.description:
For those of you who like the peace and quiet of bush camping, we offer free camping on the Bulloo River in Thargomindah. Over 8 hectares of river frontage with fire pits, solar lights and bins provided you are sure to find that perfect spot to set up camp and put your feet up.

Located just east of town, cross over the two bridges on your way out of town and then before Burleys crossing turn either right or left depending on what looks like a good spot to you. As you can see in the second photo, the right side is a smaller area and the left goes down quite a way.

properties.name: Rex Lookout
properties.description: Rex Lookout in Queensland, Australia, is a popular tourist destination known for its stunning views of the Coral Sea, Trinity Bay, and the Daintree Rainforest. The lookout is located on the Captain Cook Highway, about 40 kilometres north of Cairns. Rex Lookout is a great place to stop and take in the scenery, or to start a hike in the Daintree Rainforest. There are also several tour operators that offer hang gliding and paragliding experiences from the lookout.

properties.name: Hinchinbrook Lookout
properties.description:
