properties.name: Capricorn Coast Visitor Information Centre
properties.description:
Capricorn Coast Visitor Information Centre
When planning a trip to the Capricorn Coast, make your first stop at the Capricorn Coast Visitor Information Centre, located on Ross Creek Roundabout, Scenic Highway in Yeppoon. 
The Capricorn Coast Visitor Information Centre can help you create an itinerary to suit your needs, ensuring the best opportunity to experience all that the Capricorn Coast has to offer. 
From discovering the underwater magic of the Southern Great Barrier Reef from easily accessible beaches and islands, to exploring the lush rainforests of Byfield, this is your one stop shop for information on where to stay, eat, play and the ultimate ‘must do’s’ for your visit.
Services offered to visitors

This accredited Visitor Information Centre offers a one-stop-shop for:
1. Friendly and welcoming environment supported by passionate volunteers
2. Travel information
3. Maps and brochures
4. Itineraries
5. Accommodation and tour bookings
6. Queensland Park National Parks camping permits for your outdoor and island adventures.
Top 10 things to do in region
1. Visit Great Keppel or Pumpkin Islands and discover a barefoot paradise with easy access to the underwater magic of the Southern Great Barrier reef. Island hop and explore sea caves with an exhilarating tour. 
2. Discover a living laboratory as you explore the wonders of the multi-award-winning Capricorn Caves. Experience the serenity of spectacular above ground limestone cave system. 
3. Swim in Queensland’s largest infinity pool. The Yeppoon Lagoon is the jewel in the crown of the Yeppoon foreshore precinct and the surrounding parklands offer barbeques and shady areas great for picnics.
4. Take an adventure by foot along Capricorn Coast’s national park hiking tracks and even spot a turtle swimming below from ‘Turtle Lookout’. 
5. Cuddle a koala at Cooberrie Park Wildlife Sanctuary – one of the few places in Australia you can get up close and personal with the local residents.
6. We know they say you should never smile at a crocodile, but would you hold one? The Capricorn Coast is home to Queensland’s first Crocodile Farm, Koorana.
7. A popular track for walker, joggers, cyclists and families, the Capricorn Coast Pineapple Rail Trail takes visitors through picturesque bushlands and urban landscape.
8. Take your tastebuds on a tantalising journey as you embark on the Capricorn Coast Food Trail, which showcases local farm to fork experiences across the region.
9. Explore the outdoor beauty of Byfield National Park and immerse yourself amongst the rainforest and crystal-clear creeks. Keep an eye out for a glimpse of the rare Byfield fern as you paddle, kayak or wander in paradise. 
10. Reflect and remember at Emu Park’s Centenary of ANZAC Memorial Walk. The award-winning tribute sits in a fitting location allowing visitors a unique and remarkable experience.

properties.name: Stanthorpe Visitor Information Centre
properties.description: Australia's Nationally Accredited Information Centres are staffed by local experts and are your one-stop-shop for maps of the region and information about the best things to see, as well as booking tours and accommodation.

properties.name: Warwick Visitor Information Centre
properties.description: Australia's Nationally Accredited Information Centres are staffed by local experts and are your one-stop-shop for maps of the region and information about the best things to see, as well as booking tours and accommodation.

properties.name: Queens Beach Bowen
properties.description: Beach that has some limited facilities onsite

properties.name: Goondiwindi Natural Heritage & Water Park
properties.description:
A section of the Serpentine Creek has been converted to form the Natural Heritage & Water Park. 

The 210ha recreational water park opened early in 2004 and offers plenty of activities for all ages. The purpose built 3km water channel provides great opportunities for water sports of all kinds including waterskiing, wakeboarding, canoeing and boating. It is also the perfect place to view the vast bird life, have a picnic on the lawn or swim at the designated area.

As a result of initiatives by the former Goondiwindi Town Council, the Federal Government through Environment Australia, made a decision to fund a Natural Heritage & Water Park, to make available skiing and boating facilities and to provide a focal point for tourism and recreation in the town and district.

properties.name: Warrego River Walk
properties.description:
Cross the Darby land bridge over the Warrego River and enjoy the walk on your left.  

The walk takes you along the banks of the Warrego, across black flood plains and through the channels.  It's a great place for bird watching and fishing and enjoying the stillness and space and also ideal for early morning walkers.

properties.name: Streets Beach
properties.description: Streets Beach is a South Bank icon and a must-visit while you’re in the Parklands. As Australia’s only inner-city, man-made beach, boasts a sparkling lagoon surrounded by white, sandy beaches and sub-tropical plants. Streets Beach is free to use and is patrolled by qualified lifeguards all year round.

properties.name: Saunders Beach
properties.description:
Saunders Beach is part of the Northern Beaches precinct of Townsville. Saunders Beach has a residential community and some commercial accommodation. The beach is largely untouched and visitors frequently have the beach to themselves. 

With over six kilometres of beach to discover, take a long refreshing walk, drop a line in to fish, and claim a piece of paradise to yourself. Have lunch at the Cafe or Take-Away and store under a magnificent fig tree, then relax at the beautiful Saunders Beach Park. Stay on the beach at the Retreat House or Ocean View Units. A boat ramp is also available for the keen fisher.

properties.name: Horseshoe Bay Rotary Lookout
properties.description:
Enjoy the most amazing views of the Coral Sea and Horseshoe bay from the lookout. Make sure you take your camera. 

If you enjoy walking this is a must. Walk around all the beautiful granite to Murray Bay then onto Rose bay bringing you back to Grays Bay or Horseshoe Bay.

properties.name: Millennium Esplanade and Tannum Sands Beach
properties.description: For over 50 years, the esplanade beach areas of Tannum Sands has served as the principal destination for passive and active beachside pursuits for the Gladstone Region. Located just 20 kilometres south of Gladstone on the Central Queensland coast, this coastal foreshore area provides individual pavillions which provide intimacy and cool, weather proof refuges which make the most of the ocean views.

properties.name: Kings Beach Beachfront Salt Water Pool
properties.description:
Caloundra’s swimming pool on the stunning Kings Beach foreshore is equipped with shade sails and has a free 25-metre sea-water lap pool, children’s swimming pool and wading area with disabled access. The pool is easy to access and plenty of parking is available. 
Bring your family along for a great day out.

properties.name: Hydeaway Bay Beach
properties.description: Hydeaway Bay Beach is on the coast of the Whitsundays, around 45 minutes drive north of the tourist town of Airlie Beach. The beach at Hydeaway Bay is a lovely sandy beach over 1.5 kilometres long. Covering the beachfront area along the main street.

properties.name: Horseshoe Bay
properties.description: Horseshoe Bay is Bowen's most iconic beach and a favourite for locals and visitors alike. The beach is framed by two granite outcrops which provide a haven for a wonderful range of fish and coral just a short swim from the beach. The bay is a top spot for divers and snorkellers.

properties.name: Horseshoe Bay
properties.description: Horseshoe Bay is the premier location for watersports on Magnetic Island offering activities to excite the whole family. Along the shores of Horseshoe Bay is an array of equipment hire options including jet skis, kayaks, stand up paddle boards and more! The Bay also provides a great swimming enclosure.

properties.name: The Great Artesian Spa
properties.description:
The Great Artesian Spa is a unique spa experience located in Mitchell, Queensland, Australia. 

It features two large pools of naturally heated artesian water, one at a comfortable temperature for relaxation and the other cooler for those who prefer it. The artesian water comes from the Great Artesian Basin, the world's largest underground freshwater aquifer. 

The water is naturally heated as it travels through the Earth's crust and emerges at the surface at a temperature of around 32 degrees Celsius.

properties.name: Elliott Heads Beach
properties.description: Elliott Heads is a 15 minute drive from Bundaberg Central Business District and is surrounded by rural cane and small crop farms. Elliott Heads offers swimming at the patrolled surf beach or drop your boat in for a fish at Riverview.

properties.name: Dicky Beach
properties.description: Dicky Beach is an unspoiled stretch of sun-drenched white sand, on Queensland's magnificent Sunshine Coast. The north-east facing beach is about two kilometres north of Caloundra and was named after the iron screw Steamship SS Dicky which was washed ashore in 1893 during a cyclone.

properties.name: Cunnamulla Fella
properties.description:
The Cunnamulla Fella is a song written by Stan Coster and sung by Slim Dusty. 

He is an iconic Australian Bush character. The town of Cunnamulla has erected a statue of the Cunnamulla Fella as a tribute to Stan and Slim and to the "ringers" of the bush. 

The statue is double life size bronze.

properties.name: Coolmunda Dam Recreation Area
properties.description:
Coolmunda Dam is located approximately 15km east of Inglewood. It is a popular dam for fishing and watersports. There are no vessel type restrictions on the dam. 

Accommodation is available at the Lake Coolmunda Caravan, Cabin and Holiday Park. 

Coolmunda Dam is stocked by the Lake Coolmunda Restocking Group Inc. 

The facilities at the dam include boat ramp, toilets, barbeques, picnic tables, swimming pool, tennis court and playground. Pets are welcome at the park. The Coolmunda Conservation Park has trails suitable for bush walking and mountain bike riding, and is a popular fishing spot.

The dam is stocked with golden perch, Murray cod and silver perch. In 2017/18, 99,659 golden perch, 15,000 silver perch and 500 Murray cod were stocked from SIPS permit sales. 

A total of 1,356,167 golden perch, 164,275 silver perch and 148,106 Murray cod have been stocked in Coolmunda Dam from SIPS.

properties.name: Coolibah Walk
properties.description:
The Coolibah Walk is located along both banks of the Barcoo River which borders Tambo on the northern side. 

The river with its many swimming holes and fishing spots has been and continues to be part of the Tambo way of life. The walk is well signposted and you will find waterholes which have played a significant part in Tambo’s history. 

For example ‘The Garden Hole’ once provided water for the Chinese Gardeners who kept the Tambo Community supplied with fresh fruit and veggies. 

Sand Bank was and still is a favourite fishing spot.

properties.name: The Bulloo River Walk
properties.description:
A stroll along Quilpie's Bulloo River Walk is a tranquil way to appreciate the native flora and fauna of the Bulloo River Catchment, Warrego Way and the Natural Sciences Loop. 
Signs, bearing information about the plant species, are located along the walk. 

The Bulloo River is an ideal spot to relax under a shady tree and birdwatch whilst the natural sounds of the bush. Keen birdwatchers are encouraged to identify as many bird species as they can. 

The Bulloo River is an ideal place to cast a fishing line and catch a Yellowbelly (Golden perch) or throw in a yabby pot and snare some delicious Yabbies (fresh water crayfish). You could have yourself one of the freshest feeds the Outback has to offer.

properties.name: Grays Bay
properties.description: One of the most picturesque bays in Queensland is Gray’s Bay - one of the few places on the East Coast where you can watch the sun set over the ocean.  It really is a treat, especially when the stand up paddleboarders are silhouetted against the darkening sky.

properties.name: Balgal Beach
properties.description: Balgal Beach forms part of the popular Northern Beaches district of Townsville North Queensland. Offering a superb sand beach and secure swimming in the stinger net from November to May, Balgal is ideal for a relaxing day by the ocean or a fun way to spend time with the whole family.

properties.name: Baldy Top Lookout
properties.description:
Baldy Top Lookout is a scenic lookout located on the Toompine Road, approximately 7 kilometres south of the town of Quilpie in Queensland, Australia. It is one of the most elevated points in South West Queensland and offers stunning panoramic views of the surrounding countryside, including the Carnarvon Ranges and the Warrego River.

The lookout is easily accessible by car and there is a short walking path that leads to the top of the hill. The lookout is also equipped with picnic tables and barbecue facilities, making it a great place to enjoy a meal or snack while taking in the views.

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Cloncurry
properties.description:
Uncover a piece of outback history at Discovery Parks – Cloncurry. More than just a base for exploring 'The Curry,' we're part of the region’s rich heritage. 

This is where Reverend John Flynn established the Royal Flying Doctor Service, changing outback communication forever with his pedal radio. Interested? 

The Mary Kathleen Memorial Park and Museum offers the full story, along with fascinating exhibits, from Burke’s iconic water bottle to an impressive collection of rocks and minerals. 

This isn’t just a quick stop—it’s an opportunity to immerse yourself in the heart of Australia's history at Discovery Parks – Cloncurry.

properties.name: Nindigully Pub
properties.description:
The Gully  is one of Queensland's oldest hotels. 
 
The pub license was issued in 1864 after operating as shearer's accommodation for the Nindigully Station. From the late 1800s the Nindigully Pub was a Cobb and Co coach change over station.

Today, the pub still stands in its original condition and position. Located on the banks of the Moonie River, the pub has become a favourite watering hole and camping spot amongst locals and travellers.

Nindigully offers hot showers and toilets at the historic pub free of charge. Plenty of camping and caravan space is available along the Moonie river. Patronage at the pub or donation for the upkeep of facilities is requested.

properties.name: Rainbow Beach
properties.description: Beach that has some limited facilities onsite

properties.name: Ellangowan Hotel
properties.description: Free camping behind pub, also free (donation) camping spot available across the road. Small walk to bbq and playground Liam

properties.name: Hidden Camp - Pie Creek
properties.description: Camping for rv's tents and camping trailers

properties.name: Clem Walton park
properties.description: Clem Walton Park has spacious camping on the Corella River, it is not far from the Corella Dam. Entry is via about 3km of winding dirt road off the Barkley Highway.

properties.name: Hotel Brandon
properties.description: Small but nice tidy park at the back of Hotel Brandon. Cheap meals.

properties.name: Widgee Bushmans Bar and Campdraft grounds
properties.description: Short term casual camping only. Cost at this time is $8 per adult per night, with power or $6 without, but limited number of power outlets, kids free. The Bushmans bar is open Friday and Saturday nights and serves excellent meals and has bar service from 4pm to late if enough patrons stay on. Some weekends feature live music on stage (you get  2 choices of music: country and western!). There are good hot showers, and septic flush toilets, 8 acres of grassed shady grounds. Please note the grounds are a community area for pony clubs and other events, so please check before setting up camp. Phone 0754840282 for details. Note this is all run by volunteers, so be respectful of their help and services. No bank card facilities, but the local shop has eftpos, petrol, diesel, good fast food, and general stores. Widgee is a small district 26km from Gympie, with bitumen road access to Kilkivan Wide Bay Hwy. Also check out the Widgee Bushmans Bar website for events.
properties.fees: $10 per adult per night, with power or $7 without

properties.name: Lake Mary Kathleen - Camping Area
properties.description: This scenic camping area with no facilities is located beside the lake. There is a fishing spot, a boat ramp and a few walking tracks. Caravans, big rigs and pets are not permitted here. This site is accessible by conventional vehicles, however in wet weather 4WD is recommended. Watch out for algae in the lake.

properties.name: Pomona Caravan Park
properties.description:
The Pomona Caravan Park is situated within the grounds of the Noosa AH&I Society's Showgrounds in Pomona, in the hinterland of Queensland's Sunshine Coast.

Pomona is the perfect place to base your exploration of this beautiful part of Australia. It a 32 km country drive (around 30 minutes) to the beaches and National Park at Noosa Heads, and around 65 km to Australia Zoo.

properties.name: Nanya Road Camping Area
properties.description: Gravel area at the entrance of a little sideroad off the highway. Some trees protect from roadnoise. Relatively quiet place with lots of gravel and grassy parking possibilities. No facilities, please take rubbish home.

properties.name: Glebe Weir Picnic and Camping Area
properties.description:
Glebe Weir camping area provides powered sites for vehicle based camping, caravans and camper trailers. Facilities include toilets, wood fireplace, boat ramp, picnic tables and shelter.

Local activiites include fishing, swimming, waterskiing and canoeing. You will need to bring your own drinking water and firewood. Camping fees can be paid at the self-registration station.  Advanced bookings are not available.

properties.name: Junction Parking Area
properties.description: Basic roadside rest area. Spacious and level area. Toilets and picnic tables are across the road. Except for trucks passing by it's a quiet place and also good for non-SC vehicles and there are not many around. Good place for a night.

properties.name: Cooktown RV Rest Area
properties.description:
The rest area is available for fully self contained vehicles that must have the following: 

Permanently fixed toilet, shower, washing and cooking facilities built within the vehicle.

Grey water and black water containment systems fixed within the body of the vehicle with fixed plumbing and fittings that enable discharge to a Dump Ezy point (open containers or buckets to collect grey or black water are not permitted under any circumstances).

As of 1 January 2024, the RV Rest Area will only be open from 1 June - 31 August each year. Outside of these dates, travellers are requested to stay at one of the local caravan parks.

The following conditions also apply:

- Use of the area is for a maximum of 3 nights 
- Use of generators is permitted 
- Dogs must be restrained at all times and must not cause a nuisance to neighbours or pedestrians. You must clean up after your dog
- Noise must be kept to a minimum after 9:00PM 
- Your donation is greatly appreciated and will help us maintain the RV Rest Area and make it available for other users

properties.name: Fred Drew Rest Area
properties.description:
While this spot can be noisy due to its proximity to the highway, it serves as an excellent base for exploring Innisfail and the surrounding area.

Although it is officially a 24-hour rest area, some longer-term campers appear to stay there. We stayed for a few days and felt secure enough to unhitch our van and go exploring.

With amenities like a playground, toilets, green grass, and a covered picnic shelter with BBQs, Fred Drew Rest Area is a handy stopover whether you're heading north or south along the Queensland coast.

Located 4 km north of Innisfail and 26 km south of Babinda in Far North Queensland, Fred Drew Rest Area is ideally situated for travellers.

properties.name: Thunderbird Park
properties.description:
Come for the day or stay and play at Australia's largest adventure playground, located between Brisbane and the Gold Coast in Tamborine Mountain. It is a place of constant surprises.



Our range of onsite adventure attractions make Thunderbird Park an exciting experience for every age group.
properties.fees: Unpowered sites from $32 - $52 per night. Powered and van sites $58 per night. Price inclusive of 2 guests. $10pp for additional guests. Kids under 5 are FOC.

properties.name: Greenpatch Campground
properties.description:
Open during the dry season ONLY (May-October), however this can vary due to local weather conditions.

Check with council before arrival to check its current opening dates.

The maximum length of stay is 72 hours (3 nights)

Users may not return to the same campground within 14 days

properties.name: Raglan Tavern
properties.description: Customers can enjoy a free overnight parking for SC only. There is also a motel operating from these premises.

properties.name: Utopia Cafe
properties.description: Information supplied by the Visitor Information Centre network helping provide tourist information across Australia

properties.name: Busy Bee Cafe
properties.description: Information supplied by the Visitor Information Centre network helping provide tourist information across Australia

properties.name: Dan's Diner
properties.description: Information supplied by the Visitor Information Centre network helping provide tourist information across Australia

properties.name: Aramac Freedom Park
properties.description:
Large campsite on the left hand side as you enter town. 

Costs $6/night with honesty box at gate as you enter. 

No toilets, but water available throughout. Some tables and chairs scattered throughout the park.

Communal fire place at rear of park

properties.name: Island View Caravan Park
properties.description:
Island View Caravan Park offer fantastic style accommodation for couples, families and groups holidaying in Australia’s beautiful Tropical Coast of Capricorn Queensland. Their guests can enjoy a range of quality self-contained holiday accommodation, van and camping sites , extensive family friendly facilities, kids’ activities, warm hospitality and a relaxed atmosphere.

Island View has a jumping pillow, a barbecue area called the NAJBA Bar - very modern with up-to-date amenities. Also now an Alfresco Area which can hold functions for up to approximately 80 people per function, with game table, a big screen television and two new pools (one adults only and one for the whole family).

properties.name: Discovery Parks - Mount Surprise
properties.description:
Escape to the stunning landscapes of North Queensland at Discovery Parks - Mount Surprise. Our family-friendly park offers a range of accommodation options, from powered and unpowered sites to comfortable cabins.

 Explore the unique natural wonders of the region, including Undara Lava Tubes and the stunning scenery of the Einasleigh Uplands. Enjoy campfires under the stars, relax by the pool, and experience the true spirit of Outback Queensland. Book your adventure today!

properties.name: Gregory River Free Camp
properties.description:
With clear, fresh and croc-free running water, this is outback bush camping at its finest! 

Be sure to plan a day trip into the Boodjamulla National Park while you’re here so you can experience kayaking and trekking around the stunning gorge.

properties.name: Montville Country Cabins
properties.description:
Montville Country Cabins
There are nine self-contained country cabins.  Six cabins are suitable for couples and three cabins are suitable for couples or families.  The family cabins are away from the couples cabins.  Every cabin has stunning views looking over the remnant ancient rainforest or our formal gardens and spring fed lake.

properties.name: High Valley Dawn Permaculture Farm
properties.description:
High Valley Dawn Permaculture Farm Tours are open to people of all ability/mobility levels.

There is onsite parking near the front gate of the market garden (the first stop in our Farm Tour) where people of all ability levels can disembark. The majority of the tour is carried out on grounds that are flat and accessible to people of all fitness levels, ability levels, as well as for people in wheelchairs and mobility scooters.

There are some sections of the tour that may be difficult for people in wheelchairs – such as in the Food Forest – however other options can be provided for those people while the main tour visits those areas. Please let us know in advance if you have special requirements in terms of mobility.

Assistance animals are welcome to come into the market garden and Food Forest areas, as long as they stay on a lead. There are parts of the garden that we do not walk on (such as garden beds) hence animals need to be kept on a lead at all times and guided to stay on the paths.

properties.name: Windmill Bay Camping Area
properties.description:
Campers and beach-lovers will score the best of both worlds! Nestled against 200m of sandy beach that fringes the Great Barrier Reef World Heritage Area(external link), this is your base for all beach, land and water activities in the park.

Stake a claim on the perfect, sheoak-shaded spot for you tent or high-clearance camper trailer in the open, grassy camping area. It can be windy so remember to put in extra pegs! Set out from here and enjoy the day four-wheel driving, boating, walking, fishing and playing.

At night, sit around your camp fire (bring your own off-ground container and milled timber) and listen to the waves gently rolling ashore.

Windmill Bay camping area is in Cape Palmerston National Park, 115km south-east of Mackay on the Central Queensland coast. You need a high clearance 4WD to get to the camping area.

The camping area is 12km from the southern boundary on the Cape Palmerston drive.

Turn off the Bruce Highway at Ilbilbie (76km south of Mackay and 157km north of Marlborough) and drive east towards Greenhill. Before Greenhill, turn left into Cape Palmerston Road. The park boundary is about 6km along this road.

Camping area features: shaded by she-oaks, Windmill Bay fronts a 200m sandy beach.

Location: 12km north from the park boundary.

Access: the camping area can be reached by high clearance 4WD only.

Number of sites: undefined. Maximum of 6 people per site.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car, camper trailers.

Camp site surface: sand.

Facilities: picnic tables, bush-style pit toilets. Visitors are encouraged to provide their own portable toilets.

Open fires: on-ground campfires prohibited. Above-ground fire containers permitted—bring your own clean, milled timber. Remove your fire container when you leave. Fuel stoves are recommended.

Generators: not allowed.

Essentials to bring: drinking water, food, rubbish bags, insect repellent, sun protection, first-aid kit and a reliable torch. Read more about before you visit.

properties.name: Cape Creek Camping Area
properties.description:
This sheltered camping area is a great home base from which to explore the park and surrounding waters.

Set up your tent or high-clearance camper trailer in this large and grassy area cradled between a sandy peninsula and the mouth of Cape Creek. Protected by prevailing winds and shaded by sheoaks, Cape Creek is an excellent base from which to explore the park.

Jump in your boat and explore the coastline and creeks. Catch your dinner and cook it over your camp fire (bring your own off-ground fire container and milled wood).

Keep your binoculars and cameras handy because the waters are known for the dugong and other marine life, and the beaches and trees are alive with birdlife.

Getting there and getting around Cape Creek camping area is in Cape Palmerston National Park, 115km south-east of Mackay on the Central Queensland coast. You need a high clearance 4WD to access the camping area.

The camping area is 15km from the southern boundary on the Cape Palmerston drive. Turn off the Bruce Highway at Ilbilbie (76km south of Mackay and 157km north of Marlborough) and drive east towards Greenhill. Before Greenhill, turn left into Cape Palmerston Road.

The park boundary is about 6km along this road.

Make sure you check the tide times before you drive on the beach as the tides vary up to 6m.

Cape Creek camping area is open 24 hours a day. Check-in to your camp after 2pm and check-out by 11am on the day of departure.

Camp sites are suitable for: tent camping beside your car, camper trailers.

Camp site surface: sand/grass.

Facilities: Toilets are not provided at Cape Creek, visitors are advised to bring their own portable toilets or to bury all faecal matter and toilet paper 15–20cm deep at least 100m from tracks, campsites and waterbodies.

Open fires: on-ground campfires prohibited. Above-ground fire containers permitted—bring your own clean, milled timber. Remove your fire container when you leave. Fuel stoves are recommended.

Generators: not allowed.

Accessible by 4WD and boat.

properties.name: Forrest Beach RV Park
properties.description:
RV self contained vehicles only at a camp walking distance to the beach. Toilets, showers and dump point. 

Pay $15 per night to takeaway shop. 

Receipts checked by shire 5pm. 

Flat campground and great fish n chips shop.

properties.name: Heinemanns Country Bakery
properties.description:
Heinemann's Country Bakery offers mouth-watering treats, pies, breakfast, lunch and great coffee coupled with good country service and a smile.

This is the home of one of Australia's famous meat pies!

properties.name: Carrollee Hotel
properties.description: Information supplied by the Visitor Information Centre network helping provide tourist information across Australia

properties.name: Rodborough Park
properties.description:
Nice little Playground with a big grassy area next to a small river on the side of the Road. Bit noisy at night, camping in a tent possible. Lots of families in the morning with kids so sleeping is over at around 9am. 

Has a public rubbish bin and space for around 12 vehicles.

properties.name: Mount Beerburrum and Glasshouse Mountains Walk
properties.description:
The Mount Beerburrum and Glasshouse Mountains walk is a challenging but rewarding hike that takes you to the summit of Mount Beerburrum and offers stunning views of the surrounding Glasshouse Mountains and Sunshine Coast.

The walk begins at the Mount Beerburrum car park and follows a steep, paved track to the summit. The track is approximately 700 meters long and takes around 30 minutes to climb. 

The summit of Mount Beerburrum offers 360-degree views of the surrounding area, including the Glasshouse Mountains, Moreton Island, and the Brisbane skyline.

properties.name: Lawgi Heritage Park & Farm Stay
properties.description:
Free camp below heritage museum (donations welcome).  

Toilets and showers available.

Sloping site great views and welcoming owners that are happy to introduce you to the animals while marking use of the camp kitchen wonderful historic museum to explore a trip down memory lane

properties.name: Normanton River Free Camp
properties.description:
A brilliant spot to pull up for a day or two, with free camping permits issued by the Library and Visitor Information Centre. Watching the flow of the river and flicking a few lures around from the bridge next to the sites made this spot worthy of a mention. 

- Free camp for 48 hours max
- Must be self contained

properties.name: Turtle Sands
properties.description:
Turtle Sands is Australia’s newest turtle see and stay experience in Mon Repos, near Bundaberg. Tucked safely behind the dunes of a globally significant turtle conservation beach, Turtle Sands is the only place on the mainland of Australia where you stay, play and rest within meters of where these magnificent marine turtles nest and hatch.

Turtle Sands connects guests to a secluded beach, modern facilities and nearby nature reserves through a network of walking tracks. A central pool and social area with surrounding gardens acts as a hub for connection and play. Designed with a way for everyone to stay, the property offers villas, studios, glamping tents, accessible accommodation options and powered caravan and camp sites.

properties.name: Eli Creek
properties.description:
Eli Creek, the largest creek on the eastern beach of Fraser Island, pours up to four million litres of clear, fresh water into the ocean every hour. 

Eli Creek is a popular picnic and swimming spot, with a boardwalk that follows the creek inland through banksia and pandanus.  

Swimming or floating down the swiftly flowing water is a local favourite past time.

properties.name: Coorberrie Park Wildlife Sanctuary
properties.description:
Visit Cooberrie Park and support the vital work this wildlife sanctuary does for the rescued wildlife from Central Queensland.
Cooberrie Park began as a botanical garden more than 100 years ago. In 1973 rescued wildlife started to arrive and each year more than 100 sick, injured and orphaned wildlife is rehabilitated and released back to the wild.

Cooberrie Park also takes care of wildlife long term which is unable to be released back to the wild, they then become ambassadors for their species as they are either too injured to back to the wild or were victims of the illegal pet trade. They are transferred from Government departments and the RSPCA.

Cooberrie Park also has a successful breeding program for Koalas and Cassowaries. 

Just by visiting you are supporting the wildlife of Central Queensland.

properties.name: Pandanus Tourist Park
properties.description: This caravan park in Port Douglas has a range of accommodation styles: fully self-contained cabins, self contained units, basic park cabins. PANDANUS TOURIST PARK has powered or unpowered camping sites for caravans, trailers & tents with refurbished amenities and great facilities.

properties.name: Palm Cove
properties.description: Palm Cove is a tiny enclave of fine dining, luxury resorts & spectacular pools beside a palm fringed beach & a great launch pad from which to explore TNQ.

properties.name: Cooktown Holiday Park
properties.description: Now is the time to visit Cooktown in all its glory. Everywhere is lush and green. Take in some of the breathtaking scenery.

properties.name: Brisbane Holiday Village
properties.description:
Queensland's best Holiday Park!

Award-winning Brisbane Holiday Village is the ideal choice for your next stay when visiting Brisbane. Whether it is for business, holiday or relocating, our extensive quality cabins cater to all budgets. We offer both powered and unpowered sites along with spacious, self-contained cabins.

Our landscaped gardens make it the perfect location to park a caravan and take in the surroundings..

The Village is 15 minute drive south of Brisbane City and is close to sporting venues, shopping, hospitals and restaurants. There is easy access to both the Gateway Motorway and Pacific Highway with public transport facilities at the Village's entrance. Brisbane Holiday Village is a popular destination for those visiting Brisbane to see friends, family, sporting or cultural events as well as attending medical treatment or business trips.

Set on 33 landscaped acres, Brisbane Holiday Village features a large swimming lagoon, shallow children's lagoon with water fountains, 18 hole mini-golf course, multi-purpose sports field, 350m bike track, children's playground area, full size tennis court, outdoor table tennis, undercover barbecue area , daily lorikeet feeding, guest amenities and laundries, restaurant and convenience store. The restaurant is open seven days and offers affordable meals for families and can cater for large groups.

properties.name: Linville Village Free Camp
properties.description:
The old Linville Train station is a beautiful free campsite with many grassy and level sites. Toilets are clean and have toilet paper, soap and lights. 

Rubbish bins and fire places are available. 

Opposite the road there is a general store and a restaurant and a callbox. 

There is no cell reception in the area.

properties.name: Routh Creek Camping
properties.description: Small campsite right next to the river. Coming from the E, turn right before the bridge and follow the little downwards way. Unlike most places along the highway, this is more hidden from the road, and has less road noises. No facilities. Depending on how busy it is, suitable for all kinds of vehicles, but road a little bumpy. Check before driving down.

properties.name: Perkins Road
properties.description: Grassy area along the road, a little further up the road after roadhouse on your right hand side. Less noisy than the roadhouse, but without facilities. SC only.
